report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 53-year-old, left-handed woman with a history of brain tumor resection one year ago. She presents with complaints of severe headache and seizures with loss of consciousness (tonic-clonic seizures).  Diabetes mellitus, arthritis, and blood clot in the left leg.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Glucophage, Zoloft, and calcium.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is a 7 Hz, 30 to 60 V dominant rhythm.  Intermittent bilateral as well as unilateral right focal slowing is characterized by frontal theta and delta.  There is a right frontal breech demonstrated by increased beta and increased amplitude of theta.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there are more prominent bursts of frontal slowing and a breech on the right.  Although the EEG is abnormal, it is nearly symmetric and well organized at times. Hyperventilation produces right frontal delta.  Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.  There is no EEG change at the time of twitching.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent bilateral as well as unilateral focal slowing characterized by frontal theta or delta.
Right frontal breech with increased beta and increased amplitude of the delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing suggests an underlying structural problem most likely affecting both frontal hemispheres. No sharp waves could be identified. A follow-up EEG during deeper stages of sleep may be useful in identifying focal epileptiform activity given the breech rhythm.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Intermittent bilateral as well as unilateral focal slowing characterized by frontal theta or delta. Right frontal breech with increased beta and increased amplitude of the delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 56-year-old woman with meningioma in 2002, now with infrequent complex partial seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Lamictal, Glucophage, Zoloft, calcium, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm of 30 uV with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is an increase in rhythmic theta followed by one or two vertex waves.  There is a suggestion of a breach rhythm in drowsiness, which is higher amplitude theta in the frontal regions.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in the amplitude and a small amount of rhythmic slowing.  Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.
At the close of the record, there is a more subtle amplitude asymmetry in the left frontal region, but clear focal slowing and no epileptiform features.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG at the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In this record, the breach rhythm in the frontal region can be seen.  There is no epileptiform activity and no clear focal slowing.  This is similar to a more recent recording.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG at the limits of normal.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 49-year-old male with seizures, alcohol abuse, hypertension, cardiomyopathy, cirrhosis and hemiparesis.  Dilantin level is zero.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Ativan, and thiamin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed.  The patient is described as restless and frequently moving.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a posterior dominant rhythm of approximately 10 Hz, 30 to 50 V and a modest amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The patient is noted to be restless throughout. Brief drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background beta.
HR:  118 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If characterization of this patient’s epileptiform activity is important, a follow-up study capturing deeper stages of sleep may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old male with alcohol abuse, epilepsy, stroke in 1997, and cardiomyopathy.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Heparin, and Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The vast majority of the record is drowsy with a mixture of theta and beta frequency activity.  In this state, there is rare, subtle left frontotemporal slowing.  Sometimes this is picked up bilaterally in the frontal regions.  On occasion, this is associated with a discrete, left frontotemporal sharp wave maximum at F7 and T1, sometimes appearing as a couplet.  Features of deeper stages of sleep include vertex waves and spindles.  As the patient reaches stage II sleep, the EEG becomes more symmetric and more synchronous.  There are rare left anterior temporal sharp waves in stage II sleep.  These discrete discharges persist throughout the light sleep record.  In maximal wakefulness, the patient arouses and the EEG becomes well organized, symmetric with a low voltage, symmetric reactive 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of frontocentral beta activity.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left frontotemporal sharp and slow wave or discrete spike and slow wave activity.
Subtle left frontotemporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.  Correlation with this patient’s imaging may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left frontotemporal sharp and slow wave or discrete spike and slow wave activity. Subtle left frontotemporal focal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old male with epilepsy, alcohol abuse, stroke, and hypertension who presented to Episcopal with recurrent seizures requiring Ativan and Dilantin.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record in a patient who is somewhat uncooperative.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates wakefulness and drowsiness.  There are brief portions of the record when the patient has his eyes opened with a low voltage beta frequency pattern.  Other portions of the record demonstrate a pattern rich in alpha and theta frequency activity, with a posterior dominant rhythm of approximately 8 Hz.  There is some head rocking artifact as the study continues.

HR:  __ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild slowing of the background rhythm to 8 Hz.
Excess background beta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were seen in this record.  Comparison with this patient’s previous EEGs would be helpful in terms of the search for epileptiform activity.  The mild background slowing may be due to a postictal state or medication effect.  The excess beta is likely due to the benzodiazepine exposure.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Mild slowing of the background rhythm to 8 Hz. Excess background beta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: TI1is is a 51-year-old  male with epilepsy  and alcohol abuse who presents after a generalized  breakthrough seizure.  The patient is non-compliant with his medications.   Prior stroke with residual left-sided weakness.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Topamax, and Librium.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed  at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement  with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION  OF  THE  RECORD:  As  the  tracing  opens,  the   background  EEG  is  mildly disorganized and slow with excessive amounts of theta.  There is a fair amount of frontocentral beta activity.  Occasional left temporal spike and slow waves are seen, as well as occasional right temporal and frontocentral sharp waves that sometimes appear as brief trains. Spike and wave complexes occur independently  from  either  side.    There  is  occasional  mil d  focal  left  temporal  slowing.    Photic stimulation elicits a discrete driving response. Stages of sleep are not achieved.
HR: 84BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.   Independent temporal sharp waves, which are more frequent on the right than the left hemisphere.
2.   Mild generalized and disorganized background.
3.   Occasional slowing from the left hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for this patient 's epilepsy. In comparison  to  previous  EEGs,  this  was  the  second  record  out  of  eight  that  showed  focal epileptiform discharges.  The amount of discharges is increased compared to the record from January
2004.   At this point, it is not clear whether this EEG picture signifies a progression  of the patient's seizure disorder or if it is an interictal phenomenon.   Correlation with neuroimaging  studies may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.   Independent temporal sharp waves, which are more frequent on the right than the left hemisphere. 2.   Mild generalized and disorganized background. 3.   Occasional slowing from the left hemisphere.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old  male with a right frontal skull  defect, epilepsy,  hypertension,   stroke,   hepatitis,   alcohol   abuse   with   alcohol   withdrawal associated severe paranoia
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Ativan, and Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital  video EEG is performed in the lab using  standard  10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was attempted and photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE  RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized, low voltage, with generous low voltage beta activity and a posterior dominant rhythm of approximately 9 Hz.  Hyperventilation is attempted early on in the record, but the patient is either  not cooperative or is excessively drowsy.   Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements and an increase in background beta.   Vertex waves are seen in stage I sleep.   Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is initially asleep, but does elicit a brief driving response.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this
record.  There is a generous amount of beta  frequency activity, which is to be anticipated with benzodiazepine use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 52-year-old, right-handed male with epilepsy, seizure-free for 1 month.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow with a 5 to 6 Hz posterior dominant rhythm in a background with a small amount of excess theta.  Intermittently, in wakefulness and drowsiness, there is bit more arrhythmic delta activity on the left compared to the right.  Hyperventilation seems to accentuate this asymmetry.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the asymmetry is somewhat less prominent.  Other features of drowsiness include rhythmic background slowing with an increase in background beta.   Snore artifact is seen and is followed by arousals.
Photic stimulation produces LAMBDA waves, but no definite driving.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing and disorganization.
Occasional focal slowing on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  In this individual with a right frontal skull defect, one might anticipate accentuation of beta in that region and perhaps easier identification of sharp waves. No previous EEGs were available for comparison.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to Background slowing and disorganization. Occasional focal slowing on the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old male with alcohol abuse, stroke, epilepsy, and temporal abnormalities admitted with alcohol-withdrawal seizure
MEDICATIONS: Klonopin, Topamax, Keppra, Serax,
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. The patient had previously been experiencing severe benzodiazepine withdrawal on July 3. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is awake throughout much of the record.  The background EEG is rich in beta frequency activity and there is also excess background theta.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is some underlying rhythmic temporal slowing most prominently seen from the left with some spread into the frontocentral regions.  There is prominent lateral rectus eye artifact noted in the awake and drowsy record.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving at faster flash frequencies.  There is perhaps a single underlying right temporal sharp wave.
HR:  __ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
A handful of subtle temporal abnormalities left and right, but no definite spikes or sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  The features described above are similar to previous EEGs, some of which have demonstrated significant left temporal features, others which have not consistently identified left temporal abnormalities.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. A handful of subtle temporal abnormalities left and right, but no definite spikes or sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 40-year-old, left-handed woman with epilepsy since childhood with increasing headaches, nausea, vomiting, and accelerating seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Heparin, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record with hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In the initial portions of the record, there is a marked intrahemispheric asymmetry.  From the left hemisphere, there is a 9.5 Hz, 35 V posterior dominant rhythm.  This is somewhat disrupted on the right, and the right hemisphere demonstrates disruption of faster frequency activity with arrhythmic delta activity particularly from the centrotemporal regions and T2 sharp and slow wave or spike and slow wave complexes. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and seems to accentuate this pattern. As the post-hyperventilation pattern resolves, the focal slowing becomes somewhat less prominent and the intrahemispheric asymmetry slightly less marked.  Later on, as the patient drifts into stage I and stage II sleep, there is again disruption of faster frequency activity particularly from the right frontal regions. Symmetric vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are identified in stage II sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits brief driving bilaterally at faster flash frequencies.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing from the right hemisphere characterized by disruption of faster frequency activity as well as focal delta and theta activity maximum in the temporal regions.
T2 spike and slow wave complexes, which are overall high amplitude.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This record was compared to this patient’s five previous EEGs.  Some have demonstrated epileptiform activity on the right or left temporal regions, as well as others with bitemporal activity.  The activity in this record is much more marked on the right.  Correlation with imaging may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Focal slowing from the right hemisphere characterized by disruption of faster frequency activity as well as focal delta and theta activity maximum in the temporal regions. T2 spike and slow wave complexes, which are overall high amplitude.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 28-year-old male with epilepsy since his teens, high functioning mentally handicapped young adult. Last tonic-clonic seizure was in 1993, but had a small seizure last month characterized by shaking of hands and clumsiness.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 60 V posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In this sharply contoured background, there are occasional left anterior temporal sharp and slow wave complexes with associated focal slowing.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing occasional slowing from the temporal regions independently or bilaterally.  Following this, the patient becomes drowsy.  POSTS are seen in early stage I sleep.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to:
1.	Left temporal sharp waves with suspicious sharply contoured slowing from the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In the sharply contoured background, consideration for a study with more extensive sleep may be helpful to further delineate epileptiform activity from the background.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to 1.Left temporal sharp waves with suspicious sharply contoured slowing from the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 38-year-old female with epilepsy. No other details are known and no seizure history is known.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were attempted.  The patient spoke no English and had no caregiver to help translate. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial portions of the record are well-organized with a 9.25 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In the initial portions of the record, the patient is a bit drowsy and hyperventilation is attempted.  There are bursts seen in this portion of the record in the temporal regions.  There are irregular bursts, which appear in the left or right temporal regions, sometimes a bit more on one side than the other or starting on the left and going to right or vice versa.  With the use of the T1-T2 electrodes, the activity appears to be maximum at T1 and there is an underlying sharp wave at T1-T3.  This becomes more prominent in the later HV recording. In these bursts, there are also T2 sharp waves and a sharply contoured background.  Following hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, there are additional sharp waves again seen at T1.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in the irregular temporal theta and the occasional sharp waves.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Irregular temporal slowing with an unusual field of spread often involving both temporal regions but asynchronous.
Left greater than right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.  If further characterization of this patient’s epilepsy is needed, an additional recording capturing sleep or one of her seizures would be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Irregular temporal slowing with an unusual field of spread often involving both temporal regions but asynchronous. Left greater than right temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old woman with possible seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Ambien, Wellbutrin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10.4 Hz, 50 to 60 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by anterior spread of the alpha rhythm followed by attenuation of the alpha with a handful of vertex waves.  In the transition to sleep, there are some bursts of mixed rhythmic theta and delta, which are somewhat irregular but not epileptiform in nature.  An identical 3-second burst is seen at the close of hyperventilation.
At the close of the record, wicket activity is identified in the transition to and from sleep, which is somewhat asymmetric, a little bit more prominent on the left than the right.
HR:  68 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The somewhat unusual response in hyperventilation and seen with a paroxysmal, somewhat irregular burst in HV and on one occasion in drowsiness, is not epileptogenic in nature and is of unclear clinical significance.  The asymmetric wicket described above is a normal finding.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 46-year-old gentleman who presents with left wrist pain and syncope, loss of consciousness with urine incontinence. History includes diabetes, hypertension, chronic renal insufficiency, and gout.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, insulin, and _______ medicine.  Check tech sheet
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is fairly organized with low voltage.  There is a 9 Hz, 15 V posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of frontocentral beta activity.  Frequent vertex waves, spindles, and K complexes were identified.  The patient was awakened by his snoring, but he rapidly went back to stage II sleep.  Moderate muscle activity is seen with snoring.  Photic stimulation elicited mild driving.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Normal EEG recording does not exclude the possibility of seizures or epilepsy. If clinically indicated, a repeat EEG recording may increase the chances of reviewing the epileptiform discharges.  The patient was found to have excessive snoring, which interrupted his sleeping.  Consider evaluating  obstructive sleep apnea by polysomnogram.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 55-year-old male with open heart transplant on July 21, 2003 for CHF who presented with encephalopathy.  He also had a PCA-type infarct.
MEDICATIONS: Cyclosporine recently started, Prednisone, _________, insulin, and Soma(?).
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, a posterior dominant rhythm is seen of 6 Hz, 30 V.  The overall background is diffusely slow with excess theta.  No epileptiform activity is seen during this EEG tracing.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Diffuse slow excess background theta.
Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG demonstrates a non-specific pattern.  Consideration should be given to a toxic or metabolic cause or postictal state.  This study was inconsistent with any definite pattern of metabolic encephalopathy.  No epileptiform activity was identified in this recording.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Diffuse slow excess background theta. Slowing of the alpha rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 55-year-old male with ischemic cardiomyopathy, sepsis, fluid overload, three convulsions, now lethargic, pacemaker, atrial fibrillation, hypothyroidism.
MEDICATIONS: Antibiotics, multiple cardiac medications, Prednisone.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is lethargic, but answers questions.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: This bedside portable EEG is relatively low voltage.  The patient is lethargic and there is a fair amount of muscle artifact.  There is a suggestion of a posterior dominant rhythm of 7.5 Hz, 15 V in a background that is low voltage with beta and small quantities of low voltage theta.  When the patient is awake and opening and closing his eyes, the alpha rhythm is a bit more prominent.  As the recording continues, the patient is increasingly alert.  The background shows improved organization and the mild slowing described above is decreasing.
HR:  104 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to:
1.	Mild background slowing, which is actually improving by the close of the record.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: Despite the history of three, acute tonic-clonic seizures, there were no focal features and no epileptiform abnormalities were identified. The gradual improvement over time may be part of the improvement from a postictal state.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to 1.Mild background slowing, which is actually improving by the close of the record.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 56-year-old gentleman with a heart transplant, right-hemispheric stroke, convulsion 08/03, memory impairment, and metabolic encephalopathy.
MEDICATIONS: Gengraf, Cellcept, Pepcid, Hydralazine, Cardura, Synthroid, Pravachol, calcium, Mycelex, Procrit, Prednisone, and vitamins.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed, but photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is low voltage.  There is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm, which demonstrates a somewhat more generous field of spread in the right hemisphere compared to the left.  There are no other significant asymmetries.  The patient is frequently drowsy with intermittent rhythmic slowing followed by arousals.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a subject of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no focal or epileptiform features seen in this record.  The patient does appear to be somewhat drowsy and intermittently starts to fall off to sleep and then has spontaneous arousals.  Consideration for a disorder with initiation or maintenance of sleep would be possible, as would review of the actual recording conditions as a noisy or uncomfortable environment could produce the same pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a subject of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 59-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 19, last seizure 2/03.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  There are no previous EEGs available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is an 8 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The patient is intermittently drowsy with slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm and rhythmic background theta.  Deeper stages of sleep are not identified.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are seen in this record.  To further characterize this patient’s epilepsy, a follow-up study capturing deeper stages of sleep could be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 56-year-old, right-handed woman with double vision, ataxia, headaches, prior pontine stroke, MI, DM, HTN, and asthma.
MEDICATIONS: ???
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 25 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There are intermittent portions of the record with focal slowing from the left temporal region characterized by disruption of faster frequency activity and somewhat irregular theta and mixed delta.  On other occasions, there is more isolated, rhythmic 4 Hz activity again maximum in the left temporal region.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is attenuation in the alpha rhythm and the same bursts are identified.  At times, these are somewhat sharply contoured.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Rare, arrhythmic focal slowing from the left temporal region.
Somewhat more prominent, rhythmic 4 Hz activity in the left temporal region.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite epileptiform features were identified in this record.  However, if epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow-up study, in the lab capturing deeper stage of sleep may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Rare, arrhythmic focal slowing from the left temporal region. Somewhat more prominent, rhythmic 4 Hz activity in the left temporal region.

report:

report:
History:	67 year old female with history of stroke and episodic facial twitching, now resolved
for follow up EEG.
Medications:	NONE
Sedation:	None
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes, awake, drowsy, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow
waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.
There is intermittent focal slowing noted over the left hemisphere, fronto-temporal region.  No
epileptiform discharges are present.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces a modest, symmetric photic
driving response.
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, intermittent, left frontotemporal
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy due to intermittent left frontotemporal focal
slowing. No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically
indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information.  Focal slowing
may indicate a structural brain lesion.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy due to intermittent left frontotemporal focal
slowing. No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically
indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information.  Focal slowing
may indicate a structural brain lesion

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 46-year-old male with a history of epilepsy since birth, seizure-free until three years ago when he began to have symptoms.  The patient reports a warm feeling in his head then loss of sight, shaking and confusion, but no loss of consciousness.  He remains upright, but may have to grab onto something.  History of chronic pain syndromes, acid reflux, hepatitis C, depression, and other medical problems including C-spine disease.
MEDICATIONS: Prevacid, Zyprexa, Benztropine, and amitriptyline.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is mainly a drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is drowsy throughout much of the record.  There is a low voltage, 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage beta.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is an increase in theta.  There is intermittent, irregular theta activity in the left temporal regions, left greater than right, with a subtle, sharply contoured slowing seen in the same region.  On rare occasions, there is some bitemporal slowing with some sharply contoured activity on the right. Features of stage II sleep include vertex waves and spindles.
Photic stimulation produces a minimal bilateral driving response.  The patient was drowsy through photic.  Hyperventilation is performed with poor effort.  The temporal features are identified in hyperventilation, which is almost equivalent to a drowsy state for this individual.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to:
1.	Irregular, sharply contoured temporal theta, left greater than right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No spike and slow wave or definitive sharp and slow wave discharges were seen in this record.  To further characterize this patient’s epilepsy, an additional recording may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to 1.Irregular, sharply contoured temporal theta, left greater than right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 49-year-old male, evaluated for alcohol withdrawal.
MEDICATIONS: 	Elavil, Neurontin, Depakote, Thiamine, Folic Acid
INTRODUCTION: 		Digital video EEG performed in the lab with a standard 10-20 system with electrode placement and one lead of EKG channel. 	This is an awake and drowsy record.	 The EEG also is performed under photo stimulation, and the EEG is recorded five days after his admission.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	In wakefulness there is an 8 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.	The background includes excess theta.	There is asymmetric muscle artifact.	Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements and an increase in delta. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: 	Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are identified. These features are nonspecific and can be seen in a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function due to many causes.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to 1. Mild background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman with epilepsy, seizure-free for nearly two years.  Previous EEGs demonstrated generalized epileptiform activity and generalized spike and slow wave activity in 1997.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The major abnormality in this record are bursts of frontally predominant, well formed, high amplitude 3.5 to 5 Hz spike and slow wave activity.  A typical burst duration is three seconds, but bursts can be seen that are longer, up to 5 seconds including some that have some theta.  In addition, there are rare, subtle frontal  spike and wave complexes, a handful of which are maximum in the right frontal region or the left and which appears as a couplet with first one in the left and the second in the right or vice versa.  The epileptiform activity is clearly accentuated in hyperventilation and in early drowsiness.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits a photoparoxysmal response with brief bursts of high amplitude frontally predominant 4 to 6 Hz spike and slow wave activity.  None of the bursts last the duration of the stimulus and in one occasion the burst is seen following HV.  There is a single burst of 5 Hz spike and slow wave activity immediately following hyperventilation.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Generalized, 3-6 Hz spike and slow wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a generalized mechanism for epilepsy.  These results are similar to previous records.  The presence of occasional frontal isolated spikes can be seen in an inherited generalized mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Generalized, 3-6 Hz spike and slow wave activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 25-year-old, left-handed woman with a prolonged period of seizure-free status with previous generalized spike and slow wave epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and drowsy record. No clinical seizures were recorded.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. The major abnormality in this record is a total of seven generalized spike and slow wave complexes, most of which are 5 Hz, but occasionally slightly slower or faster. Typical bursts are four seconds in duration, but there is a triplet of three bursts lasting a total of eight seconds. There is only a single, isolated frontal spike and slow wave complex, although there is a current burst. This generalized epileptiform activity occurs in wakefulness, seems to be elicited slightly in hyperventilation, perhaps elicited by photic stimulation, although it is clearly present in the background. Drowsiness may also be a precipitating factor. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
HR: 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Five to six hertz generalized spike and slow wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is essentially identical to the previous 2003 study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Five to six hertz generalized spike and slow wave activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 27-year-old woman with epilepsy starting in 1997, seizure-free since 2000.
MEDICATIONS: Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is a11 awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, symmetric, reactive posterior dominant rhythm. Central MU is identified, but testing is not performed to confirm this. Features of drowsiness include an increase in background beta, as well as anterior spread of the alpha rhythm. On rare occasions, there is a small amount of rhythmic, mid-temporal theta of drowsiness. Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits a frontally predominant, high amplitude, 5 and 13 Hz photoparoxysmal response of short duration, lasting less than three seconds without clinical signs.
HR: 70BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frontally predominant spike a11d wave activity of 3 to 6 Hz.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The photoparoxysmal response described above can be seen in inherited epilepsies. It was elicited at the 5 Hz stimuli at the onset of the flash stimulus. No clinical seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Frontally predominant spike a11d wave activity of 3 to 6 Hz.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 27-year-old left-handed woman with childhood epilepsy. The patient stopped topiramate earlier in 2007 and had a seizure in October 2007.
MEDICATIONS: Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 10 Hz symmetric reactive posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Weakness observed. The patient is drowsy throughout most of the record with background theta. Epileptiform is elicited in hyperventilation, drowsiness, and photic stimulation. The vast majority of this activity is rhythmic, frontally predominant, symmetric, a 2-7 Hz spike and wave activity. It is clearly accentuated by photic stimulation. On rare occasions an occipitally predominant 7 Hz spike and wave complexes are also observed. Duration of the spike and wave bursts are typically 2 seconds, but some are as long as 4 seconds. Photic stimulation also elicits driving.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized high amplitude spike and wave activity and poly spikes
2. Wave activity reaching 7 Hz.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing differs from previous in that in addition to frontally predominant spike and wave activity there was also on 1 occasion occipitally predominant spike and wave activity. Aside from this these studies are similar to this patient's many previous
studies dating to 2003. The activation with hyperventilation and photic stimulation suggests an inherited mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized high amplitude spike and wave activity and poly spikes
2. Wave activity reaching 7 Hz.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 49-year-old woman with adult onset epilepsy, complex partial seizures sometimes with an aura of a funny nasal feeling.
MEDICATIONS: Lamictal and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. In wakefulness, on rare occasions, there is a small amount of discrete beta activity from the right temporal region.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and again produces a small amount of discrete, rhythmic theta activity.  Some of this is identified in the posterior regions on the right and measures at 6 Hz.    As hyperventilation continues, there are one or two bursts of shifting arrhythmic delta activity from the temporal regions.  Following hyperventilation, there is some EKG artifact in the right temporal region.  Despite this, there is subtle, discrete right temporal slowing and a handful of tiny, discrete right temporal sharp waves, which can be differentiated from the patient’s EKG and are identified in quiet wakefulness.
Photic stimulation elicits brief driving.  At the close of the record, just following hyperventilation, intermittent bursts of background slowing with vertex waves and K complexes are identified followed by arousals, supportive of stage II sleep.
HR:  __ BPM. Check tech sheet
IMPRESSION: Subtle, but abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Right temporal focal slowing and small discrete sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The epileptiform features in this record are less prominent than those seen a year ago. With the subtle focal slowing and the discrete sharp waves, a partial mechanism for epilepsy rather than a normal variant would be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Subtle, but abnormal EEG due to 1.Right temporal focal slowing and small discrete sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old woman with epilepsy, admitted for recurrent seizures associated with aspiration pneumonia.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Zithromax, Zantac.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm, higher amplitude on the right compared to the left.  In hyperventilation and early drowsiness, there is subtle focal slowing from the right mid-temporal region with rare, discreet T2/T4 sharp waves as well as a single sharp wave from the left. There are isolated, rhythmic bursts of 2 to 3 Hz activity, again maximum in the right temporal region.  There is also EKG artifact picked up in the same electrodes.  This can be differentiated from the focal slowing or epileptiform activity. Vertex waves and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  The patient is observed to be in stage II sleep during photic stimulation.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Rare, subtle right temporal focal slowing.
Rare temporal sharp waves, right greater than left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.  The features are on the right are similar to previous studies, and the single left temporal sharp has not previously been identified.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Rare, subtle right temporal focal slowing. Rare temporal sharp waves, right greater than left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 53-year-old male with aggressive, widely metastatic lung cancer, bilateral cerebral metastases, and cognitive impairment.
MEDICATIONS: Decadron and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient has a previous right parietal craniotomy. This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is medium amplitude, well organized with a 10.5 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal awake EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If an EEG with sleep, hyperventilation or photic stimulation is desired, a repeat study in the lab may be appropriate.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 54-year-old male with metastatic lung cancer.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and insulin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The awake background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  The most striking abnormality in this record is a high amplitude spike and slow wave, poly spike and slow wave complex identified from the right hemisphere with a generous field of spread including C4, P4, and T4.  The focal spiking may be intermittent, periodic, or occur in transient clusters.  When the spiking stops, the posterior dominant rhythm on the right is well defined and there are portions of the record where it is defined bilaterally.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the epileptiform activity becomes increasingly periodic and the EEG develops a small degree of discontinuity in sleep around the epileptiform activity.
Photic stimulation elicits primarily a photoelectric effect, but there is a suggestion of a driving response underneath that.
HR:  118 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal epileptiform activity from the right hemisphere with a relatively generous field of spread including the parietal, central, and posterior temporal regions.
Associated focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No seizures were recorded.  This EEG supports a structural abnormality as well as a partial localization method for seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Focal epileptiform activity from the right hemisphere with a relatively generous field of spread including the parietal, central, and posterior temporal regions. Associated focal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 18-year-old male with a learning disability, childhood epilepsy with a breakthrough seizure.  Most recent seizure was not witnessed.  The patient was found on the floor with a bloody nose and tonic-clonic activity.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is significant EKG artifact in the background.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing a small amount of background slowing. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in the amplitude of the background, as well as a small increase in background theta.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  114 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  Comparison with this patient’s childhood EEGs may be helpful in terms of his recent seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:

report:
History:	29 year old male with a history of seizures. Last seizure in 2013.  This is a follow up
Medications:	Tegretol, Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  The AP gradient is weak.  Excess diffuse admixed 50-75 uV, 5-
7Hz activity is present throughout the recording.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm
attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild
Disorganization, mild
No stage 2 sleep
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 23-minute EEG due to mild background slowing and
disorganization. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild diffuse cerebral
dysfunction.  No epileptiform discharges are present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If
clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 23-minute EEG due to mild background slowing and
disorganization. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild diffuse cerebral
dysfunction.  No epileptiform discharges are present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If
clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information

report:

Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic central theta, as well as anterior spread of the alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation produces an increase in the amplitude of the background. report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 17-year-old male with a history of generalized epilepsy, previous history of spike and slow wave activity, last seizure sometime this past summer.  No warning and no postictal drowsiness.  Seizures have been described like “waking up from a dream.”
MEDICATIONS: Topamax.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10.5 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and occasional posterior slow waves of youth. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.  Hyperventilation is performed with fair effort and does not activate the record.
The major abnormality in this tracing is a subtle finding and includes very discrete bursts of paroxysmal, sharp and slow complexes of approximately 4 to 5 Hz occurring as couplets.  There are also some brief paroxysmal bursts of slowing without a definitive sharp and slow wave complex.  These appear to be generalized and unfortunately seem to be contaminated by some eye artifact, which follows them.   No clinical correlates are noted.
HR:  __ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Subtle but clearly present paroxysmal 4 to 5 Hz spike and slow wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to the reports of previous EEGs, this EEG shows less in the way of epileptiform activity.  The subtleties of this activity may be part of the maturational changes for this teenager.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Subtle but clearly present paroxysmal 4 to 5 Hz spike and slow wave activity.

report:

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to,

report:

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, ASA, Enalapril, Cozaar, Norvasc, Carvedilol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake and asleep record with photic stimulation done.

In addition, there is an interhemispheric asymmetry with higher amplitude on the left, a digital focal slowing on the left, with sharply contoured slowing on the left. Mild generalized frontal background slowing.
Superimposed focal slowing, most prominent in the temporal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 22-year-old woman with a history of epilepsy, but has been seizure-free for years.  This is a follow-up EEG.
MEDICATIONS: Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.

Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving bilaterally, with an unusual  photoparoxysmal response which included  slowing  with frequency evolution but no spike and wave activity and no clinical symptoms.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Discrete right temporal sharp activity with associated underlying focal slowing.
Unusual photoparoxysmal response
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to this patient’s previous EEG done on December 18, 2002, this tracing yields a similar discrete right temporal sharp activity supporting a partial mechanism of epilepsy in this patient.  The photoparoxysmal response was reported in this patients’ childhood records.  Wicket activity is a normal variant.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Discrete right temporal sharp activity with associated underlying focal slowing. Unusual photoparoxysmal response

report:

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 12-year-old female with a history of epilepsy starting at age 8; last seizure at age 10.  Patient here for evaluation to stop antiepileptic medication.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage I sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is mildly disorganized and diffusely slow with excessive theta activity.  There is a 10 Hz, 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  One single sharp activity was found in the C3 region.  Hyperventilation caused a symmetric, slow build-up with 3 to 4 Hz rhythmic slow activity. Subtle sharp activity at T4 was also seen in drowsiness. Drowsiness is characterized by vertex waves. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.  Occasional wicket activity was identified.

Single sharp activity in the left central area.
Subtle sharp activity seen in the right temporal area.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to this patient’s EEG of July 12, 2000, this tracing is much improved.  Hyperventilation, which caused slow activity build-up, is a normal phenomenon of this age.  Wicket activity is a normal variant.  No clinical seizures were recorded during this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to Mildly disorganized background with excessive slow activity for a child of this age. Single sharp activity in the left central area. Subtle sharp activity seen in the right temporal area.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage I sleep record.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 37-year-old male with HIV infection, schizophrenia, hepatitis C, and a question of seizures versus non-epileptic seizures, as well as behavioral issues.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and HIV medications.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is described as poorly cooperative.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow with a 7 to 8 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and excess background theta, as well as generous, low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In this background with theta, there is left temporal wicket activity with some wicket identified on the right. In the transition to drowsiness, there are occasional bursts of frontally predominant delta.  Features noted as the patient becomes drowsy include an increase in background beta.  Occasional K complexes are seen in stage II sleep, again followed by arousals.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing a small degree of slowing in the background.  Photic stimulation does not significantly activate this record.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient’s medications, hepatic problems, or retroviral infection may all produce the background slowing described above as may a postictal state.  While the wicket is a sharply contoured normal variant, no definite epileptiform features were seen, and a more prolonged recording in stage II sleep may be helpful to identify epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Generalized background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 39-year-old male with epilepsy and HIV infection with multiple frequent seizures and strong suspicions for non-epileptic seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Phenobarbital, and Tylenol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. The patient has a long behavioral event and requires Ativan to calm down.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  The patient starts hyperventilation early on in the record without the development of epileptiform activity.  At 11:48:34, he begins to have shaking movements, shaking the head from side to side and arms going up and down.  There are then some rotatory components or circular movements of the head.  The activity waxes and wanes.  The physician comes in to test the patient at 11:55:30.  The patient’s behavior waxes and wanes.  He is examined by a physician and nurse, and is clearly interactive during the spell.  Ativan is given at 16:14 and by 16:17, he is a bit more responsive and interactive.  When asked where he is, he responds that he is at [hospital] Hospital.  The EEG demonstrates a relatively normal pattern by the end with some generous beta.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The prolonged behavioral event, lasting almost 20 minutes, was not associated with epileptiform activity in the EEG.  Consideration for other diagnostic categories is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
History:	65 year old woman with seizures.
Medications:	Keppra, Paxil
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10-10.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is noted.  During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm
attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 26-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information.  Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication
effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 26-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information.  Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication
effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:

MEDICATIONS: Benadryl, Folate, Clonidine, Ativan, and Dilantin.

Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in the background beta activity, as well as attenuation of the alpha rhythm. HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage I sleep.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage I sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 47-year-old male with epilepsy and drug abuse who presents with right arm shaking and weakness and right eye twitching.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Clonidine, and insulin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and briefly asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10.5 Hz, 25 to 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  There is a subtle intrahemispheric asymmetry seen mainly in hyperventilation, which is characterized by drop-out of faster frequency of the left centrotemporal area and occasional left frontotemporal sharp waves.  Stage I sleep is briefly achieved and characterized by vertex waves and slow rolling eye movements.  MU rhythm is seen better in the right hemisphere than on the left.  Photic stimulation elicits a minimal driving response.
HR:  87 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
A subtle intrahemispheric asymmetry with left centrotemporal slowing in early hyperventilation.
Occasional left frontotemporal sharp waves, which increase in hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a focal mechanism for epilepsy in this patient.  Correlation with neuroimaging studies would be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to A subtle intrahemispheric asymmetry with left centrotemporal slowing in early hyperventilation. Occasional left frontotemporal sharp waves, which increase in hyperventilation.

report:

DESCRIPTION OF THE  RECORD: The background EEG is organized. The posterior rhythm is about 10Hz alpha, and the anterior rhythm is low voltage beta. Diffusely, there is excessive beta activity seen in this record.  Drowsiness and sleep were not noted during this record. There is no abnormal epileptiform activity seen in this record.   There is no abnormal interhemispheric  attenuation or slowing seen in this record.

HR:  80BPM.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG, however, there is excessive sedative  drug effect due  to beta activity.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: In this patient who is on sedative agents, the excess beta probably represents medication effect. However, abnormal epileptiform activity was not seen this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG, however, there is excessive sedative  drug effect due  to beta activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 43-year-old male with recurrent seizures, last seizure three weeks ago with loss of consciousness with generalized tonic-clonic activity for one to two minutes.  History of skull fracture associated with subdural hematoma following an MVA in 2002 and alcohol abuse.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric, continuous, but mildly disorganized.  There is a 12 Hz, 10 to 15 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm, which is attenuated with eyes opened. There is a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation was performed with good effort, producing an increase in the slow activity of theta in the frontal region.  Post-hyperventilation, the activity returns to baseline within two minutes. Sleep is not achieved in this tracing.  Photic stimulation elicits driving, but no abnormal responses.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Mildly disorganized background.
Excessive beta activity seen throughout the record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The above findings are non-specific.  The increased beta activity may be due to medication or long-term alcohol use.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to Mildly disorganized background. Excessive beta activity seen throughout the record.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This  is  a  44-year-old   male  with  alcohol  withdrawal,  head trauma, and epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Probably Trazodone, Lexapro, or others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video BEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system  of  electrode  placement  with  one  channel  of  EKG.  The  patient  is  somewhat confused.
DESCRIPTION OF THE  RECORD: The background BEG is abnormal and includes a pattern of diffuse  beta.   The left hemisphere  demonstrates  higher amplitude  arrhythmic delta  activity  with  a breach  rhythm  and  at  times  sharply contoured  delta  in the  left frontocentral frontotemporal region.   Features of drowsiness include an increase in background beta, but deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
HR:  96BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal BEG due to:
1.  Excess background  beta.
2.   Continuous  mixed  arrhythmic  delta and theta from the left hemisphere,  particularly from the frontocentral region.
3.   Sharply contoured delta in the same region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This BEG supports a structural abnormality  on the left, as well as likely  a prior breach rhythm given the head trauma history.  Excess beta may be due to medications  or other causes.  No seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal BEG due to 1.  Excess background  beta. 2.   Continuous  mixed  arrhythmic  delta and theta from the left hemisphere,  particularly from the frontocentral region. 3.   Sharply contoured delta in the same region.

report:
HISTORY: 18-year-old female with new onset seizures in November 2003 x two.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric, continuous, and  well organized for age.  There is a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which is well attenuated with eyes opened.   There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation activates the record with focal slowing at T6 and O2 areas and occasionally with subtle 3 Hz slow wave discharges in T6 as well as occasional bilateral posterior temporal slow activity. Focal findings can also be observed in drowsiness. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing at T6 and O2 accentuated in hyperventilation with subtle 3 Hz slow wave discharges at T6, as well as slowing in the bilateral posterior temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal findings in this tracing are suggestive of an underlying pathological process in this patient and supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Focal slowing at T6 and O2 accentuated in hyperventilation with subtle 3 Hz slow wave discharges at T6, as well as slowing in the bilateral posterior temporal region.

No reactivity

etiologically nonspecific.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old male with paroxysmal dyskinesias versus epilepsy (PKD) diagnosed at age eight.  Symptoms occur with no warning, now with increasing symptoms in the setting of stress.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record. Of note, the patient was experiencing a feeling as if he was about to have one of his attacks on the day of this study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm of 50 uV with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The overall waking background is well organized. On one occasion in drowsiness and during hyperventilation, there are occasional, brief bursts lasting one to five seconds, typically on the order of three seconds, of slightly irregular theta.  Particularly during hyperventilation, the theta seems to be a bit more prominent on the right with disruption of the posterior dominant rhythm on the right. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
The patient experiences an ongoing feeling throughout the EEG as if he is about to have one of his spells and at 14:39 he reports pressure in his right leg. He reports to the tech at 14:47 that the right leg feels numb at that time.  No EEG changes are seen in association with these symptoms, and the brief bursts of slightly irregular slowing are not seen at the specific times that the patient reports his symptoms.
HR:  68 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Brief bursts of slightly irregular theta, which during hyperventilation seem to disrupt the alpha rhythm on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were seen in this record.  The brief bursts of slightly irregular theta are a non-specific abnormality and may be correlated with neuroimaging.  The symptoms that this patient experienced were not associated with a change in the EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to Brief bursts of slightly irregular theta, which during hyperventilation seem to disrupt the alpha rhythm on the right.

report:

Generalized background slowing.
Modest disorganization.
Occasional FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features are non-specific and may be seen in a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy, as well as postictal state.  No epileptiform features were seen.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing when the patient is little more stable may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. Modest disorganization. Occasional FIRDA.

report:

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.

The focal slowing was more dramatic during sleep and the asymmetry did not change during sleep.

Mildly disorganized background.
Focal arrhythmic delta activity, more predominant on the left than the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal findings in this EEG are indicative of an underlying pathological process suggestive of a structural lesion. The patient’s loud snoring may be suggestive of obstructive sleep apnea and follow-up with a pulmonologist to rule out a sleep disorder is suggested.  No epileptiform features were identified in this record. If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Mildly disorganized background. Focal arrhythmic delta activity, more predominant on the left than the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 63 year old woman with epilepsy, schizophrenia, COPD admitted with multiple complex partial seizures, drug interactions. Previously seizure free.
MEDICATIONS: Coumadin,  Dilantin, Hydralazine, Ciprofloxacin, Percocet
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1  channel of EKG. The date of this patient's seizures is not provided.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness background EEG includes an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm on the right, disrupted on the left. The left hemisphere includes arrhythmic delta activity with a high amplitude periodic sharp wave, maximum at T2 with a generous field of spreading involving the total of T3, T5 and F7. As the recording continues and the patient is stimulated this arrhythmic delta activity in the sharp waves waxes and wanes. The sharp waves may occur in bursts and trains but none last more than 10 seconds. The patient drifts into stage  1  sleep with vertex waves. The focal sharp wave contoured delta, focal slowing and sharp waves persist. There is a generous field of spread both for the sharp waves and to the focal slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving, more so on the right.
HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	Prominent focal slowing from the left temporal region.
2.	Prominent left temporal sharp waves, sometimes periodic, sometimes occurring in trains.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   This EEG supports a highly irritative focus and a localization related mechanism to epilepsy. Please pull previous studies for comparison to this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Prominent focal slowing from the left temporal region. 2.Prominent left temporal sharp waves, sometimes periodic, sometimes occurring in trains.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old right handed male with recent left MCA infarct, aneurysm repair, ACA clip, chronic encephalomalacia in the right frontal region now with drowsiness and new left-sided weakness transferred back from the nursing home.

Markedly abnormal background with marked asymmetry.
A slow pattern on the left.
A pattern that is also abnormal on the right with C4 sharp waves.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Markedly abnormal background with marked asymmetry. A slow pattern on the left. A pattern that is also abnormal on the right with C4 sharp waves.

report:
HISTORY: This is a 40-year-old, left-handed male with epilepsy since age 9 with loss of consciousness and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  No previous records were available for comparison.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In the transition to drowsiness, there is occasional temporal wicket, but there is a suspicious, underlying right temporal sharp wave identified in early drowsiness.
As the patient emerges to and from sleep, there is some rhythmic frontal mixed theta and delta, which is on the whole symmetric, although on one or two occasions there is a suggestion of maximum on the right.  Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  On two occasions, there are bursts of rhythmic frontally predominant, paroxysmal activity.  On one occasion, this occurs in the setting of hyperventilation and there seems to be some underlying eye blink, but there is suspicious, 3 to 5 Hz frontally predominant spike and slow wave and poly spike and slow wave activity followed by a more clearly defined eye blink.  The second burst occurs with the transition to sleep.  Again, the burst is less than two seconds long with approximately 5 Hz frontally predominant spike and wave/poly spike and wave activity.  No eye blink can be seen at this time, although the activity is picked up on the eye monitor at the midline.
Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  66 BPM. April 15, 2004

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Suspicious, 3 to 5 Hz poly spike and slow wave activity seen in hyperventilation and on one occasion in drowsiness.
Subtle right anterior temporal sharp waves with questionable focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Consideration for more than one mechanism to account for this patient’s seizures would be appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Suspicious, 3 to 5 Hz poly spike and slow wave activity seen in hyperventilation and on one occasion in drowsiness. Subtle right anterior temporal sharp waves with questionable focal slowing.

report:

Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:		International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy, photic

Description:

Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
No epileptiform discharges No stage 2 sleep
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 24-minute EEG, awake and drowsy. No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded. If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
