report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old woman with a history of hypertension, end-stage renal disease on hemodialysis admitted for subdural hemorrhage, which was surgically.  Acute seizures, not described

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, antihypertensives, and others.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the Neuro ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is continuous and symmetric with generalized slowing.  There is a 7 to 8 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which is well attenuated with eyes opened.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Soon after the EEG commences, the patient began to shake her left arm and then both arms and hands on her abdomen.  The shaking was in a different direction at different rhythms.  The patient could open and close her eyes and follow commands during this episode.  Alternatively, when her left-hand shaking stopped, she began to open and close her legs with shaking, left side worse then the right.  With the prolonged episode, muscle movement artifact can be seen, but no significant EEG changes or correlates were found.  On the video camera, several doctors were called to see the patient.  The patient can open and close her eyes, follow commands, and lift her arms and legs up.  Interestingly, the patientÕs episodes spontaneously subsided if no one paid attention to her and she responded to a placebo of saline injection.  Throughout the EEG, there were no epileptiform discharges, but occasionally sharply contoured delta activity in the left central area is seen.

HR:  116 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Diffusely slow background.
2. Occasional sharply contoured delta in the left central area.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The diffusely slow background, as well as occasional sharply contoured delta activity in the left central area may be suggestive of an underlying pathological process in this patient, which is commonly seen in patients with hypertension and end-stage renal disease on hemodialysis.  This finding can also be seen in patients with subdural hematoma.  During the tracing, the patient had prolonged episodes of arm or leg shaking without EEG change, as well as being responsive to commands.  This is suggestive of non-epileptic seizures.  These findings were communicated with the primary neurosurgery team.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern or clinically indicated, when the patient is more stable and cooperative, a repeat EEG in the lab with full activation including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, as well as capturing deeper stages of sleep may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Diffusely slow background. 2. Occasional sharply contoured delta in the left central area.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old male with a history of epilepsy and a syncopal episode with jerking movements of the body and gasping sounds.
MEDICATIONS: Aspirin, Benadryl, and Tylenol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the/at the lab/bedside? using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record with hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The vast majority of the waking record is poorly organized, although at the very end of the record, the background EEG is actually reasonably well organized with a low voltage pattern and a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  In the early portions of the record, when the patient appears to be awake, the background EEG is moderately disorganized with some shifting slowing.  There is also some temporal wicket activity seen.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and elicits rhythmic bursts of frontally predominant, high amplitude delta, which are quite prominent.  In addition, underlying this, there are some right temporal sharp waves.  In the post-HV recording, there is an underlying right temporal sharp and slow wave activity.
Photic stimulation elicits a photoelectric artifact only.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Despite the technical limitations described above, this EEG is abnormal due to:
Right temporal sharp waves.
Shifting arrhythmic delta activity seen particularly in the initial portions of the record.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for this patient’s epilepsy.  The dynamic changes with improvement in the organization towards the end of the record may be part of this patient’s recovery from some sort of acute disturbance, which may be postictal, metabolic, or post-syncope. With a prominent frontal delta in HV, this is a non-specific finding and comparison with previous studies may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Despite the technical limitations described above, this EEG is abnormal due to Right temporal sharp waves. Shifting arrhythmic delta activity seen particularly in the initial portions of the record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 30 to 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm. In wakefulness, there are occasional, high amplitude left anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes.  These reach amplitudes well over 100 uV and are preceded and followed by focal slowing.  There is intermittent left mid-to-anterior temporal focal slowing seen in brief bursts lasting less than one second with a mixture of delta and theta frequency activity, as well as a disruption of alpha frequency activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is also some rhythmic left temporal theta identified. Features of drowsiness include an increase in background beta, as well as attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  The drowsy record is primarily recorded in referential montage, and the left anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes can be identified in this montage.
Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.  The epileptiform discharges are also seen in photic stimulation, but are not clearly accentuated by this procedure.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal spike and slow wave activity identified in wakefulness.
Intermittent focal slowing seen from the left temporal region, accentuated in drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.  In comparison to previous studies, the epileptiform activity in this record is on the left as opposed to being on the right in the initial study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left anterior temporal spike and slow wave activity identified in wakefulness. Intermittent focal slowing seen from the left temporal region, accentuated in drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old right handed male with epilepsy post-stroke, tonic clonic seizures for the last four years, last seizure was one month ago. History of hypertension, epilepsy post-stroke.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Keppra, Metoprolol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There is occasional shifting temporal theta, more prominent on the left than the right. Discrete anterior temporal sharp waves are observed with rare (2) right centrotemporal sharp waves and a very subtle accentuation of beta activity in the right centrotemporal region, seen in sleep. Hyperventilation accentuates the focal features from the left temporal region. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Left temporal focal slowing.
2. Sharp waves seen primarily on the left.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings have been described in previous EEGs and support a localization related mechanism for epilepsy. Of note, the epileptiform activity on the right has been noted in this individual with many studies, not all have identified epileptiform activity as is often the case in complex partial epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Left temporal focal slowing. 2. Sharp waves seen primarily on the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old right-handed man with history of seizures during asleep described as generalized tonic-clonic activity.  His last seizure was 6 months ago.  Past medical history is significant for hypertension and memory difficulties and hypertriglyceridemia.  This is a followup EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, oxazepam, Lamictal, citalopram, lithium.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm is 8.5-9 Hz in frequency, 30-35 microvolt in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 7-7.5 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness, which is distributed symmetrically.  There is presence of stage 1 sleep characterized by disappearance of alpha rhythm, slowing of the background activity and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves.  Brief stage II sleep was captured characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and did not result in a driving response.  Hyperventilation was also performed and results in diffuse slowing of the background activity.  Heart rate was 70-80 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to excess theta activity during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to toxic, metabolic, hypoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of sedating medication or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures are identified in this record.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a repeat sleep deprived EEG or continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to excess theta activity during wakefulness.

report:

Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If epilepsy is a concern, a repeat EEG when the patient is awake with routine activation procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, as well as capturing deeper stages of sleep may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old male with complex partial epilepsy, now with increasing seizures since he ran out of Lamictal.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Tegretol, Lamictal, and Glucotrol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is abnormal. The right hemisphere is relatively well organized with a posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz, 30 uV.  The left hemisphere demonstrates intermittent arrhythmic delta activity seen occasionally in wakefulness, accentuated by hyperventilation, maximum in the temporal region.  There are a handful of left anterior temporal sharp waves identified in hyperventilation in the bursts of rhythmic slowing.  Following hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, the focal slowing from the left is accentuated.  On one occasion there is a train of sharp waves identified from the left temporal region, as well as a single right temporal sharp wave.  These can be differentiated from the patient’s EKG artifact.   On some occasions, there is a somewhat periodic left temporal sharp wave picked up, but mixed in this discharge there will be a subtle right anterior temporal sharp wave.  Vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  The epileptiform activity appears to decrease in stage II sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving at faster flash frequencies.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal focal slowing.
Left anterior temporal sharp and slow wave complexes, which are sometimes periodic.
Occasional right temporal sharp waves, which seem to occur out of the background, independently at times periodic sharp waves on the left, but occur during the same epochs when the focus on the left is active.  No seizures were recorded.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy as well as structural abnormality on the left.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left anterior temporal focal slowing. Left anterior temporal sharp and slow wave complexes, which are sometimes periodic. Occasional right temporal sharp waves, which seem to occur out of the background, independently at times periodic sharp waves on the left, but occur during the same epochs when the focus on the left is active.  No seizures were recorded.

report:
History:	62 year old man with a history of seizures.
Medications:	Keppra, Depakote
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9-9.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow
waves appear diffusely.
Intermittent polymorphic theta and delta activity is present in the left temporal region.  No
epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and accentuates focal
slowing in the left temporal region.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce additional abnormalities.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
Focal slowing, polymorphic, intermittent, mild, left temporal
Interpretation:
This is an abnormal awake and very briefly drowsy 27-minute EEG due to intermittent mild focal
slowing in the left temporal region.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is
etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  No epileptiform discharges are present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an abnormal awake and very briefly drowsy 27-minute EEG due to intermittent mild focal
slowing in the left temporal region.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is
etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  No epileptiform discharges are present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 22-year-old woman with seizures since age 9.  Increasing seizures in pregnancy characterized by jerking of the hands followed by loss of consciousness, tonic-clonic activity, incontinence, tongue biting, and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, folate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 80 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a modest amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing a small amount of slowing as well as increasing the amplitude of the background.  At the end of hyperventilation, there is a single burst of arrhythmic delta seen first on the left and then on the right.  Following this, the patient becomes drowsy with an increase in background beta as well as occasional vertex waves.  Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves, K complexes, and POSTS with intermittent arousals from sleep.  As she awakens from sleep for photic stimulation, a hypersynchronous pattern is identified.
Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response seen with a spiky driving at 5 Hz, but no definite spike and slow wave complex.
HR:  56 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered normal in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The single asynchronous burst seen in hyperventilation is of unclear clinical significance.  Given the pattern identified with a 5 Hz driving response, comparison with childhood EEGs may be helpful in characterizing this patient’s epilepsy.  Alternatively, additional recording with repeat photic stimulation at various frequencies and/or accentuated by hyperventilation could be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered normal in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 26-year-old female with seizures in February and July of 2004.  Most recent seizure associated with Xanax withdrawal. Positive family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a symmetric, reactive 10 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The major abnormality in this record is occipitally predominant rhythmic approximately 5 Hz activity.  This can be seen in wakefulness and is clearly accentuated in hyperventilation.  On some occasions it is seen into stage II sleep.  This activity can be reviewed in both circle montage and a referential montage.  In hyperventilation, this activity appears to be sometimes maximum on the right spreading to the left, but in other settings, the activity appears to be symmetric, nearly identical or clearly identical at O1 and O2.  During hyperventilation, the occipitally predominant theta frequency activity has some paroxysmal build up, but does not evolve.  Other features of hyperventilation include both eye blink and hypersynchronous rhythmic high amplitude delta.
Features of stage II sleep include vertex waves and spindles.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.  Some of the occipitally predominant bursts can be seen even in photic.
HR:  82 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Occipitally predominant, 5 to 6 Hz theta activity, increasing in hyperventilation and persisting into stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: To further localize this activity, a follow-up study with special electrodes may be valuable.  Correlation with neuroimaging may be helpful.  These findings were not seen on this patient’s previous EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Occipitally predominant, 5 to 6 Hz theta activity, increasing in hyperventilation and persisting into stage II sleep.

report:

report:
History:	44 year old woman who suffered a reported status epilepticus in 9/2015.
Medications:	Dilantin
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10-10.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow
waves appear diffusely.
Occasional polymorphic theta and delta activity is captured over the left anterior temporal region.
No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at
multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
Focal slowing, polymorphic, occasional, mild
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL 22-minute awake and drowsy EEG due to occasional mild left anterior
temporal slowing. This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically non-
specific, but possibly structural in origin.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL 22-minute awake and drowsy EEG due to occasional mild left anterior
temporal slowing. This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically non-
specific, but possibly structural in origin

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 61-year-old woman with COPD, steroid-induced diabetes, pneumothorax with PEA, and concerns regarding encephalopathy.
MEDICATIONS: Prednisone, insulin, Heparin, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is intubated but awake and interactive with the tech.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is low voltage, but demonstrates an awake pattern with low voltage beta.  It is difficult to define an alpha in this low voltage record.
HR:  150 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The absence of an alpha rhythm in a low voltage record such as this does not constitute an abnormality as a single finding.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 61-year-old woman with change in mental status and steroid dependency OPD.
MEDICATIONS: ?
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient has a tracheostomy and is unable to follow commands.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is low voltage, diffusely slow with a mixture of rhythmic, low voltage theta and delta as well as smaller amounts of beta.  There are occasional asymmetries, and in some sections of the record there is more rhythmic theta from either hemisphere.  The delta is overall symmetric.
HR:  EKG N/A.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Shifting asymmetries in terms of the predominance of theta frequency activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features are non-specific and support a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function involving both gray and white matter.  This may be due to a toxic or metabolic process, as well as a diffuse brain disturbance.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. Shifting asymmetries in terms of the predominance of theta frequency activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old woman with epilepsy, last seizure five days ago.  Onset of seizures at age 4.  Patient experiences numbness on the right side of the head for one minute then loss of consciousness, drops to the ground with generalized shaking lasting five minutes, and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Topamax.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a modest amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Photic stimulation is performed early on in the record and produces a small degree of bilateral driving.  Following this, the patient becomes drowsy, with an increased in background theta and a small degree of disorganization of the background as well as POSTS.
Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves and spindles.  Snore artifact is seen with brief arousals from sleep.
HR:  64 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old woman with a history of seizures; last seizure yesterday.  Seizures described with auras and numbness on the right side of the face and head followed by expressive aphasia and loss of consciousness.  Patient experiences urinary incontinence and postictal confusion.  Seizure frequency has increased since the patient was switched from Tegretol to Topamax.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 8 to 10 Hz, 40 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  Hyperventilation produces diffuse paroxysmal slowing in the left temporal area more so than the right.  Following hyperventilation, the patient falls into stage I sleep identified by vertex waves with accentuation of the delta activity, left temporal area more than right with occasional sharp waves.  Photic stimulation elicits minimal driving.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Occasional left temporal sharp waves.
Hyperventilation producing left temporal slowing more than the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The above findings in this tracing are supportive of this patient’s seizures. If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep would be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Occasional left temporal sharp waves. Hyperventilation producing left temporal slowing more than the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 28-year-old female with head trauma in 2002 without LOC followed with staring spells without tongue biting, last seizure one week ago.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a suggestion of posterior slow waves of youth. Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles seen in stage II sleep.
Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and produces subtle, left temporal slowing.  The background in HV is sharply contoured and there is some shifting bursts in the T1 and T2 regions, which are sharply contoured but no definitive epileptiform activity.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving and just prior to photic stimulation, there is a suggestion of a C3 sharp wave.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Subtle left temporal focal slowing elicited in hyperventilation and persisting afterwards, at times sharply contoured.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definitive sharp waves were seen in this study.  Because of the nature of this patient’s spells, an additional recording may be warranted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Subtle left temporal focal slowing elicited in hyperventilation and persisting afterwards, at times sharply contoured.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 45-year-old woman with epilepsy for ten years, last seizure two weeks ago.  Patient’s seizures described as staring with oral automatisms and wandering mind.  [Check for previous EEGs]
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a modest amount of rhythmic temporal theta seen bilaterally.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and produces a prominent increase in theta, particularly in the temporal and occipital regions, again relatively symmetric.  Photic stimulation elicits harmonic, supraharmonic, and subharmonic driving responses.
HR:  102 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Unusual hyperventilation response with posterior temporally predominant rhythmic theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite epileptiform features were seen in this record.  The features described in the occipitotemporal regions are unusual.  It is possible that these would represent a normal variant such as alpha subharmonic.  Comparison with previous EEGs may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to Unusual hyperventilation response with posterior temporally predominant rhythmic theta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 47-year-old woman with a 20-year history of epilepsy.  Seizure control better, now having approximately six seizures a month described as the left eye feeling hot, staring, inability to communicate, though she is able to hear, and twitching of the arms.  Postictally, she has migraines and is confused.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 to 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  It is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing with occasional vertex waves in stage I sleep. Hyperventilation produces an increase in theta.  In photic stimulation, there is a discrete driving response.  In addition, the left posterior temporal discrete sharp and slow wave complexes are identified, maximum at T5, but at times involving O1 and P3.  It may occur during photic stimulation or just after.  The discharges are all single, isolated discharges never appearing in trains or pairs.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Discrete left posteriotemporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Discrete left posteriotemporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 22-year-old woman with epilepsy since childhood, one of a pair of twins.  Mild cognitive impairment and obsessive-compulsive disorder.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Lamictal, Risperdal, Lithium, and Paxil.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In wakefulness, there is frequent eye blink, but in the transition from wakefulness to drowsiness, there is also notched, sharply contoured, frontally predominant 5 to 7 Hz activity in the frontal regions, as well as a signal left mid-to-anterior temporal sharp wave.  There were a total of four left anterior temporal sharp waves.  Features of sleep include an increase in beta activity as well as occasional vertex waves and spindles.  There are multiple brief arousals from sleep.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and appears to accentuate some of the rhythmic frontal 5 to 7 Hz activity.  In sleep, there is a second, left temporal sharp wave.
Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Some sharply contoured, notched 5 to 7 Hz activity seen in the frontal regions, sometimes with isolated discharges and sometimes seen with brief bursts seen in wakefulness and in sleep.
Rare left anterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.  The rhythmic theta frequency activity described above may be part of this patient’s constellation of neurologic abnormalities.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Some sharply contoured, notched 5 to 7 Hz activity seen in the frontal regions, sometimes with isolated discharges and sometimes seen with brief bursts seen in wakefulness and in sleep. Rare left anterior temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman with complex partial epilepsy and learning disability since childhood.  Infrequent seizures versus seizure-free.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Lamictal, Risperdal, Lithium.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is in stage II sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles. The patient is alerted for hyperventilation.  As she does so, there is some wicket activity identified in the left anterior temporal region.  The awake record demonstrates a 9 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  Hyperventilation produces an increase of the amplitude of the background.  Following HV, the patient drifts back to stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  Photic stimulation elicits an alerting response with scant driving.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is a slight asymmetric wicket seen as the patient is aroused from sleep, but no focal or epileptiform features are identified in this record.  This contrast to previous studies identified left temporal abnormalities in childhood.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 61-year-old woman with a single, probable complex partial seizure on February 20, 2004 with loss of consciousness.  Patient awoke in an ambulance.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage I sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 8.5 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In the transition to drowsiness, there is some slightly irregular temporal bursts seen with some shifting asymmetries left and right.  On one or two occasions, there is a T1 phase reversal.  Other features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved. Of note, there is some electrode artifact picked up in the T2 electrode in drowsiness.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces some background slowing as well as a single burst of sharply contoured left temporal delta activity. Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.
HR:  __ BPM. Check tech sheet
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Irregular, shifting temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is a clear burst of sharply contoured delta activity from the left temporal region and some suspicious sharp activity in drowsiness.  Some of this resembles wicket and with a combination of the electrode artifact and the wicket, no definitive conclusions regarding clearly epileptiform activity can be made.  In comparison to a previous EEG in April 2004, the previous EEG was normal.  A repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep would be helpful to more clearly evaluate this individual for seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to 1.Irregular, shifting temporal slowing.

report:

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:

2. Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
3. Shifting slowing.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Excess theta. 2. Slowing of the alpha rhythm. 3. Shifting slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 36-year-old woman with asthma, anxiety, and epilepsy for ten years consisting of complex partial seizures.  Patient admitted with multiple seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Phenobarbital, Ativan, Combivent, Prevacid, Flonase, and Trazodone.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric.  There is an 11 Hz, 15 uV posterior dominant rhythm and diffuse excessive beta activity.  Hyperventilation increases the slow activity in the background.  Sleep is evidenced by vertex waves, spindles, and K complexes. Single sharp wave was identified at T3, unfortunately this channel also has some artifact.  Photic stimulation elicits driving.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  44 year old left handed female with refractory seizures, GERD, hyperlipidemia, DVT, PE, asthma, diabetes, and hypertension who complains of chest pain.  She did not take Zonisamide this morning.
MEDICATIONS:  Zonisamide, Lisinopril, Percocet, Narcan, Zocor, Lovenox, ASA.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded in stage I and stage II sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen frequently at F7/T1.
Focal slow waves seen almost continuously at F7/T1 throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal sharp waves.
Continuous slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy, with seizures likely arising from the left anterior temporal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which has a high correlation with a structural lesion in that region.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Left anterior temporal sharp waves. Continuous slowing.

report:
History:	47 year old woman who was found down.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, asleep
Description:
The posterior dominant rhythm consists of polymorphic up to 9 Hz unstable alpha activity with poor
AP gradient.  The background contains excess polymorphic theta and delta activity.  Patient rapidly
transitions between wakefulness and drowsiness.  Symmetric vertex waves, sleep spindles and K-
complexes are noted.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  There is nearly continuous T5
electrode artifact.
Summary of Findings:
Artifact, electrode, nearly continuous,  T5 electrode artifact
No epileptiform discharges
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and asleep portable EEG due to mild diffuse slowing and
background disorganization. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild diffuse
cerebral dysfunction.  But in this patient, these findings could also be contributed to excessive
drowsiness ( given rapid transitions between wakefulness and drowsiness).  The lack of epileptiform
discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 55-year-old male who was being evaluated for an intra-arterial TPA when he had a seizure.  He was noted to be aphasic and was in the middle of the stroke protocol when the event occurred.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, aspirin, Heparin, thiamin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record in a patient who varies between drowsiness and restlessness.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There are brief portions of the record where the patient is maximally alert and a low voltage 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm is identified.  During much of the waking record, there is bilateral excess theta.  In addition, temporal wicket is seen.  There is intermittent, arrhythmic temporal slowing identified, left greater than right.  Features of stage I sleep include vertex waves.  As the recording continues in this postictal patient, the overall background organization improves and the focality is more left temporal than right.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Initially, bihemispheric slowing.
Shifting temporal slowing, which by the close of the record is most prominent on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This tracing supports a dynamic process, which seems to be improving over time and may reflect a postictal state.   Correlation with neuroimaging is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Initially, bihemispheric slowing. Shifting temporal slowing, which by the close of the record is most prominent on the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 31-year-old male with childhood epilepsy, seizure free until recent years.  Patient states that he is currently seizure-free for the past year.

A subtle asymmetry is noted between the 2 hemispheres with a bit of 7 Hz theta noted in the right hemisphere relative to the left and very subtle disruption of the alpha rhythm on the right.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the record becomes increasingly synchronous and symmetric.  Other features of drowsiness include rhythmic background theta and attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Brief spindles were noted with POSTS in stage 2 sleep.  Photic stimulation was performed as the patient is drifting in to stage 2 sleep, and did not significantly activate the record.  Hyperventilation produced a vigorous hyperventilation response with an increase in rhythmic theta as well as an increase in beta.  There is some subtle, asymmetric bursts noted in hyperventilation with higher amplitude rhythmic theta noted on the left.  There is one, suspicious underlying sharp waves noted at the close of hyperventilation in the right centrotemporal region.
Heart rate 56 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to:
A very subtle asymmetry, identified using a frequency analysis with an increase in 7 Hz activity noted intermittently in the right hemisphere with disruption of the alpha rhythm.
An asynchronous hyperventilation response with higher amplitude rhythmic theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Only a single sharp wave was seen there for this must not be considered definitively epileptogenic.  This is the 7th EEG for this individual.  Previous EEGs have identified right mid temporal sharp waves, which were not identified at this time.  This patient's 2004-2008 EEGs were not available for comparison.  No prominent epileptiform or focal features were noted, and no new findings were noted in this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to A very subtle asymmetry, identified using a frequency analysis with an increase in 7 Hz activity noted intermittently in the right hemisphere with disruption of the alpha rhythm. An asynchronous hyperventilation response with higher amplitude rhythmic theta.

There are rare left anterior temporal sharp and slow waves demonstrated in wakefulness and in the transition to sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
Intermittently, during the record, the patient has some muscle artifact picked up in the left which is clearly differentiated from the focal slowing and the epileptiform activity and is associated with some muscle or twitch artifact but is not a seizure.
HR:  __ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing.
Left anterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The background is appropriate for an individual of this age.  The epileptiform activity and the focal slowing support a partial mechanism for epilepsy.  The behavior, however, of facial automatisms was not associated with a change in the EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Focal slowing. Left anterior temporal sharp waves.

report:

50 uV, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow  rolling  eye  movements.  Deeper  stages  of  sleep  are  not  achieved.    The  only abnormality in this EEG are three bursts of rhythmic, frontal delta, left greater than right. Two occur in wakefulness and one in drowsiness. Hyperventilation did not activate the record. Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
HR:  96BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.   Three  bursts of asymmetric, rhythmic frontal delta, left greater than right, without obvious spikes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No sharp waves or spikes were seen. This EEG raises the possibility of a process in the frontal region.  Adults with frontal lobe epilepsy do not always demonstrate epileptiform  activity.   Comparison with previous EEGs would be
helpful.  Repeat EEG is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.   Three  bursts of asymmetric, rhythmic frontal delta, left greater than right, without obvious spikes.

report:

report:

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 58-year-old male with falls.  Evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Norvasc, Lipitor, Dilantin, Zocor, Lorazepam, and aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is organized with a 10 Hz, 20 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.
The major abnormality in this record is intermittent rhythmic temporal delta (FIRDA) seen in quiet wakefulness, accentuated by hyperventilation, and prominent in the transition to sleep.  It is sometimes associated with left anterior temporal spike and slow wave or sharp and slow wave complexes.  On one occasion, fast activity is associated with this.  Photic stimulation elicits both an arousal response and some driving.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Occasional spike and slow or sharp and slow wave activity in the left anterior temporal region.
Left temporal FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The epileptiform features in this record are more prominent compared to previous studies.  This EEG supports a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.  This is this patient’s third EEG in 2006, and it is his sixth EEG since 2002.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Occasional spike and slow or sharp and slow wave activity in the left anterior temporal region. Left temporal FIRDA.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 58-year-old male with increasing seizures requiring an increase in Phenytoin dosing.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Ativan, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and doesn’t seem to activate the record.  The patient seems to be a bit drowsy. In addition, despite some EKG artifact, there are some underlying sharp waves seen primarily at T1, but occasionally at T2 as well.   As the patient drops into stage I sleep, again the sharp waves and rhythmic temporal delta are seen in bursts.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent rhythmic temporal delta, left greater than right, primarily seen in drowsiness.
Independent, T1 or T2 spike and slow wave complexes seen primarily in drowsiness, greater on the left than the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.  Correlation with imaging may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Intermittent rhythmic temporal delta, left greater than right, primarily seen in drowsiness. Independent, T1 or T2 spike and slow wave complexes seen primarily in drowsiness, greater on the left than the right.

report:

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and well organized for age.  There is an 8 to 10 Hz, 50 to 70 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which attenuates with eye opening. There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation increased the burst of theta slow wave activity in the background.  There is a single T3 sharp wave without focal slowing.  Occasionally, occipital slow activity and POSTS were seen in drowsiness. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and vertex waves. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.  Photic stimulation elicits mild subharmonic driving.
HR:  86 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal awake and drowsy EEG in a subject of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to this patient’s previous EEG, this tracing shows improvement without focal slowing. Only one sharp wave was observed in the left temporal area, which can be seen in a normal subject of this age.  The posterior slow waves of youth and POSTS are normal variants. Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal awake and drowsy EEG in a subject of this age.

sharp activity in the left anterior temporal and occipital regions.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 55-year-old male with epilepsy.  Patient had one event during the EEG characterized by tenseness with eyes opened, not focused, mild tremulousness of body and legs, and unable to respond to questions during the event.  The patient was somewhat confused for 1.5 minutes afterwards.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Norvasc, Lasix, and Lipitor.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Photic stimulation is performed early on in the record.  A brief driving response is seen, but as the patient relaxes a little bit further, subtle left temporal slowing is seen.  Hyperventilation is performed subsequently and the subtle focal features can be identified.  A seizure occurred following hyperventilation and post-hyperventilation.  Post-hyperventilation, the focal slowing gradually increases 20 seconds after the onset of hyperventilation.  The seizure onset is at 14:08:37 with no clinical signs, but high amplitude spike and slow wave activity with rhythmic delta and then high amplitude delta and sharply contoured delta with a clear phase reversal at T1.  The patient starts to arouse at 14:08:57, opening his eyes and then stiffening.  He is slightly tremulous and demonstrates chewing movements.  The activity makes the transition to repetitive alpha frequency activity and then 5 Hz frequency activity by 14:09:17.  The activity begins to slow and ends at 14:09:38 for an approximate one-minute seizure duration.  The background EEG demonstrates postictal slowing in the minutes that follow, which gradually resolves.  The patient is unable to speak during the seizure and in the postictal period he nods his head from side to side.  He has a relatively lengthy postictal period including almost all the way to the end of the record.  Over time, he becomes increasingly able to speak, although initially he answers all questions with “uhm-uhm” noise.  Over time, he can answer questions, but has difficulty performing simple tasks.
HR:  94 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal seizure, relatively well characterized by scalp EEG.
Left temporal focal slowing with rare sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Diagnostic of a partial mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left temporal seizure, relatively well characterized by scalp EEG. Left temporal focal slowing with rare sharp waves.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old, right-handed male with epilepsy since age 12.  Last seizure one week ago with postictal drowsiness.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a high amplitude 50 to 75 uV posterior dominant rhythm of 10.5 Hz. Drowsiness is characterized by anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  Other features of drowsiness include a handful of POSTS and an increase in background theta.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits symmetric bilateral driving. Following photic stimulation, just at the close of the EEG, there is a single burst of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity of 6 Hz in duration.
HR:  ___ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
A single burst of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity of 6 Hz in duration.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: A single burst of epileptiform activity does not make this record abnormal, however, the activity described above is compatible with a primary generalized epilepsy.  It may be more cost effective to compare this EEG with previous, childhood studies rather than repeating a study.  Alternatively, if additional mechanisms are needed to characterize epileptiform activity, a fasting, sleep deprived study with generous hyperventilation could be effective.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to A single burst of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity of 6 Hz in duration.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 12-year-old male with a history of staring spells with impairment of consciousness lasting two to five seconds, occurring one to two times per month.  These episodes have been occurring since age four.  History of hypertension and  renal disorder.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized for a child of this age.  There is a 9.5 Hz, 70 to 80 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a fair amount of theta.   There is intermittent rhythmic left posterior temporal spike and sharp waves with occasional generalized bursts of spike wave activity lasting two to three seconds.  Hyperventilation and post-hyperventilation seems to accentuate the discharges, which are followed by brief slowing for several seconds thereafter.  The left posterior temporal discharges are localized at T5, and occasional sharp waves are also noted on the right parietal area at P4 without causing generalized spread. The generalized discharges are frontally predominant and seem to arise out of a left temporal focus maximum at T5.  Photic stimulation elicits discrete driving.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Bursts of generalized spike wave discharges, which are preceded by a left posterior temporal discharge focus.
Somewhat slow and disorganized background for a child of this age.
Occasional sharp waves in the right hemisphere at P4.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy in this patient with a left posterior temporal focus suggestive of complex partial seizures with occasional secondary generalization.  Correlation with neuroimaging studies is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Bursts of generalized spike wave discharges, which are preceded by a left posterior temporal discharge focus. Somewhat slow and disorganized background for a child of this age. Occasional sharp waves in the right hemisphere at P4.

report:

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is asleep.   The background EEG is symmetric, continuous, with an excessive amount of diffuse beta activity.   When the patient is awakened, a 7 to 8 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm is seen.   Superimposed on the background is excessive theta and delta slow activity seen more in the central and posterior regions.  As the tracing continues, spindles are also seen mainly in the central area symmetrically.  Photic stimulation does not activate the record.

Background slowing.
Slow alpha rhythm.

It can be seen in patients who are excessively sleepy, in a postictal phase, or due to medications.  Clinical correlation is recommended, however, no focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record. If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG when the patient is more alert and with routine activation procedures may be helpful.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 3-year-old male with afebrile seizures characterized by eyes rolling back in the head for five minutes, occurring once or twice per month.  Former 28-week gestation infant born weighing 3 lbs., 10 oz.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record. This is the third EEG for this individual.  The two previous EEGs indicated that he had febrile convulsions.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  In sleep, vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are identified.
The major abnormality in this record, is discrete bursts of frontally predominant 3 Hz spike and wave activity seen in the transition to and from stage II sleep.  These are high amplitude discharges, typically occurring in discrete pairs, frontally predominant, symmetric, ranging from 3 to 3.5 Hz.  They can overlap with a spindle, which is a normal morphology of stage II sleep.  On one occasion, a pair of spike and wave complexes may be associated with an arousal.  At the close of the record, the child is stimulated from sleep, and occipitally predominant rhythmic slowing is followed by an awake pattern with LAMBDA when the child is more fully awake.
HR:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	The appearance of frontally predominant, high amplitude spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This activity was not seen in the two previous EEGs.  Correlation with this patient’s history may be helpful in that there were two previous EEGs demonstrating febrile convulsions with a child who may have developed afebrile convulsions and an EEG pattern that is most consistent with an inherited epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.The appearance of frontally predominant, high amplitude spike and wave activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old female with staring spells a1d lip smacking since fifth grade with generalized spike and slow wave activity in childhood, now with headaches and subtle left temporal findings on the most recent EEG. Previous hospitalization and EEG 03/05.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, symmetric, reactive posterior dominant rhythm of 30 to 50 uV. There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. There is some eye movement artifact picked up in the temporal regions as well as some EKG artifact. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in theta in the background. Following HV, as the patient becomes drowsy, there is an increase in background beta and some rhythmic central theta. In drowsiness, there is also some rare, rhythmic 4 to 5 Hz activity from the left temporal region. This is seen on a single location with brief bursts lasting less than a second. Photic stimulation elicits both vigorous driving and some photoelectric artifact. On two occasions, in photic stimulation with a 17 Hz stimulation and following the 15 Hz stimulation, there seems to be some rhythmic focal slowing with a mixture of theta and delta identified from the left hemisphere.
HR: 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Bursts of somewhat irregular slowing identified following photic stimulation from the left hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Although there are a handful of other features including a brief burst of theta from the left, which may be a normal variant, the more remarkable slowing seen in photic stimulation raises the possibility of either a structural or functional abnormality on the left. In this individual with a childhood history of generalized spike and slow wave activity, this finding has not been seen in either of her two adult EEGs. Individuals with childhood epilepsy may haw focal features in adulthood, but those described here are unusual for that.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Bursts of somewhat irregular slowing identified following photic stimulation from the left hemisphere.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, background EEG included the 9.5 posterior dominant rhythm a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. There is a small amount of background theta. In relaxed wakefulness, there are a handful of subtle sharp waves from the left or right temporal region. Most of them are small and discreet, but some have a more of a broader morphology, although they are never high in amplitude. They lack the simplicity of benign epileptiform transience of sleep. The patient has stimulated for hyperventilation and these morphologies disappear. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing an increase in background theta. There is a suggestion that it may also accentuate an arrhythmic delta from the left with independent right and left temporal sharp and slow wave, or spike and slow wave complexes. The epileptiform activity identified in hyperventilation was denoted on the record. Towards the close of the record, high amplitude right inter temple spike and slow wave complexes with generous field of spread were observed. As the patient becomes drowsy, the right temporal sharp waves are again well defined and the left temporal features are not as commonly identified. Other features of sleep include vertex waves and posts. Photic stimulation elicits harmonic with supra harmonic striving.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Right anterior temple spike and slow wave complexes accentuated by hyperventilation and seen in the transition from wakefulness into drowsiness.
2. Occasional more poorly defined left temporal sharp waves.
Clinical correlation: For this young adult with a strong family history of epilepsy, this study today is most supportive of a localization related mechanism with a right inter temple sharp wave with a generous field of spread. There is a remarkably bigger striving response, but not a clearly pathological one.
Additional review of the epilepsy in the family would be important to know if this individual's epilepsy is similar or just similar to other members in the kindred. In contrast to previous studies, the vast majority of epileptiform features today were on the right rather than the left.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Right anterior temple spike and slow wave complexes accentuated by hyperventilation and seen in the transition from wakefulness into drowsiness

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 24 year old right handed woman with epilepsy and 3 seizures on May 3 after medication adjustment. Onset of epilepsy at age 18.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Lamictal, Folic Acid
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a symmetric, reactive, 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Wicket activity is identified from the temporal regions bilaterally. Discrete right temporal sharp waves are noted at T2. They are so discrete in nature and occur out of the wicket that they almost look like an artifact; however, there is clearly an after-going slow wave and there is disruption of the background. They are also nearly the amplitude of the EKG artifact but clearly can be differentiated from the EKG as fortunately they do not occur in conjunction with the EKG. These appear in relaxed wakefulness as the patient start to drift off toward sleep. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous bilateral driving response.
HR: 96 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Right anterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This pattern has been seen previously for this individual. No sharp waves from the left were observed today.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Right anterior temporal sharp waves.

report:

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal BEG for an adult of this age due to 1.  Absence of the normal awake adult developmental milestones. 2.  BEG in sleep demonstrates some asymmetries of the theta in the transition to sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 68-year-old male undergoing a left carotid endarterectomy.
MEDICATIONS: Desflurane, Propofol, Etomidate, Lidocaine, Synephrine, Fentanyl, Versed, and Heparin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the OR using standard CEA montage with one channel of EKG. The recording begins at 8:20 AM and concludes at 12:17 PM.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the patient is in the OR.  He may have been sedated, but induction has not occurred.  There is a 7 to 8 Hz background at 8:24:39 and an anesthetic pattern with the appearance of rhythmic frontal delta and some triangular-shaped waves in the posterior region.  Following the induction of anesthesia, the EEG is slightly discontinuous, but there is no significant focality.  The discontinuity waxes and wanes and is at times subtle.  Heparin is given at 10:15, and the initial clamp is placed at 11:01.  The EEG becomes somewhat discontinuous at 11:02.  These findings are communicated to the surgeon who requests a shunt.  In the discontinuous pattern, there is also a bit of shifting asymmetry.  In addition, there is some slowing identified out of the left prior to placement of the shunt.  The shunt is opened at 11:05.  In addition, as the shunt is placed, there seems to have been a change in the level of anesthesia and in this low voltage pattern, there is more faster frequency activity.  The EEG returns to baseline by 11:06.  The clamp is removed and reclamped at 11:55, 12:01.  Patency is confirmed by doppler at 12:02.  Throughout the procedure, with the clamping  and unclamping, there is some waxing and waning with at times a bit more slowing on the left or the right and also some subtle discontinuity.
By the close of the recording at 12:17, there is some shifting asymmetries, with some head-rocking movements but a question of a bit more slowing in the left posterior quadrant.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION: EEG monitoring during this carotid endarterectomy was remarkable for:
An abnormal baseline with shifting asymmetries.
Transient focal slowing from the left and discontinuity with placement of the clamp; alleviated by shunt.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION: EEG monitoring during this carotid endarterectomy was remarkable for An abnormal baseline with shifting asymmetries

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the patient is in the OR.  He may have been sedated, but induction has not occurred.  There is a 7 to 8 Hz background at 8:24:39 and an anesthetic pattern with the appearance of rhythmic frontal delta and some triangular-shaped waves in the posterior region.  Following the induction of anesthesia, the EEG is slightly discontinuous, but there is no significant focality.  The discontinuity waxes and wanes and is at times subtle.  Heparin is given at 10:15, and the initial clamp is placed at 11:01.  The EEG becomes somewhat discontinuous at 11:02.  These findings are communicated to the surgeon who requests a shunt.  In the discontinuous pattern, there is also a bit of shifting asymmetry.  In addition, there is some slowing identified out of the left prior to placement of the shunt.  The shunt is opened at 11:05.  In addition, as the shunt is placed, there seems to have been a change in the level of anesthesia and in this low voltage pattern, there is more faster frequency activity.  The EEG returns to baseline by 11:06.  The clamp is removed and reclamped at 11:55, 12:01.  Patency is confirmed by doppler at 12:02.  Throughout the procedure, with the clamping  and unclamping, there is some waxing and waning with at times a bit more slowing on the left or the right and also some subtle discontinuity.
By the close of the recording at 12:17, there is some shifting asymmetries, with some head-rocking movements but a question of a bit more slowing in the left posterior quadrant.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION: EEG monitoring during this carotid endarterectomy was remarkable for:
An abnormal baseline with shifting asymmetries.
Transient focal slowing from the left and discontinuity with placement of the clamp; alleviated by shunt.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION: EEG monitoring during this carotid endarterectomy was remarkable for An abnormal baseline with shifting asymmetries

report:

MEDICATIONS: Aspirin, Lisinopril, Percocet, Esmolol, Zofran, Trileptal, others.

Generalized background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	This is a 33-year-old woman admitted to the hospital because of a fall with leg and arm injuries and question of seizures.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY: 	Seizures, pseudotumor, migraines, fibromyalgia. Per the patient she had seizures this morning. Prior to the seizures the patient had vomiting. The patient vomited when brought to the EEG room.
MEDICATIONS: 	Zonisamide, Klonopin, Lovenox, morphine, Toradol and Reglan.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG is performed in the EEG laboratory on the floor using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG. Hyperventilation was not
performed. Photic stimulation was completed. This is awake throughout record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	In wakefulness the background EEG is symmetric and fairly organized for her age. However, the background is slowing with excessive theta and delta activity. There is 8 Hz, 30 microvolts posterior dominant rhythm which is well attenuated with the eyes open. There is a small amount low voltage frontal central beta activity. No sleeping stages were achieved during this tracing. Photic stimulation did not
activate the record.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: 	Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing with excessive theta activity.
2. Borderline slow alpha rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: 	This tracing is a nonspecific finding and may be to due to either the mild cerebral dysfunction excessive sleeping medications, or due to her mental status. However, no
focal findings, no epileptiform discharges were seen in this situation. If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Background slowing with excessive theta activity. 2. Borderline slow alpha rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 50-year-old woman with adult onset epilepsy.  Family says she has not been taking her medicines, admitted with recurrent seizures characterized by head turning to the left and posturing.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan and Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the emergency room using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Patient was postictal, wearing a face mask and poorly cooperative.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG is abnormal and at times, partially obscured by muscle and movement artifact.  The overall background is slow.  Superimposed upon this, there is an asymmetry with more arrhythmic delta activity and disruption of faster frequency activity on the right relative to the left.  There are bursts of irregular theta delta with underlying sharp waves noted from the right hemisphere.  The irregular epileptiform activity demonstrates variable maximum, but is typically maximum in the right posterior quadrant or T4, P4T6.  In addition, there is handful of bursts of more right frontotemporal rhythmic slowing and a handful of lower voltage discrete F8 sharp waves.
Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in muscle and movement.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing and disorganization.
Superimposed focal slowing from the right hemisphere, particularly right temporal region.
Irregular epileptiform activity in the right hemisphere particularly posterior quadrant, but at some points more anteriorly, anterior frontotemporal pathology.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient's previous baseline EEG on long-term monitoring are not available at this time for comparison.  This EEG supports a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.  EEG monitoring will continue.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Background slowing and disorganization. Superimposed focal slowing from the right hemisphere, particularly right temporal region. Irregular epileptiform activity in the right hemisphere particularly posterior quadrant, but at some points more anteriorly, anterior frontotemporal pathology.

report:

report:
History:	46 year old man with a history of seizures and headaches.
Medications:	Depakote - but patient is not compliant
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
Sleep, stage 2
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy
