Past history of stroke with chronic right hemiparesis.  The patient has now had 2 episodes of 5 seconds of screaming, followed by tonic extension, and then 1 hour of postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, Keppra, glipizide, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness the background EEG is well organized.  An alpha rhythm of 50 Hz 70 mV was identified.  As the patient becomes drowsy there is a small amount of shifting slowing.  Stage 1 sleep was not sustained.
Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
Heart rate:  72 BPM, occasionally irregular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a minimally abnormal EEG for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is similar to a previous EEG in 2010 where both EEGs demonstrated 8 Hz alpha rhythm of 50-70 mV.  No epileptiform features were noted.  If additional information is needed, a more prolonged study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.
Of note, in this individual with a stroke and hemiparesis, no focal features were noted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a minimally abnormal EEG for an adult of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 77-year-old male with diabetes, hypertension, MI, and stroke admitted with fevers and chills.  Evaluate for rigors versus seizures.
MEDICATION: Heparin, Vancomycin, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record in a patient who seems to be experiencing some of the muscle movements during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Although the patient is drowsy throughout much of the record, in maximal wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  The shivering movements produce the muscle artifact, but are not associated with epileptiform features.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is some shifting arrhythmic delta identified from either hemisphere.  Other features of sleep include vertex waves, rare spindles, and snore arousals.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Mild excess beta.
Occasional shifting arrhythmic delta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient demonstrated some brief shiver-like movements without EEG change.  This would support a non-epileptic nature for these movements.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to Mild excess beta. Occasional shifting arrhythmic delta activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 40-year-old woman with epilepsy following a craniotomy for aneurysm.  Hypertension and depression.  Last seizure one month ago.
MEDICATIONS: Wellbutrin, Zoloft, Abilify, morphine, methadone, Dilantin, and HCTZ.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. The patient’s previous EEGs were not available at this time.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is intermittent rhythmic theta from the left hemisphere.  Although there is a breach rhythm, and there is some muscle artifact, there appears to be an underlying spike and slow wave complex identified from the left mid-temporal region, accentuated by hyperventilation.  Following hyperventilation, the patient becomes drowsy and in drowsiness there are vertex waves and POSTS.  The amplitude is somewhat higher from the left than the right, accentuating the POSTS on the left.  As the patient reaches sleep, in this sharply contoured background, there is both accentuation of beta on the left but there are a handful of sharp waves that also come out of this background.  Snore artifact is also identified in stage II sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits a driving response, which is markedly accentuated on the left.
HR:  54 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal theta accentuated by drowsiness and hyperventilation.
Left temporal sharp waves in hyperventilation and in stage II sleep.  The morphology is compatible with a breach rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The prominent breach rhythm accentuates the beta activity in stage II sleep and produces an increase in the amplitude of the background in photic stimulation, but is simply a manifestation of the previous craniotomy.  The focal slowing and sharp waves supports a temporal lobe disturbance and a localization-related mechanism for seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left temporal theta accentuated by drowsiness and hyperventilation. Left temporal sharp waves in hyperventilation and in stage II sleep.  The morphology is compatible with a breach rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 56 year old left handed woman with history of seizures, now admitted after multiple recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term monitoring, 6 hours EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  Wakefulness and sleep were recorded.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  After 10:00 at night until 6:00 in the morning from November 6 to November 7, 2011 there was marked muscle and multielectrode artifact to almost impossible reading the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record at the beginning opens to a diffusely slow low amplitude recording with no clear posterior dominant rhythm.  By 2 hours into the recording faster frequencies can be seen and improvement of the EEG to baseline was seen.  At best the posterior dominant rhythm reaches 8 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of frontal central beta seen.  Some sleep architecture is seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Occasional bursts of polyspike and generalized spike and waves seen at 4.5 to 5 Hz with anterior predominance  symmetrically over both hemispheres.  None of the bursts last more than 1 second.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz and 20-60 mV amplitude.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized spikes and waves.
Polyspikes and excessive theta in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The EEG findings are consistent with those of idiopathic generalized epilepsy.  In addition, there is evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  In this patient it is likely due, at least in part, to medication effect.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Generalized spikes and waves. Polyspikes and excessive theta in wakefulness.

MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background is well organized with a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and exquisitely accentuates brief bursts of 4 to 5.5 Hz spike and wave activity. The activity is not sustained, however, in HV the patient reports feeling "a little twitchy" even with a handful of discharges. The longest duration of discharges is four seconds and is at the end of HV, as the patient is becoming drowsy and testing is not performed. There is also a pair of sharp and slow wave complexes identified in the left with similar morphology, but with  a bit of localization.    Drowsiness also seems to accentuate the generalized epileptiform  activity.   Photic stimulation does not produce spike and wave activity.
HR:  72BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Generalized spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Previous EEGs were not available at tills time for comparison.  A sample of the epileptiform activity was printed out and should have been provided with this report.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.  Generalized spike and wave activity.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 29-year-old male with epilepsy since age five with
mental retardation. Last seizure two weeks ago with loss of consciousness and postictal
confusion for 15 minutes.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was
performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior
dominant rhythm. Central MU activity is seen independently from each side, but testing

theta activity identified in the midline at the frontocentral region, but a little bit more to

slowing. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 66BPM.
IMPRESSION: This is a mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
1. Infrequent theta from the frontocentral regions, right greater than left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.
These findings may be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This is a mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to 1. Infrequent theta from the frontocentral regions, right greater than left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 29 year-old, right handed male with a seizure in November during sleep. Follow-up EEG requested, but no previous EEG is available.
MEDICATIONS: Protonix, thiamin, Depakote, and Tranxene.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organized with a symmetric, reactive alpha rhythm. Central MU activity is seen, but testing is not performed to confirm this. Drowsiness and sleep are characterized by fluctuations between a drowsy and sleep pattern with persistence of eye movements into stage II sleep and very brief fragments of stage II sleep with spindles followed by arousal. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and does not significantly activate the record. Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.
HR: 60BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.
The fragmented sleep described above is reported in many different conditions and could include something as simple as a noisy background or a somewhat sleep deprived individual.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This 30-year-old right-handed male with learning
disability and a recurrent epilepsy in adulthood. Recurrent seizures
in adulthood with a childhood history of epilepsy, currently seizure
free for the last 3 months.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol 200 mg twice daily.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using
standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness background EEG is well
organized. There is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm of 30 microvolts
with small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Lambda
waves are observed in wakefulness. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous
bilateral driving. Features of drowsiness slow rolling eye movements
and an attenuation of the alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation does not
significantly activate the rhythm. In photic stimulation there is
vigorous driving. The patient appears to be awake during photic
stimulation with eye movement, but there also seems to be a vertex
sharp wave, sometimes seen prior to or following the photic
stimulation. Additional testing is not performed upon the photic
stimulation to make sure that the patient is not becoming drowsy. He
has eye movements to suggest that he is awake, and once the photic has
concluded this vertex sharp wave is not observed at another time.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. The presence of a vertex sharp wave during photic stimulation in
wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is a very unusual finding. It may be
correlated with imaging. This contrast to a previous study which was
normal.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. The presence of a vertex sharp wave during photic stimulation in
wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 47-year-old male with a history of generalized tonic-clonic seizures – last seizure about one year ago.  History of drug and alcohol abuse.  Patient was hospitalized for one week in a coma.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra and Carbatrol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is remarkable for continuous eye blink artifact with absence of the alpha rhythm as a result of same.  There is a suggestion of a posterior dominant rhythm, but again measurement of the alpha frequency could not be obtained due to the eye blink artifact.  Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal awake EEG with continuous eye blinking artifact.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The absent alpha rhythm is to be expected secondary to the continuous eye blink artifact, which can be seen in an anxious or nervous individual.  To further evaluate this patient’s epilepsy, a repeat EEG with sleep recording could be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal awake EEG with continuous eye blinking artifact.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 52 year old left handed male with a past history of epilepsy,
thought to be seizure-free since 2005 but now with episodes of incontinence.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Carbatrol.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was completed.


DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is very low voltage and includes primarily a lower voltage 5 Hz to 6 Hz beta frequency pattern with
scant amounts of delta in drowsiness and scant amounts of alpha frequency activity.
Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response which can be identified using the
software.


HR: 60bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Low voltage theta pattern.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are similar to a previous study from 2006,
with a low voltage pattern with prominent eye blink. The ability to identify the theta in the background may be due to the use of newer technologies. No epileptiform features
were seen in the last 2EEGs. Consideration for a diffuse disturbance of cerebral
function is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Low voltage theta pattern.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  52 year old left handed man with history of peri-stroke, anoxic injury, seizures, hepatitis C, who presents with increased change in mental status and EEG to rule out subclinical seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lovenox, Lorazepam
REASON FOR STUDY:  Rule out subclinical seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and EKG electrodes.  The patient was mainly lethargic during this study and some sleep was recorded.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  There is a small amount of T4 electrode artifact continuously throughout the recording period.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a low voltage diffusely slow background with no clear posterior dominant rhythm or normal frontal central beta.  Some waves forms are consistent with stage I sleep were seen, but no classic sleep architecture is clearly present.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz seen continuously.  At one point during the EEG there is stimulation and there is an increased amount of muscle artifact and frequencies improved to a theta frequency.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific with regards to etiology. No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Generalized slow waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old left handed male with prior EEGs, presents with status in the past and hypoxic injury as well as history of CVA, hep C, cirrhosis, and TBI who now is having myoclonic jerks.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Ceftriaxone, Vancomycin, Zosyn, Heparin

REASON FOR STUDY:  Rule out seizures; patient having myoclonic jerks.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was unresponsive during the EEG.  No activating procedures were performed.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:   None

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 30 microvolts.  There is no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There appears to be no clear reactivity.  During the recorded video, there appears to be some sudden jerks with the typical appearance of myoclonus; however, the EEG did not reveal any clear correlate.  No normal sleep architecture was seen.

ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 30 microvolts.

SEIZURES:   None

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized slow waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regard to etiology.  No seizures were seen.  Please note that the myoclonus observed during the video had no EEG correlate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized slow waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old left handed man with history of seizures, hepatitis C cirrhosis, traumatic brain injury, and myoclonus.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Metoprolol, Zosyn, Vancomycin, Ceftriaxone.
REASON FOR STUDY:  History of seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during coma.  No activating procedures were performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a disorganized background with no real posterior dominant rhythm or normal frontal central beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture seen.  No activating procedures were performed. During the recording the technician tries to involve the patient with verbal stimuli, as well as noxious stimuli, and ocular pressures, however, there is no change in the EEG pattern.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 1-2 Hz with an amplitude of around 10 mV seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Marked generalized slow waves.
Low amplitude.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of marked diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Marked generalized slow waves. Low amplitude.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old left handed man with history of seizures, presents with possible status epilepticus with past medical history of stroke, hepatitis C cirrhosis, traumatic brain injury, now with EEG for myoclonus versus seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Albuterol, Ipratropium, Dopamine, Ceftriaxone, Pantoprazole, Versed, Fentanyl.
REASON FOR STUDY:  History of seizures, now with myoclonic jerks.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with addition of an anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.   The patient was recorded in wakefulness.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or normal frontal central beta.  The patient did not appear to go into normal sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz with low-amplitude 20-30 mV seen continuously.
Throughout the recording, there is low-amplitude sharply contoured periodic discharges seen maximally at CZ occurring about 1 Hz with no clear clinical correlate, most consistent with CZ sharp waves and periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges.
SEIZURES:  None.
Of note, during the recording, the technician did stimulate the patient, and the patient appeared to be eye fluttering and moving rhythmically, but there is no EEG correlate to this eye movement seen or fluttering of the eyes.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slow waves.
Central PLEDs.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction and irritability in the central region which may be due to an underlying lesion or focus of irritation.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to utility.  No seizures were clearly seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Generalized slow waves. Central PLEDs.

report:

Arrhythmic delta from the left mid-temporal region.
Rare sharp waves.
Shifting arrhythmic temporal delta from either side.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 44-year-old woman with epilepsy since childhood whose last seizure was three days ago.  Her seizures are described as left-sided shaking with subsequent loss of consciousness and generalized convulsions, which is followed by postictal confusion.  Frequency of seizures is one to two times per year.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the overall background EEG is fairly well organized with a 9.5 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  There is mild excess theta seen in the background.  Occasional sharply contoured left mid-temporal delta is seen, which is accentuated in hyperventilation and post-hyperventilation.  The focal slowing is accompanied by occasional sharp waves at T1.  There is also one single right centrotemporal sharp wave identified. Photic stimulation elicits brief, symmetric driving.  Throughout the tracing, there is artifact originating from impedance issues at the T3 electrodes.
HR:  87 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild excess theta.
Occasional left mid-temporal focal slowing with sharp waves.
One single right centrotemporal sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial or localization-related mechanism for epilepsy in this patient.  The technical problems seen in this record due to impedance issues at the P3 electrode, may have partially obscured important references, therefore, obscuring underlying sharp waves, a repeat study would be valuable. Correlation with neuroimaging would also be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Mild excess theta. Occasional left mid-temporal focal slowing with sharp waves. One single right centrotemporal sharp wave.

report:

report:

report:

Frontally predominant intermittent rhythmic delta.
Excess theta.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  45-year-old male with leg weakness, epilepsy, sarcoid, vena cava syndrome , renal failure , multiple strokes. Left leg weakness causing falls, but no current seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin
INTRODUCTION :  Digital video EEG is performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. There is no photic stimulation nor hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is an 11 hertz, 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage , frontocentral beta activity. Occasional shifting arrhythmic delta activity in a transition from sleep in either hemisphere.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 37-year-old male with epilepsy, head trauma, alcohol and cocaine abuse found with right frontal contusion.  This happened on ________????
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Ativan, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is described as responsive to stimuli.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is somewhat arousable.  The overall background is rich in beta frequency activity, particularly in the frontal regions.  The patient is wearing a hard collar with multiple apparatus on the face, neck, and scalp.  Spontaneous arousals are associated with more of a pattern of diffuse beta.  Head-rocking artifact is picked up in the posterior scalp electrodes.  Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting response with an increase in beta and theta.  There are rare asymmetries with a bit higher amplitude rhythmic theta in the right or frontal regions.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background primarily with a pattern rich in beta frequency activity, but with smaller amounts of theta and alpha frequency activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The reactivity and variability are positive prognostic features.  Medications that produce beta may account for the pattern described above in this individual who is responsive to external stimuli.  There are no epileptiform features identified in this record, and the focal frontal features are subtle.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Replacement of normal background primarily with a pattern rich in beta frequency activity, but with smaller amounts of theta and alpha frequency activity.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman with two first-ever seizures occurring during sleep with postictal confusion, but no incontinence.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized for an adult of this age with a symmetric, reactive 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Features of drowsiness include vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.
Towards the close of the record, as the patient is in stage II sleep and photic stimulation begins, there is some artifact but there are also some pairs of suspicious underlying left centrotemporal sharp waves of low amplitude and discrete, but appear to be interrupting the background.  The patient otherwise remains in stage II sleep during photic. Low voltage left temporal sharp waves are seen only in this section of the record, and almost seem to have an electropositivity between T3 and F7, but do appear to have otherwise a clear field in the left centrotemporal and posteriotemporal regions.
HR:  70 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Unusual but abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Suspicious left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Additional EEG recording with special electrodes or special techniques may be helpful to more clearly evaluate the underlying dipole that produces this activity and to be more certain that it is not artifactual in nature.  Correlation with imaging may also be valuable for this adult with new onset seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Unusual but abnormal EEG due to 1.Suspicious left temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 62-year-old male with epilepsy since age 17 with recurrent seizures one year ago, but none recalled by the patient for the last year.  He has been living in a nursing home.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Neurontin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.  At that time, a low voltage 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm is identified bilaterally.  Despite movement artifact, there is a glimpse of a left mid-to-anterior temporal region in HV.  This is followed by a drowsy pattern at which point there is some subtle focal slowing discernable in the left anteriotemporal region.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, he begins to snore, again producing a fair amount of artifact.  Other features of sleep include some vertex activity.   In sleep, well-defined left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave complexes are identified.  The patient remains asleep during photic stimulation, with features of stage II sleep and spindles, but no clear driving.  In this sleep state, during HV, the left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave complexes are better defined and then the patient briefly awakens towards the end of HV.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave activity.
Left anteriotemporal focal slowing.
Low voltage, somewhat slow background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Despite the technical challenges described above, this EEG is similar to a previous record with focal temporal epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave activity. Left anteriotemporal focal slowing. Low voltage, somewhat slow background.

report:

MEDICATIONS: Tegretol and Zoloft.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is remarkable for an intrahemispheric asymmetry with a 10 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm on the right, sometimes disrupted on the left.  In addition, in the right hemisphere, there is low voltage frontocentral mixed theta and delta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing an increase in the amplitude from the left, as well as one or two bursts of generalized paroxysmal slowing.
Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response.
HR:  92 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This EEG supports a structural abnormality on the right involving both gray and white matter.  Comparison with previous studies may be valuable in terms of the search for epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.

report:
History:	34 year old female with history of seizures since childhood.  She reportedly had at
least 2 seizures in the last week.
Medications:	Hydrochlorothiazide, Tegretol, zoloft, Ambien
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
The posterior dominant rhythm consists of well formed and modulated 9 Hz alpha activity that
attenuates with eye opening.  PDR is better formed and modulated over the left.  There is an
anterior-to-posterior frequency-amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes
anteriorly.  During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely,
followed by symmetric vertex waves.
There is continuous interhemispheric voltage asymmetry with lower voltages over the right.
Additionally, there is paucity of faster frequencies over the right hemisphere, especially over the
anterior and median quadrants.  Semi-rhythmic sharply contoured delta activity at 1-1.25 Hz is
observed over the right frontotemporal region during and following hyperventilation.  Occasional
right frontotemporal sharp waves are noted.  Maximal scalp negativity occurs over F8, T2, Fp2 and
F4 electrodes.  These discharges become more apparent during photic stimulation.  No clear
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) produces semi-rhythmic sharply
contoured right frontotemporal delta activity and accentuates right frontotemporal sharp waves.
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, continuous, right hemispheric, mild-to-moderate, especially over
Attenuation, continuous, mild, right hemispheric
Sharp waves, occasional, right frontotemporal, accentuated by photic stimulation
Other, right frontotemporal, focal semi-rhythmic delta is seen with photic stimulation
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 24-minute EEG due to mild-to-moderate right
hemispheric slowing that is most pronounced over the anterior and middle quadrants and occasional
right frontotemporal epileptiform discharges. Focal slowing and voltage attenuation over the right
is suggestive of focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology.  A potential epileptogenic
focus emanates from the right frontotemporal region.  Given accentuation of epileptiform
discharges and focal slowing with photic stimulation, this EEG is suggestive of photosensitive
seizures.  Please correlate clinically electrographic seizures are captured.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman followed at [Hospital] with the diagnosis of epilepsy and three tonic-clonic seizures per month, all occurring out of sleep.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10.5 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is some single electrode artifact picked up in the right frontotemporal electrodes, but there is an abnormality identified in this EEG identifiable after the electrodes are attended to. This includes rhythmic focal slowing from the right temporal regions, which is at times sustained and sharply contoured at the end of HV and early drowsiness.  In addition, using bipolar and average reference electrodes, there are two pairs of subtle frontotemporal sharp waves.  One has generous representation at Fp2, F4, and T4, as well as F8 and T4.  The other is clearly F8 and T4.  Other features of drowsiness include vertex waves and an increase in background beta.  Photic stimulation is remarkable for eliciting an alerting response and some driving bilaterally.  The patient is drifting in and out of stage II sleep in photic stimulation.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Right temporal focal slowing clearly accentuated by hyperventilation.
Subtle underlying pairs of right frontotemporal/frontocentral sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a structural or functional mechanism for this patient’s epilepsy and may be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Right temporal focal slowing clearly accentuated by hyperventilation. Subtle underlying pairs of right frontotemporal/frontocentral sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 57 year old right handed male with status epilepticus earlier this morning status post 10 mg of Ativan, Dilantin, and Keppra. History of cervical myelopathy. Intubated and paralyzed prior to the EEG.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra, Ativan, Etomidate, Fentanyl, Versed, ROCURONIUM
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is starting to emerge from paralysis and demonstrates stiffening and movements.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the patient is a bit quieter. Activity demonstrates a slow pattern with some rhythmic mixed theta and delta on the left with a lower voltage, slower, a bit more suppressed pattern on the right, particularly in the temporal regions.
Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting with an increase in muscle as well as alpha and theta frequency activity. During the EEG, the patient starts to wake up, move around, and cough. After this, there is a more alert pattern with more theta frequency and alpha frequency activity from the left, but the right remains quite slow. By the end of the record in this very sharply contoured record, there was a suggestion of underlying sharp activity versus part of the fast activity at F3. In addition, more sharply contoured slowing is seen at T4-T6.
HR: 84 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Nearly continuous focal slowing on the right hemisphere.
2. Occasional T4-T6 sharps and question F3 sharps as well.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe, bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function as would be expected following the use of sedative, hypnotic medications. The focal slowing and rare sharp waves on the right are compatible with past right temporal hemorrhage. Additional evaluation of this patient's cerebral function may be needed. Ongoing EEG monitoring was undertaken to make sure no additional seizures occurred.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Nearly continuous focal slowing on the right hemisphere. 2. Occasional T4-T6 sharps and question F3 sharps as well.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 57 year old right handed male admitted with 4 seizures, alcohol abuse, past history of intracerebral hemorrhage, hepatitis C, stroke, and hypertension.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Tylenol

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is poorly responsive.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10Hz alpha rhythm identified on the left. Faster frequency activity is attenuated on the right. The patient is conversant with the tech. This patient has an event during the EEG. The event occurs at 10:08 a.m. It is characterized by staring, jerking of the head from side to side. The EEG is remarkable for some sharp waves and some motion artifacts. The sharp waves are seen in the right frontocentral region. There is significant muscle activity. The patient is conversant during the spell. No postictal slowing is noted. Photic stimulation elicits a brief driving response on the left.

HR: 78 bpm

IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Focal slowing from the right.
2. An event during the EEG without impairment of awareness. Although there is some artifact, there are some discharges in the same region as the patient's sharp waves. While the event might not be considered a simple partial or a complex partial seizure, the motor activity observed may be linked to the epileptiform activity elicited from the right frontocentral region which could have produced the features described above.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Focal slowing from the right

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old female with epilepsy and dizziness.  No other information is available.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Dilantin, and Buspirone.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient has an event during the EEG. Hyperventilation is performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Although the patient is markedly drowsy throughout much of the record, there is a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta and theta.  Hyperventilation is performed with fair effort, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.  At the end of hyperventilation, the patient has a single episode of both shoulders jerking at 11:37:07.  Slowly, at 11:53, she starts to have rocking of the head from side to side and then has rocking from side to side with alternating movements of the hands, with hands coming up and going down and then head rocking from side to side.  During this event, although there is some movement artifact, the EEG otherwise demonstrates an awake pattern.  The technologist interacts with the patient during the event giving her a code word.  The patient has multiple different behaviors during this episode including brief hyperextension of the back and then slow rocking from side to side.
Towards the end of the behavior, the tech uses a nasal tickle.  The patient looks apprehensive and at one point turns away just briefly, but doesn’t move substantially.  She does blink to threat during the event, and towards the end of the event, seems upset or angry and is staring away from the direction of the technologist.  As the technologist moves around the room, however, the patient can be seen to track the tech with her eyes.  After the event is over, the patient tells the tech that the only thing she can remember is that her name is [patient’s name].
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Although the patient was initially quite drowsy, there is no epileptiform activity.  This patient had a complex and prolonged behavioral event without EEG change.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:

record.  In comparison to a previous record, both studies show normal cerebral activity, but no behavioral events were recorded today.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	A 53-year-old with depression, anxiety and epilepsy. History of nonepileptic seizures. The patient has had episodes where she could hear others talking but could not respond, episodes where she feels shaky. Typically has increased seizures around health care providers.

INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This patient's previous EEGs were not available for comparison today. This is a 1-hour EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 4-year-old male with a one-year history of epilepsy; last seizure three weeks ago with foaming at the mouth. History of staring spells, generalized shaking lasting two to three minutes.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was performed.   This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well enough organized for age with a posterior dominant rhythm averaging 6 Hz, sometimes somewhat faster, reaching amplitudes up to 100 uV.  Features of drowsiness include hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing.  Vertex waves are identified with brief sleep epochs and then spontaneous arousals. Hyperventilation produces rhythmic slowing.
Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. Although there are multiple episodes of hypersynchronous rhythmic 5 Hz activity, the static can be re-reviewed and is without epileptiform activity and is simply characteristic of a prominent hypnagogic hypersynchrony.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Additional EEG recording including capturing more extended sleep may be important to characterize this child’s epilepsy if previous EEGs have not done so.  Photic stimulation may also be employed.  In comparison to previous EEGs, this study was of better quality technically, but neither studies identified epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 5-year-old male with epilepsy admitted on the 16th after he fell down the stairs and had a convulsion and a laceration on his cheek lasting five minutes.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Tylenol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.  This is this child’s third EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is a 6.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive.  There are portions of the record when the child is awake when the background is appropriately organized for age.
The major abnormalities in this record include complex epileptiform activity, which can be best viewed at fast paper speed of six seconds per page and/or average reference.  These include spike and slow wave complexes, which are high in amplitude and sometimes seem almost electropositive in the mid-temporal region, but in most of the montages are maximum at C3.  They are variable with some having a much more generous field of spread to the frontocentral region or left hemisphere and others more restricted.  They are picked up by volume conduction in the contralateral hemisphere.  In addition, there are some generalized frontally predominant spike and slow wave discharges, some of which are 3.5 to 4 Hz, but which are slightly irregular.  As the child drifts off to sleep, marked background slowing is observed and prominent, high amplitude slow spike and wave complexes are identified.  These are picked up in the frontocentral region, but more so on the left.
As the child drifts off to sleep, he is lying on his side, away from the camera and towards his mother.  Initially, he seems to have jerking forward of the head.  Subsequently, he seems almost to be having a salaam-like seizure as he drifts off to sleep, jerking towards his mother with his arms coming up a little bit.  This seems to elicit an arousal from sleep.  The epileptiform activity is high in amplitude, but some sections of the sleep record seem to demonstrate a sleep pattern that is remarkable for prominent attenuation of the typical morphologies in sleep with this high amplitude spike and slow wave pathology, most prominent in the frontal regions and again with an unusual field but with more of a predominance to the left hemisphere.  The child does fall off to sleep at 12:51.
HR:  114 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Prominent epileptiform activity with complex epileptiform activity, slow spike and wave activity, and focal spike and slow wave activity, but activity that on the whole raises concerns about a process involving the left hemisphere.
Concerns that the background activity in sleep is slower than expected particularly in the frontocentral regions, left greater than right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings must be correlated with imaging and clinical exam at this juncture.  They differ from the two previous EEGs, which were not successful in identifying epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Prominent epileptiform activity with complex epileptiform activity, slow spike and wave activity, and focal spike and slow wave activity, but activity that on the whole raises concerns about a process involving the left hemisphere. Concerns that the background activity in sleep is slower than expected particularly in the frontocentral regions, left greater than right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old woman with recent onset epilepsy and seizures, which often can be eliminated by the patient with reassurance.  The patient had six seizures after she ran out of her Effexor.  Patient had a spell immediately upon cessation of the EEG characterized by staring and blinking.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Effexor, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is awake.  There is a 9 to 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a fair amount of eye artifact.   Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and does elicit some left anteriotemporal sharp and slow wave complexes in association with hyperventilation. Following hyperventilation, the patient becomes somewhat drowsy and there is a small amount of slowing in the left mid-temporal region in this somewhat drowsy pattern.  There is also a high amplitude left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave complex.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is a left anteriotemporal spike component, but this has a bifrontal field.  This activity can be reviewed with other montages where again it seems to be primarily left temporal with some spread into the eye movement channel.  It is prominent with almost a focal spike and wave component as the patient becomes drowsy and reaches stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is in stage II sleep and does not significantly activate the record.  The record ends at 13:45 and the seizure is not captured on the video or the EEG.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for this individual due to:
Focal, high amplitude spike and slow wave activity identified from the left anteriotemporal region with almost a focal spike and wave component.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features differ significantly from previous EEGs and suggests that additional recording and additional evaluation is warranted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for this individual due to Focal, high amplitude spike and slow wave activity identified from the left anteriotemporal region with almost a focal spike and wave component.

report:
:
History:	75 year old man with a history of seizures.  Patient was seizure-free until recently,
but in the last month he had 2 reported generalized convulsions.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by low voltage 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Fast alpha variant is present.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity
is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates,
and bursts of ~5 Hz monomorphic sharply contoured diffuse stereotyped theta activity appears.  This
activity becomes more prominent as drowsiness deepens.  No clear stage II sleep architecture is
Frequent polymorphic theta and delta activity is noted over the right anterior temporal region,
increasing in frequency during drowsiness.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce additional abnormalities.
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, frequent, right temporal, anterior, mild-to-moderate
No stage 2 sleep
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 25-minute EEG due to frequent mild-to-moderate focal
slowing in the right anterior temporal region.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral
dysfunction, which is etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  The lack of
epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 25-minute EEG due to frequent mild-to-moderate focal
slowing in the right anterior temporal region.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral
dysfunction, which is etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  The lack of
epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
﻿CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old male with epilepsy following head trauma at age six when he was run over by a car.  Patient seizure-free since age 13, now with twitching of the limbs lasting for 20 seconds.  Symptoms start and stop and then move up and down the limbs.  They are not associated with loss of consciousness.

MEDICATIONS:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is limited maximal wakefulness with a well-defined alpha rhythm.  The alpha frequency is 12 Hz, 30 to 50 uV and is slightly higher amplitude on the left compared to the right.  Much of the record includes drowsiness or sleep with slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  In the transition to sleep, there is a drowsy pattern with rhythmic theta, which is identified bilaterally and is symmetric.  There is a slight amplitude asymmetry on some occasions as slowing develops in the record, with again slightly higher amplitude slowing from the left compared to the right.  Vertex waves in stage I sleep are symmetric.  POSTS are identified bilaterally.

Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in background beta.  Notably, at baseline, the patient’s heart rate is 72 BPM and irregular.  In hyperventilation, the heart rate becomes more irregular, increasing to 96 BPM and is associated with the feeling of light-headedness and a twitchy feeling.  The twitchy feeling is identified at 13:51.  No epileptiform features are identified at that time, although there is an increase in background beta.

Photic stimulation elicits a driving response bilaterally.  The driving response is quite vigorous, but in the slower frequency flash stimuli, it is higher amplitude and more prominent from the left compared to the right.

HR:  72 BPM, irregular.

IMPRESSION: Given the presence of an alpha asymmetry and the amplitude asymmetry, as well as the photic asymmetry, this is a mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. The amplitude asymmetry comparing the left to the right and the slightly asymmetric photic stimulation.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  In this individual with a history of childhood head trauma, these findings should be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Given the presence of an alpha asymmetry and the amplitude asymmetry, as well as the photic asymmetry, this is a mildly abnormal EEG due to 1. The amplitude asymmetry comparing the left to the right and the slightly asymmetric photic stimulation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old male with possible posttraumatic epilepsy.  Patient has episodes when he falls asleep with of a feeling of hearing his blood rushing to the head with severe dizziness and tachycardia.  Last episode was this morning.  Patient states that he if catches it, he can stop it.  History of head trauma at age 6 with seizures, with last seizure at age 13.  This patient did experience another episode, as was seen in a previous EEG, with the feeling of tachycardia.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. No clinical symptoms were reported during this EEG. The patient is known to have a right skull defect.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 30 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. In wakefulness, there is a small intrahemispheric asymmetry with accentuation of fast activity in the right frontocentral region compared to the left.  This is compatible with a breach rhythm.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  During hyperventilation, the background EEG demonstrates an awake pattern with an increase in the amplitude and a small increase in theta.  Notably, in hyperventilation, the heart rate increases from 70 to 90 BPM.  The patient reports experiencing the typical symptoms of one of his events.
Photic stimulation is remarkable for a driving response.  The patient’s breach rhythm is somewhat more prominent during photic.
HR:  70 to 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In view of the breach rhythm, which is a manifestation of a previous skull defect, the amplitude asymmetries and the beta asymmetries are anticipated findings.  As was seen in a previous EEG, the patient again felt tachycardic during hyperventilation and again demonstrated an increase in heart rate.
Additional, neurocardiac monitoring may be helpful to further characterize his spells.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 62-year-old male with hypothyroidism, benign prostatic hypertrophy, and carpal tunnel syndrome bilaterally who presents with an episode of syncope and inability to communicate several minutes afterwards, but is able to comprehend.
MEDICATIONS: Synthroid, Cardura, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  Throughout the record, there is unusual eye movement artifact, with very high amplitude eye artifact and somewhat asymmetric eye movements. These movements are lower amplitude on the right side, notably at the F8 lead.  The activity from the left temporal area also seems to be of greater amplitude.  There is also a suspicion of delta activity at F7 to T3.  Features of drowsiness include wicket activity, slow rolling eye movements, and an increase in beta.  Vertex waves are seen in stage I sleep.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in the amplitude of the background.   Photic stimulation elicits minimal driving.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
The presence of delta in the left frontotemporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In view of the asymmetric eye movement artifact described above, this EEG should be repeated capturing stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to The presence of delta in the left frontotemporal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 62-year-old woman evaluated for speech arrest associated with syncope, prolonged, sleep-deprived video EEG.
MEDICATIONS: Cardura, aspirin, Synthroid.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.  Previous EEGs are not available for comparison. This is a one-hour EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is awake with a symmetric, reactive posterior dominant rhythm.   Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing synchronous bursts of slowing seen primarily in the temporal regions.   Features of drowsiness include background slowing followed by vertex waves, spindles, and K complexes in stage II sleep.  Wicket activity is seen in the transition to and from deeper stages of sleep.   Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  50 to 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Temporal wicket is a normal finding.  No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If this patient experiences additional events, additional recording capturing an event may be of use.  Please compare to prior EEGs
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 12-year-old male with new onset seizures on 07/24/06 with loss of consciousness and incontinence of urine.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG and two channels of muscle monitoring. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric, continuous, and fairly well organized for age.  There is a 10 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm, which is attenuated with eyes opened. There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, which transiently increases the slow activity of theta in the frontocentral region and returns back to baseline within one minute in post-hyperventilation. Photic stimulation elicits driving.  Following photic stimulation, POSTS are seen indicating light sleep, but no abnormal discharges were identified.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The POSTS observed in this tracing is a normal variant.  The normal developmental milestones have been met. Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 7-year-old female with uncontrolled tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  The patient is crying.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In apparent wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow for a child of this age with rhythmic 3 to 5 Hz activity and a posterior dominant rhythm, which is more typically on the order of 3 Hz, as well as a bit more background slowing than one would expect.  There are rare, high amplitude left frontocentral spike and slow wave complexes. Features of drowsiness include hypersynchronous slowing.  At times, there are more subtle underlying sharp waves from the left centrotemporal region.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to:
Background slowing.
Rare left frontocentral spike and slow wave complexes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The background slowing is a non-specific finding and can be seen in a postictal state, although the child does appear awake and quite interactive.  The left frontocentral spike and slow wave activity is rare, but is high amplitude and well defined.  Correlation with imaging and clinical history may be valuable.  In addition, there is a suggestion of some underlying sharp activity from the left temporal region and ongoing evaluation of that potential underlying focus may also be appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to Background slowing. Rare left frontocentral spike and slow wave complexes.

report:

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Intermittent disorganization and generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features are non-specific.  In a subject of this age, this may be due to an underlying toxic or metabolic encephalopathy or postictal state.   No epileptiform features were seen.

report:

report:

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is a symmetric continuous but superimposed on excessive amounts of movement artifact. Photic stimulation did not create driving. No epileptiform discharges were seen in this tracing.
Heart rate is 54 BPM.

report:

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm, with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  This patient demonstrates intermittent head rocking from side to side, which produces some artifact.  Photic stimulation seems to elicit this patient’s tendency to rock her head from side to side. report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 57-year-old, right-handed woman with cerebellar degeneration, myoclonus, and hepatic cirrhosis with tremor, confusion, and encephalopathy.
MEDICATIONS: Methylprednisolone, methadone, Fentanyl.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat poorly organized.  There is an 8 to 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm in a background with excess background theta.  There is a great deal of muscle and movement artifact and, in fact, the muscle is present even into sleep.  Underlying this, there is some intermittent arrhythmic delta activity sometimes sharply contoured in the left temporal region.  Vertex waves and spindles are seen in stage II sleep, but there remains a fair amount of muscle in sleep.  Hyperventilation is performed with poor effort, but does seem to produce both generalized rhythmic frontal slowing, as well as accentuating some of the focal slowing from the left.  Photic stimulation elicits scant bilateral driving.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing and poor organization.
Superimposed focal slowing from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record, however, given the amount of muscle artifact noted in the background, if epileptiform activity is of importance, a repeat sleep record may be necessary.  No periodic changes were seen.  In this individual who was evaluated for Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, not all individuals demonstrate the characteristic pseudoperiodic findings initially and additional studies over a 12 week period may be necessary.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing and poor organization. Superimposed focal slowing from the left.

report:

Left anteriotemporal spike.
Arrhythmic delta, left more than right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy and supports the given history of herpes encephalitis.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left anteriotemporal spike. Arrhythmic delta, left more than right.

report:
History:	24 year old man who presents with events concerning for seizures.
Medications:	Versed this morning in the ED.
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, lethargic
Description:
During very brief wakefulness the background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm,
which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present,
maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  Excess diffuse admixed 50-75 uV, 5-7Hz activity is present
during very brief wakefulness.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity,
frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes
intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and
symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
Hyperventilation is not performed.
Summary of Findings:
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL briefly awake and mostly asleep 23-minute portable EEG due to mild
diffuse slowing. This finding is indicative of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically
nonspecific, but in this patient is at least partially secondary to excessive drowsiness.  The lack of
epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL briefly awake and mostly asleep 23-minute portable EEG due to mild
diffuse slowing. This finding is indicative of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically
nonspecific, but in this patient is at least partially secondary to excessive drowsiness.  The lack of
epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old male with tonic-clonic seizures since age
18, last seizure two weeks ago.  Seizures occur two to three times per month.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a well-organized, 10 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits scant bilateral driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.   Additional recording capturing deeper stages of sleep may be valuable to identify epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 32-year-old policewoman with a history of infrequent
seizures since age 16. Last seizure two weeks ago described as an out-of-body
experience with mild shaking of the extremities and head followed by confusion and
sleepiness. Patient can hear, but cannot verbalize. In addition to speech problems, the
patient has a history of migraines with increased frequency recently.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation were performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is
reasonably well organized with a 9.5 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm. There is a
scant amount of background theta. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort,
producing a bit more theta, slightly more so on the left, with rare bursts of sharply
contoured slowing from the left seen at the close of hyperventilation. As the patient
becomes drowsy, there are occasional bursts of higher amplitude rhythmic, sharply
contoured theta from the left temporal region appearing in brief bursts. Photic
stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 60BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Left temporal, sharply contoured theta and underlying focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Tins EEG raises concerns regarding a localization related
mechanism for epilepsy. Comparison with previous EEGs from childhood and/or
recording may be helpful.
Director, EEG Lab
I have reviewed the study and concur with this report.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Left temporal, sharply contoured theta and underlying focal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 33 year-old police woman with 2 complex partial seizures on
August 23, 2008. The reports an aura before both of them.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in Jab using standard 10-20 system
of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are
performed. This is an awake and a sleep record for a sleep deprived individual.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 hertz, 40 UV/mm
posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta
activity. Hyperventilation does not activate the record, but she starts to drift into stage 2
sleep during the close of hyperventilation. Features of stage 2 sleep include vertex
waves, spindles. In addition, snore arousals are observed. Photic stimulation elicits
scant bilateral driving.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In contrast to previous EEGs, no epileptiform features are
observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 39-year-old woman with epilepsy, now with complaint of impaired verbal memory.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a technically acceptable EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  The patient transitioned between wakefulness and sleep with an increase in beta during sleep.
In hyperventilation and in the transition to sleep, there is subtle, underlying focal slowing noted from the left temporal region with scant temporal theta.
Photic stimulation elicited a bilateral driving response.
By the close of the record, the patient is transitioning in and out of stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and spindles as well as snore artifact.
Heart rate 84 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to:
subtle left temporal focal slowing, primarily seen in drowsiness or hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is 5th EEG for this patient.  A previous study in 2007 identified similar findings.  No sharp waves or spikes have been seen in any of the EEGs.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to subtle left temporal focal slowing, primarily seen in drowsiness or hyperventilation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 46-year-old HIV-positive male with epilepsy. History
of previous trauma with rare clusters of seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Multiple retrovirals, Lamictal 600 mg Q D, Gabapentin 1800 mg Q D,
and Lipitor.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9Hz, 40 uV posterior
dominant rhythm and a scant amount of background theta. Subtle focal slowing is seen from the right hemisphere, particularly in the temporal region. As the patient becomes drowsy, it is noted that there is a subtle increase in fast activity from the right centrotemporal region and rare, discrete right centrotemporal sharp waves. Vertex waves are noted in stage I sleep. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is relatively drowsy, but does elicit some driving.
HR: 60BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Subtle focal slowing and sharp waves from the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The beta asymmetry raises the possibility of a breach.
These findings have been seen in previous EEGs. The overall background demonstrates less in the way of background slowing and disorganization than previous studies, and the sharp waves at this time are rare.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Subtle focal slowing and sharp waves from the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 47 year-old with post-traumatic epilepsy and HIV disease.
Infrequent, but significant seizures sometimes requiring hospitalization.
MEDICATIONS: Gabapentin, Lamictal, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in lab using standard 10-20 system
of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are
performed. Previous studies are not available today for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 hertz alpha rhythm
with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Early in drowsiness, there
is slowing in the background, but when the patient is maximally awake, the EEG is
appropriately organized. Hyperventilation is performed early in the record producing an
increase in theta. Vertex waves are observed in stage 1 sleep. Vertex waves and
spindles are observed in stage 2 sleep. Arousals from sleep are noted. Photic
stimulation is performed while the patient is somewhat drowsy and drops into stage 2
sleep, but there is a brief driving response.
HR: 55 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed today. In
comparison with previous EEG is important in terms of characterizing this individual's
epileptiform activity. In the context of HIV disease, there is no background slowing
today. In contrast to 4 prior EEG's no sharp waves (Right temporal) were observed
today.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
