report:
CLINICAL  HISTORY: This  is a 54-year-old  male of unknown  handedness with epilepsy, alcohol abuse, and AED non-compliance, admitted on the i" with a fever and seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement  with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation  was performed.   This is an awake and drowsy record. The patient is intermittently agitated and confused.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is low-to-medium amplitude with a
10 Hz alpha rhythm, generous beta activity and occasional bursts of frontal delta. Features of
drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements.    A seizure emanating from the left anterior temporal   region is identified at 9:35:56 lasting 44 seconds.   The patient is noted to shift with eye blinking.  There are some automatisms and blinking associated with this.   The seizure ends abruptly with little in the way of postictal change other than more of a low voltage beta pattern.  The activity from the left temporal region is primarily theta frequency.  After the seizure ends, the patient starts to reach purposefully with his right.
The postictal recording is remarkable for occasional shifting arrhythmic delta, a bit more remarkable from the left frontal region than the right.
Photic stimulation does not activate the record. HR:  120BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1 .     A left anterior temporal focal seizure.
2.   Intermittent left temporal focal slowing.
3.   Excess beta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Testing was not performed during the seizure, but it did appear to be clinically significant with some automatisms, which may have been difficult to distinguish in this confused adult.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1 .     A left anterior temporal focal seizure. 2.   Intermittent left temporal focal slowing. 3.   Excess beta.

report:
History:	63 year old man with a history of seizures. His PMH is also notable for head trauma, a prior alcohol and drug abuse, renal dysfunction.
Medications:	Keppra, sertraline Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:		International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy, photic

Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions. During drowsiness, bitemporal theta and delta activity become prominent. This activity then progresses to diffuse bursts of of somewhat rhythmic delta activity.
No clear focal slowing is present. No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed. Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.

Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges No stage 2 sleep
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake and drowsy. No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded. If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake and drowsy. No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded. If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 47-year-old woman status post meningioma resection in 2008.  The patient has been suffering from insomnia, had a seizure following the 4th of July with some alcohol ingestion.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal, Ativan and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Technical criteria was satisfactory.  She has a breach rhythm in the right frontocentral region.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Generous, frontocentral beta activity was noted.  A breach rhythm was noted in the right frontocentral region with accentuation of beta activity and some underlying, subtle focal delta.
Hyperventilation was performed early in the recording producing rhythmic frontal theta bilaterally.
Hyperventilation was followed by drowsiness with an increase in beta, particularly in the region with a breach and some shifting slowing primarily in the right central region.  Stage 2 sleep includes spindles, POSTS and some vertex waves and is a bit more symmetric.  The patient transitioned in and out of awake and drowsy state.  There is a bit of muscle or snoring artifact noted as well.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response, which was better developed on the left compared to the right.
Heart rate 78 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing in the right central region, noted primarily in drowsiness.
Asymmetric driving response.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are congruent with the previous right hemispheric resection.  The breach rhythm with the prominent accentuation of the beta activity is an anticipated finding, particularly for a patient receiving benzodiazepine.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to Focal slowing in the right central region, noted primarily in drowsiness. Asymmetric driving response.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old woman with recurrent meningioma, seizure-free since December 2013.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal, topiramate, Ativan, Ditropan.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  The patient is noted to have a right frontal craniotomy defect.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes symmetric reactive 10 Hz alpha rhythm of 30 microvolts.  Frequent eye blink artifact is noted.  There is also some craniotomy artifact noted in the right frontal region which appears a bit more prominently in hyperventilation.  Hyperventilation does not otherwise activate the record.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta.  Deeper stages of sleep were not sustained.
Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response which is initially a little bit more vigorous on the left at lower frequencies, symmetric and at higher frequencies.
Heart rate 78 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The artifact from craniotomy defect is not considered a part of cerebral pathology.  No epileptiform features were noted.  In comparison to a previous study in 2013, right frontal focal slowing was not noted.  The 2007 EEGs were not available for comparison.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:
A 44-year-old left-handed male with 3 tonoclonic
seizures characterized by focal twitching, left arm shaking and then tonoclonic activity.
MEDICATIONS: 	Dilantin, insulin, others.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG is performed in lab using 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION  OF THE RECORD: 	Background EEG in wakefulness is somewhat slow with excess background theta. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing bursts of frontally predominant slowing; however, some of this is irregular with more irregular, sharply contoured signs on the right hemisphere with bursts lasting up to 5 seconds. The drowsy pattern demonstrates an increase in background slowing. In addition, more rhythmic, right frontal delta with suspicious underlying right frontal sharp waves are seen in brief bursts in the transition to drowsiness. Photic stimulation elicits
both photoelectric artifact and some driving.
HR: 	100 BPM.
IMPRESSION: 	Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Generalized background slowing.
2. 	Superimposed bursts of paroxysmal frontal delta much more prominent from the right hemisphere with an underlying right frontal sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a localization related mechanism for epilepsy. The focal findings may be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Generalized background slowing. 2. Superimposed bursts of paroxysmal frontal delta much more prominent from the right hemisphere with an underlying right frontal sharp wave.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	45 year-old gentleman with brain surgery for resection of tumor on the right, status post radiation now with 1-2 seizures per month, tonic, clonic with left focal facial twitching, left arm shaking then generalized tonic clonic activity with confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lipitor, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. A right craniotomy defect is observed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 hertz, symmetric active alpha rhythm. There is an amplitude asymmetry with higher amplitude activity on the right compared to the left. The patient drops into drowsiness with rhythmic theta
followed by vertex waves. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, but the
patient seems to be a bit drowsy. Immediately after hyperventilation, he drifts into stage
2 sleep with spontaneous K complexes and spindles. POST are observed. Although he has a stout neck, there is little in the way of snore artifact observed. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 	78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   Despite the craniotomy defect and the history of ongoing epilepsy, there are no focal nor epileptiform features observed. Additional evaluation looking for possible causes of his seizures is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   39 year-old woman with cavernous hemangioma, seizure free for the last three years.
MEDICATIONS:   Tegretol
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in lab using standard 10-20 system
of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG is well organized with 10Hz alpha rhythm.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In hyperventilation and brief drowsiness, there is occasional, subtle, focal slowing in the
left mid temporal region.  That focal slowing is more prominent in hyperventilation than it is in the drowsy state with somewhat rhythmic mixed state in the left mid temporal region.  Features of stage 2 sleep include vertex, alpha, K complexes and spindles.
The patient is drowsy during photic stimulation.  Drifting into stage 1 sleep, but there is a
brief driving response.
HR: 	60 bpm
IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 		Focal slowing observed primarily in hyperventilation but also seen intermittently in drowsiness with some rhythmic, sharply contoured slowing in the left mid temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   Focal slowing is a bit anterior to the cavernous hemangioma.  It supports structural function abnormality and can be seen in the context of an underlying seizures disorder.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to 1. Focal slowing observed primarily in hyperventilation but also seen intermittently in drowsiness with some rhythmic, sharply contoured slowing in the left mid temporal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	This was a 35-year-old, right handed female, health care worker with new onset of episodes of generalized shaking. The patient could feel her body shake at the beginning of the episodes. Afterwards, she felt quite drained and had diffuse body soreness. The patient's typical seizures involved head turning and body twisting to the right. The patient may experience black spots in her eyes before the spells.
MEDICATIONS: 	Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation  and photic stimulation were completed. The patient experienced one of her typical spells during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	In wakefulness, there was a generous amount of background beta and a small of background theta. Hyperventilation was performed early on in the record producing increase in theta.
Following hyperventilation,  the patient began to have an episode of eye fluttering. The eye flutter began at 11:10:17. This gradually moved on towards one of her typical spells. The spell began at 11:10:35. The patient arched her back, stiffened and demonstrated generalized shaking. The spell was over by 11:11:11 so the total duration was approximately 40 seconds. No post
ictal slowing was identified. The patient recalled that the tech asked her a word but did not recall what the word was. Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
HR: 84   BPM.
IMPRESSION: 	Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess beta.
2. Mild excess theta.
. '
3. Behavioral event without clear EEG change and without post ictal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: 	The absence of an EEG signature as well as the absence of a post ictal state raised concerns that the behaviors recorded were not ictal in nature.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Excess beta. 2. Mild excess theta. . '
3. Behavioral event without clear EEG change and without post ictal slowing.

10 Hz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral

report:
History:	58 year old woman with a reported history of seizures since -1985. Medications:	Topamax
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min
Technique:		International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Background voltages are low.  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of low voltage beta activity that attenuates with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV,  18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  The majority of the background consists of low amplitude diffuse beta activity.   During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.   During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.   Frequent positive sharp waves occur bilaterally and independently in the occipital regions during drowsiness  and light sleep.
Occasional low voltage sharp waves are seen over the left fronto-temporal region (Fp1/F7/F3). A benign variant (BETS, benign epileptiform transients of sleep) cannot entirely be excluded.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse symmetric background slowing. Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates. A single EKG lead demonstrates heart rate 54 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
Sharp waves, occasional, left frontotemporal
Interpretation:
This is an abnormal 1-hour awake and asleep EEG due to: 1. Left frontotemporal sharp waves (Fp1/F7/F3). While these sharp waves are most likely epileptiform, a benign variant (BETS) cannot entirely be excluded. Of note, low voltage backgrounds are a benign variant in the adult population.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is an abnormal 1-hour awake and asleep EEG due to: 1. Left frontotemporal sharp waves (Fp1/F7/F3). While these sharp waves are most likely epileptiform, a benign variant (BETS) cannot entirely be excluded. Of note, low voltage backgrounds are a benign variant in the adult population

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 59 year old right handed woman with severe chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ARDS, likely metastatic and aggressive breast malignancy with multiple embolic infarcts including cerebellum and bilateral thalamic and ACA. History of epilepsy.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. The patient is intubated, unresponsive and examined during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates essentially continuous pattern rich in theta frequency activity. Arrhythmic delta activity is prominent in the posterior regions, right more so than the left. Some of this is sharply contoured. In addition, on 1 or 2 occasions, there seems to be a left frontotemporal sharp wave. There is intermittent attenuation and/or disruption of the theta with slower arrhythmic delta activity. Stimulation of the patient does seem to produce an increase in theta.
HR: 116 bpm
IMPRESSION: Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing.
2. Arrhythmic delta activity most prominent in the posterior region.
3. Some sharply contoured transience in the record including posterior temporal and left frontal.
4. Intermittent background attenuation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a significant, bihemispheric pathology particularly in the posterior regions. The presence of reactivity is a positive prognostic finding, but the intermittent attenuation is a worrisome prognostic finding in this individual with multiple medical problems and bilateral cerebral ischemia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Markedly abnormal EEG due to 1. Background slowing. 2. Arrhythmic delta activity most prominent in the posterior region. 3. Some sharply contoured transience in the record including posterior temporal and left frontal. 4. Intermittent background attenuation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	24-year-old female, past medical history of Wegener's granulomatosis, kidney transplant in 1999, end stage renal disease on peritoneal dialysis,  hypertension, anemia, and deep venous thrombosis, that presents with new onset seizure, generalized tonic, clonic, with loss of consciousness  and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Calcitriol, Aranesp, Senipar, Simvastatin, Mupirocin, Heparin, Moxifloxacin, Percocet, Phenergan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed. The patient had a coughing spell while in the lab.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness the background EEG is well­ organized with 9.5, Hz 50, 50-70 microvolts posterior dominant rhythm. A normal variant is observed in the background with rhythmic mid temporal, 5 Hz activity in the temporal regions, right or left. The technologist tested the patient on multiple occasions with stimulation of the patient always terminates these strains at 5 Hz flat top shaped activity, which may be unilateral or bilaterally.
At 11: 30: 54: The patient is sitting comfortably and has a heart rate of 84. She has a coughing spell, feeling as if she cannot catch her breath, and as if she is about to lose contact. The coughing spell is associated with muscle movement artifact, followed by burst of high amplitude delta. The heart rate increases to 132 beats per minute.
By 11:31:44: the EEG has returned to normal, but the patient remains tachycardic and feels unwell. Additional coughing again produces some of the same artifact, and some burst of delta.
Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response. HR: 	84-132 bpm
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   The rhythmic mid temporal theta described above is a normal variant, sometimes referred to as psychomotor variant. The patient had 2 episodes of coughing, with an increase in delta. The physiologic conclusion would be that prolonged coughing is the results in a hyperventilation response with the same sort of entity as would be expected to see in hyperventilation in the lab.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   53-year-old right-handed  female, with left-sided weakness, aphasia, twitching and headache, fever, herpes encephalitis
MEDICATIONS:   Motrin, Ativan, Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement  with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, background  EEG demonstrates an interhemispheric asymmetry. The left hemisphere is appropriately  organized with 9 Hz 50 mV posterior dominant rhythm. The right hemisphere  is characterized  by intermittent arrhythmic delta. Although, much of the faster frequency activity persists with periodic, right centrotemporal sharp waves with a field of spread essentially throughout the entire right hemisphere. These vary in terms of the periodicity, but do not evolve to seizures. If the patient becomes drowsy, they become lower amplitude with more a pattern of sharply contoured delta. Deeper stages of sleep are characterized  by an increase in beta frequency activity. The patient is easily
stimulated with an awake pattern from the left and a periodic sharply contoured  slowing from the
right.
HR: 	96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram:
1. 	Right-sided focal slowing.
2. 	Periodic, high-amplitude  right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORR ELATION:
This EEG supports a structural abnormality  on the right involving
gray and white matter. The periodic sharp waves support cortical irritability. This is a highly irritative pattern that raises concerns for ongoing seizures.  These results were reviewed with clinical team on 10/12/2007.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram 1. Right-sided focal slowing. 2. Periodic, high-amplitude  right temporal sharp waves.

report:

INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG is performed at bedside in the ICU using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Much of the records includes significant muscle movement artifact. The interpretable portions of the record demonstrate  an abnormal background with bursts of rhythmic delta observed bilaterally and a glimpse of a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There is more delta from the right compared to the left. There is another generous field in the right temporal region both anterior and posterior. Despite the muscle movement artifact, the patient was clearly more alert than on previous occasions and was moving about.
HR: 	60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Technically limited, but abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Background slowing, bilaterally.
2. 	Intermittent rhythmic and arrhythmic delta activity from either hemisphere.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	58 year-old male with a history of 2 motor vehicle accidents, 1 in 2004 and the other in 2007  sustaining a subdural hematoma. Patient is currently complaining of  headaches and dizzy spells. There is a left temporal parietal craniotomy.
MEDICATIONS:  None
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background rhythm consists of 9 hertz alpha rhythm at 30 to 50 microvolts.  Increased amplitude on the left greater than right. There is evidence of breech rhythm on the left. Wicket spikes are also seen. Hyperventilation is performed which increases  the amplitude of the record and also accentuates the breech rhythm. Photic stimulation produces minimal paroxysmal driving.
HR: 	56 bpm
IMPRESSION:   Normal EEG with variant of left temporal breech rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Breech rhythm is an anticipated finding given his history of craniotomy. Wicket spikes are a normal variant and would be expected to be more sharply contoured in the presence of a craniotomy. No epileptiform activity was appreciated. If epilepsy is an important concern, we recommend repeating the EEG with sleep recording.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:   Normal EEG with variant of left temporal breech rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   58 year-old male with multiple motor vehicle accidents, left temporoparietal  craniotomy  with a plate. Patient was having episodes shortly after his second head trauma in December 2007 when he had episodic dizziness, double vision and drop attacks. Now, resolving post traumatic symptoms.
MEDICATIONS:   Lisinopril
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are preformed. This is a 1 hour Sleep-Deprived EEG. Left craniotomy defect is observed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 hertz posterior dominant rhythm. A prominent craniotomy defect is observed with wicked from the left central temporal region. Underneath the wicked, there is a small amount of slow delta. Hyperventilation is performed  early on in the record accentuating the focal slowing. This is followed by drowsiness  with slow rolling eye movements. Vertex waves are observed in stage 1 sleep followed by arousals. Possible REM sleep is observed in this record in the sleep deprived 1 hour record with a characteristic  theta and lateral eye movements in a past who does not appear to be awake. This may have been associated with an arousal. An EMG monitor was not employed. In the extended sleep recording, there is vertex activity. There is alpha frequency activity picked up on the left more so that the right into stage 2 sleep which is an unusual finding in that is it sometimes seen on the right would not be considered a clearly pathological entity. Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR: 	54 bpm
IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	Intermittent focal slowing particularly observed in drowsiness in the left central temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are a number of unusual features in this record including the possibility of REM sleep in a single 1 hour record. The REM sleep appeared to be fragmented.  Another usual feature was the presence of rhythmic alpha rhythmic activity from the left central temporal region into stage 2 sleep.
This could not be considered clearly pathological  as it was sometimes present on there right. In any case, the alpha frequency activity did not wax and wane as might be anticipated in an epileptiform  pathology
Given the presence of the metal plate, epileptiform  activity may be under recognized in this individual. The previous craniotomy and skull defect in this case provide a breech rhythm with accentuation of activity, but the possibility of that activity is masked could not be excluded. This individual did not experience any other his paroxysmal spells during the study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to 1. Intermittent focal slowing particularly observed in drowsiness in the left central temporal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 30 year old right handed male with epilepsy since 2007, breakthrough seizure 2 weeks ago with loss of consciousness and confusion. This is an outpatient EEG.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are
performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low-voltage frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing and increase in amplitude of the background as well as some rhythmic delta from the right hemisphere, but without disruption of the underlying faster frequency activity. As the patient becomes drowsy again, there is a subtle disruption of faster frequency activity with subtle rhythmic slowing in the right temporal region. This is seen with brief transitions into stage II sleep but deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. On one occasion, in the transition to sleep there are sharp waves with rhythmic slowing out of the right temporal region followed by an arousal period. Unfortunately, there is some wick-like activity at this same time and there are some additional more subtle sharp waves without the same faster frequency activity noted. Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response. During photic stimulation, a well defined right anterotemporal spike in slow-wave complex is observed. Additional spike complexes are noted at the very end of the record, again right anterotemporal.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Rhythmic slowing in the right temporal region.
2. Right anterotemporal spike and slow-wave complexes and sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Rhythmic slowing in the right temporal region. 2. Right anterotemporal spike and slow-wave complexes and sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 78-year-old gentlemen with tonic clonic admitted on 18th with tonic clonic

epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Dilantin, Heparin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE As the tracing opens, the patient is relatively lethargic, but
over the course of this postictal EEG, the patient is more arousable. The initial background is
low voltage, diffusely slow, but there are intermittent arousals with approximately 8 Hertz alpha
rhythm identified bilaterally right better than left. The patient waxes and wanes with some
portions of the records which are reasonably well organized with alpha and theta activity, other
which are low voltage featureless delta and others which are a mix of irregular mixed theta and
delta. Activity is slightly higher on the right. Through the course of the record, intermittent
attenuations are observed and there is a fair amount of waxing and waning although the close -
of the record does seem to be better then the beginning. There is some sharp slowing observed
in the right mid to anterior temporal region with an after going slow wave observed.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Superimposed focal slowing with disruption of fast frequency on the left relative to the right.
3. Intermittent background attenuation.
4. Rare sharp wave observed on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function
effecting both hemispheres perhaps more significantly on the left than the right. The sharp
waves, however, were on the right. No previous EEG were available for comparison.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized background slowing. 2. Superimposed focal slowing with disruption of fast frequency on the left relative to the right. 3. Intermittent background attenuation. 4. Rare sharp wave observed on the right.

background and a suggestion of a right central temporal sharp wave. Deeper stages of
sleep are not sustained. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

1. Intermittent bursts of somewhat irregular temporal slowing.
2. Suspicious right temporal sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In this individual with a history of dementia, the overall
background is within normal limits with intermittent bursts of theta. This may be
correlated it imaging and clinical history.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Intermittent bursts of somewhat irregular temporal slowing. 2. Suspicious right temporal sharp wave.

report:

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to
1. 3 Hz frontally predominant spike in wave activity in hyperventilation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year-old mentally retarded male admitted with aspiration
pneumonia and tonoclonic seizures at an unknown time.
MEDICATIONS: Lovenox, Zosyn, Azithromycin, Lorazepam, Tegretol, Keppra
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in laboratory using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.
This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the patient is awake with a
well organized, 10.5 Hertz, 30 mcv posterior dominant rhythm in a generous amount of
low voltage, frontal central theta activity. The patient is noted to have a fair amount of
snore artifact as he drifts off to sleep. Vertex waves are observed in stage I sleep,
followed by arousals. Snore and muscle artifact obscure the right temporal electrodes
as the patient drifts off into sleep. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is
transitioning to and from stage II sleep. Despite this, both the photic driving and a
photoelectric artifact is observed.
HR: 96 bpm.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definitive focal or epileptiform features were seen,
however, the muscle artifact on the right was a concern. Given this individual has a
history of obstructive sleep apnea or snoring, an additional evaluation may be
appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old male with developmental disability and epilepsy.  Three seizures per month, last October 18th.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, lovastatin, Norvasc, others.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation was attempted, but not completed at the patient's request.  Photic stimulation was completed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  The waking background is intermittently interrupted by rhythmic theta which can be diffuse, frontocentral bilateral.  There are also shifting asymmetries noted.  The patient transitions rapidly in and out of stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  In the transition in and out of sleep, rare mu activity was identified.  There is also some sharply contoured slowing in the frontocentral regions bilaterally.

Photic stimulation is performed as the patient transitions in and out of stage 2 sleep.  Scant driving was noted.  Heart rate 84 BPM with occasional PVCs.

IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
1. Intermittent excess theta.
2. Mild background disorganization.
3. Occasional bursts of frontally predominant sharply contoured slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This individual had difficult relaxing during the study.  If additional information is needed to localize this patient's epilepsy, a more prolonged sleep study may be considered.  Additional evaluation for this patient's PVCs may be warranted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to 1. Intermittent excess theta. 2. Mild background disorganization. 3. Occasional bursts of frontally predominant sharply contoured slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old lady with past medical history of subarachnoid hemorrhage in 2007, status post hypertension and asthma and also history of seizures with left-sided weakness secondary to old stroke, presents for episodes of stuttering speech and right upper extremity shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Neurontin, Norvasc, Prozac, Prilosec, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm was 9-10 Hz in frequency 30-50 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage 1 and stage 2 sleep are characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm and slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact, and presence of posts, K complexes, vertex sharp transients, and sleep spindles.  There are also intermittent bursts of bitemporal slowing at F7/T3 and F8/T4 lasting for 1-2 seconds.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies, and results in a symmetric driving response.  Hyperventilation was performed and resulted in slowing of the background activity.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through drowsiness due to bitemporal slowing.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Bitemporal slowing is suggestive of bilateral structural abnormalities or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures are captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures. If clinically indicated, a repeat EEG or continuous bedside EEG or ambulatory, an EEG monitoring maybe helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through drowsiness due to bitemporal slowing.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 46-year-old woman with complex partial epilepsy, previously evaluated in 2008, now seen in the emergency room after recurrent seizures characterized by palpitations, diaphoresis, and staring occurring 1-3 times a week, lasting 3 minutes.  These are associated with fear.  Also, a feeling as if she is on a boat.  Patient was feeling almost back to herself.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, antidepressants, other medications (suboptimal adherent).
INTRODUCTION:  Extended, digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  The patient was somewhat symptomatic during the EEG, reporting disequilibrium.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the EEG demonstrates an awake pattern with a symmetric reactive alpha rhythm.  This is disrupted by intermittent bursts of rhythmic right temporal delta with admixed sharp waves.  The bursts of sharp waves and delta are on the order of 5-10-15 seconds in duration.  No alteration in the patient's motor or sensory symptoms were seen in association with these discharges.  The patient's responses are slowed, but the tech who spends 40 minutes with the patient, finds that the patient's responsiveness is not so significantly different than the sections of the record without the bursts.  As the recording concludes, the epileptiform activity is decreasing, but there remains some rhythmic right temporal slowing.  The sharp waves are significantly more discreet.
Photic stimulation was performed at the end of the record.  A driving response was identified.  In the final minutes of the recording, another more brief burst of right temporal sharp waves was noted.
Heart rate 84 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Well-defined high amplitude right temporal sharp waves.
Bursts of rhythmic temporal theta.
Bursts of rhythmic slowing and sharp waves lasting between 5 and 13 seconds without significant change in the patient's clinical status.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings suggest a highly irritative focus.  This may be a postictal study, but ongoing vigilance is essential (the patient was admitted to the hospital based on this result).
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to Well-defined high amplitude right temporal sharp waves. Bursts of rhythmic temporal theta. Bursts of rhythmic slowing and sharp waves lasting between 5 and 13 seconds without significant change in the patient's clinical status.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	29 year old gentleman with new onset seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin load.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard  10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.	The patient had just come from the emergency room having received the Dilantin and he had a seizure in the EEG lab removing his EEG electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the recording starts out, the patient is awake and reasonably cooperative.  There is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm observed. As the tracing again, the patient is awake with a 9.5 Hz, 30 mV posterior dominate rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by
slow-rolling eye movements. Hyperventilation is initiated early in the record, at 13:30 the patient is in the middle of hyperventilation.  At this time, 13:30:50 there is an arousal.   This is followed by the appearance of beta at 13:30:55, with repetitive sharp activity and theta maximum in the left temporal region, but with some bilateral representation.  As this continues at 13:31:07, there is little in the way of clinical manifestations.  By 13:31:10, the patient is starting to look from side to side.  He looks somewhat startled or frightened. The technologist calls the patient.  The patient's is
observed to be chewing, at 13:31:20, with repetitive sharp waves in left temporal region. He seems to be having automatic movements, face and but the audio is not
discernable.  The EEG goes on to be obscured with muscle.  As the patient's behaviors change, at 13:31:44, as he does that he has had head turning to the right. He gets up, he rotating around and looking all the way to the right.  He starts to turn around and around and he puts his head down. At that point, he rolls back towards his back and he has tonic clonic activity with his back to the camera with tonic stiffening and then clonic by 13:32:05. he seems to be having tonic clonic activity in the right arm but the left arm is stiff. Foaming at the mouth is seen at 13:32:19.  while he has eye deviation to the left he is jerking primarily with the right arm.  The characteristic slow pattern at the close of the clonic tonic seizure as the motor activity slows, is observed at 13:32:39. This seizure  ends at 13:32:48.  This is a 2 minute seizure.  Afterwards, the patient is awake, but agitated and he starts to get up and move about. There is a caregiver present with the technologist who applies oxygen.  The patient removes all the electrodes and receives 4 mg of Ativan. The EEG concludes at 13:40:02, where behaviorally the
patient is postictal
HR:	60 to 120 at the maximum during the seizure.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to;
1. 	Left temporal lobe complex partial seizure of 2 minutes duration,
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   This EEG is diagnostic of a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.  There is a well defined prolonged scalp EEG correlate before the EEG is obscured by muscle and motion artifact.  Additional evaluation and assessment is advised.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to;
1. Left temporal lobe complex partial seizure of 2 minutes duration,

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  60 year old male status post a right left MCA stroke and right subdural hematoma with recurrent status epilepticus, focal motor and generalized tonic? clonic seizures earlier today.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra,  Dilantin, Trileptal, ASA, Lisinopril, Vit-B, Zocor


INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel  EKG. Patient is somnolent but moving about and answering questions.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a slow pattern bilaterally with theta-delta pattern.  In addition, superimposed upon this is a rhythmic delta from the right posterior quadrant and in this region there is also a sharp wave in the right posterotemporal region.

The patient has a seizure while working with the tech. The seizure seems to begin while the tech is working with the patient and the first ictal changes are at 15:48. The ictal changes include an increase in theta frequency activity.

By 01:49:00 very clear ictal changes are noted with the patient looking, instead of at the right, he is looking at the left and blinking. He remains responsive to the technologist at
0:48:55 as this activity builds up.  He seems to be confused, but he does follow commands and closes his eyes at 0:49:14. The tech is working with the patient so she does not observe the rhythmic repetitive theta activity in the right temporal region which spreads to the parietal and occipital region as well. He stops speaking, though.  By
15:50 the physician comes to examine the patient who is clearly confused and unable to follow commands, with roving eye movements.   He does provide a few words at
15:50:33. This electrographic seizure has a clear end at 15:51:11 and likely onset gradual evolution of faster frequencies at 15:48 for a total seizure duration of approximately 3 minutes.

Afterwards, the EEG returns to its previous, slower periodic sharp wave from the right hemisphere which gradually build up at 15:54:03.   Facial twitching is noted.

The second seizure is a grand mal seizure but starts with facial twitching and actually has a complex partial component where the patient actually seems to be somewhat

responsive and uncomfortable with focal and then asynchronous twitching. The second seizure is significantly longer in duration.  The tonic-clonic section of it is still relatively prolonged and is at least4  seconds in duration.

After the second seizure which has the tonic-clonic components, the overall EEG is quite slow but the periodic complexes in the right posterior quadrant persist.

HR:	150  bpm


IMPRESSION: Normal bedside EEG due to:
1. 	Tonic-clonic seizure.
2. 	Complex partial seizure.
3 .	Continuous right posterior quadrant periodic complexes.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal bedside EEG due to 1. Tonic-clonic seizure

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  51 year old man with Parkinson's disease, brain tumor, pinealoma status post radiation therapy many years ago with encephalopathy, MRI demonstrating  right temporal lobe enhancement.   The patient presented to an outside hospital with encephalopathy and white matter changes.  Evaluate for herpes encephalitis or other cause.  There is a history of craniotomy and epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Metoprolol, Mirapex, Lovenox, Zofran
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG demonstrates an intrahemispheric  asymmetry.  There is a discernible 9Hz 50 microvolt alpha rhythm on the right which is disrupted on the left.  In addition, there is a skull defect with head rocking in the right central region and overall disruption of mu activity on the right compared to the left. Features of drowsiness include a drop out of faster frequency activity which occurs on the right much sooner on the left.
A seizure occurs at 09:53:03. It begins with the subtle development of alpha frequency out of the right temporal scalp electrodes which evolve.  No definitive clinical signs are seen until 09:53:47 when he starts to blink.  He seems to be motionless looking at the camera.  There may be some switching in the neck, but nothing that the video observer can see.  By 09:53:47 he is staring and blinking, looking to the left.  There is clear frequency evolution at 09:54:37.  There is no testing performed in the seizure and postictal slowing is noted with the end of the seizure occurring at 09:55:22 to 09:56.  By
09:59 the EEG looks postictal.  It has returned to the slowing that was previously noted
on the right with the return of alpha briefly on the left.
Notable features during this relatively prolonged, 2 minute complex partial seizure, includes the appearance of alpha frequency activity bilaterally, although there previously had not been alpha frequency on the right.  This activity is clearly pathological and it is not the alpha rhythm which reacts to eye opening.  It is actually faster frequency than it is posterior dominant rhythm and it is associated with repetitive sharp activity at T2.
The postictal recording includes some sharp waves on the left.
HR:	60 bpm
IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	A 2.5 minute complex partial seizure.
2. 	Focal slowing from the right.
3. 	Sharp waves from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is diagnostic of a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.  Correlation with imaging is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to 1. A 2.5 minute complex partial seizure. 2. Focal slowing from the right. 3. Sharp waves from the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  51 year old male with pinealoma recurrent complex partial seizures. MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Mirapex, Metoprolol,  Lovenox, Zofran
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video EEG was performed  at bedside using 10-20 system of electrode placement  with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is recorded in a routine room.
There is no seizure spike detection employed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Through the course of this EEG, there are 6 complex partial seizures recorded.  The clinical manifestations of the seizures appear to be quite subtle for those who are not familiar with epilepsy.  The patient stares, blinks, may look to the left, and has impaired responsiveness.  He has some automatic movements.
Epileptiform activity during the seizures is characterized  by rhythmic 9 Hz activity in the right temporal region, including the right posterior temporal region.  This activity shows frequency evolution transitioning  to theta and then delta with sharply contoured activity at T2, T4, and T6. Postictal features for these seizures include marked slowing from the right hemisphere, particularly the temporal region with rhythmic theta delta, and then a lower voltage more suppressed pattern.
The seizures are relatively infrequent, but reoccur at 16:20, 16:43.  That seizure is characterized by chewing activity,  02:28 to 02:48 in which there is really little in the way of clinical correlate, but there is the clear alpha frequency activity on the right with a slower pattern on the left, 03:06,
04:52, 05:09. Some of the discharges  have little in the way of a clinical correlate. The recording ends at 6:00 a.m.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
I.   Multiple complex partial seizures, but they seem to be abating at the close of the record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The EEG supports an irritative process on the right.  The complex partial seizures are relatively subtle.  The total number of seizures is likely 6-8 in 15 hours.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to I.   Multiple complex partial seizures, but they seem to be abating at the close of the record.

report:
History:	59 year old woman with a history of seizures, now presents with increase in seizure
frequency.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by low-to-moderate amplitude 10.5-11 Hz alpha rhythm, which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present,
maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-
7Hz slow waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.
Polymorphic and rhythmic delta activity (TIRDA) is frequently observed over the left temporal
region during wakefulness and increases during drowsiness.  Two focal electrographic seizures are
captured.  Each lasts ~ 1 minute.  No clinical correlate is reported by the EEG technologist.  The
patient is not formally tested during these seizures.  They occur during drowsiness.  Seizures start
with rhythmic left anterior temporal delta activity, most pronounced over F7/t1 region.  It gradually
increases in amplitude, becomes more prominent and slightly increases in frequency from ~2 Hz to
~2.5-3 Hz.  There is some reflection  to the left parasagittal leads and left lateral/ temporal leads.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce additional abnormalities.
Summary of Findings:
Seizure, two, left temporal, anterior, each ~ 1 min long.  Occur out of drowsiness
Focal slowing, rhythmic, intermittent, moderate, left temporal, anterior
Focal slowing, polymorphic, intermittent, moderate, left temporal, anterior
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 28-minute EEG due to intermittent focal left anterior
temporal slowing, often rhythmic, and 2 focal left anterior temporal seizures that occur during
drowsiness and do not have a clear clinical correlate. These findings are indicative of an
epileptogenic focus in left anterior temporal region, and given the clinical history of partial
seizures, are consistent with a diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy.  These findings were
relayed to the ordering physician at the time of the record review.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 28-minute EEG due to intermittent focal left anterior
temporal slowing, often rhythmic, and 2 focal left anterior temporal seizures that occur during
drowsiness and do not have a clear clinical correlate. These findings are indicative of an
epileptogenic focus in left anterior temporal region, and given the clinical history of partial
seizures, are consistent with a diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy.  These findings were
relayed to the ordering physician at the time of the record review

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year-old male with a seizure in 2008 and 2009. The most recent seizure was associated with a headache.
MEDICATIONS: None listed in chart
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed in awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 10 hertz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. There is an amplitude asymmetry with slightly higher amplitude activity in the left compared to the right. In addition, there is intermittent, rhythmic theta on the left, as well as an arrhythmic slowing. Wicket activity is observed in wakefulness but underlying this wicket activity there is some suspicious sharp waves. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing some bursts of relatively generalized frontal delta. Also noted are intermittent bursts of arrhythmic, left temporal focal slowing. Vertex waves are observed in stage I sleep. In the transition to sleep, rare, left anterior temporal sharp waves are observed. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Left temporal focal slowing characterized by rhythmic and arrhythmic focal slowing.
2. Rare left anterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy. Previous EEGs were not available for comparison:
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Left temporal focal slowing characterized by rhythmic and arrhythmic focal slowing. 2. Rare left anterior temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 45 year old woman with generalized tonic clonic epilepsy since
childhood. Her last seizure was 2 months ago, 4-6 seizures per year. History of HIV and
depression.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Zoloft, Epivir, Loratadine
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation and
hyperventilation are performed. This is a 1 hour sleep deprived record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized, but
somewhat slow, with an 8 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Photic stimulation shows scant driving
response. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing some background
slowing, as well as a bit of arrhythmic delta activity in the posterior temporal regions bilaterally.
This is followed by drowsiness with anterior spread of the alpha rhythm, followed by vertex
waves. Frequent arousals from stage I and stage II sleep are observed. A handful of
asynchronous vertex waves are observed with shifting asymmetries in the right or left central
region. Snore artifact is also observed in stage I sleep.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild slowing of the alpha rhythm.
2. Rare shifting asymmetries of vertex waves.
CLINICAL No definitive epileptiform features were observed. The findings
described above are nonspecific and can be seen in a diffuse disturbance of cerebral
dysfunction due to many etiologies, including epilepsy or HIV infection.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to 1. Mild slowing of the alpha rhythm. 2. Rare shifting asymmetries of vertex waves.

report:

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 59-year-old woman with past medical history of hypertension, coronary artery disease, HIV, hepatitis C, who presents to the hospital having visual and auditory hallucinations.

INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

Photic stimulation results in minimal symmetrical occipital driving at higher flash frequencies.

No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy 21-minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in the routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy 21-minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in the routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:

There is an interhemispheric asymmetry seen with some focal slowing of the right hemisphere.  Sleep is seen with vertex waves and spindles and a little epochs of sleep, where the patient quickly awakens.  Hyperventilation accentuates the focal slowing in the right hemisphere.  Photic stimulation shows some scant driving, which is seen a bit better on the right posterior hemisphere.
HR:  66 bpm

2. 	More focal slowing seen in the right hemisphere.
Scant driving seen asymmetrically  and better in the right posterior region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is no epileptiform activity seen in this record. The generalized slowing of the background is nonspecific.  Initially, the focal slowing is seen in the right hemisphere,  but the driving is actually better in the right hemisphere,  which is incongruent and not initially expected.  The focal differences could be secondary to a structural abnormality and could get imaging this patient.  Clinical correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Generalized slowing of the background, which does reach 9 Hz, but the majority of the background is slow. 2. More focal slowing seen in the right hemisphere. Scant driving seen asymmetrically  and better in the right posterior region.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 54-year-old woman with change in mental status and recent seizures with a history of epilepsy, schizophrenia, EPOC, and left mesial temporal sclerosis.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The EKG electrode does not show a very good rhythm, a very low amplitude rhythm.  In addition, the impedances on the occipital electrodes and the right frontal and central electrodes were very high due to difficulty with the patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a recording that is mainly in sleep.  The patient is aroused at one point during the study and there appears to be a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 8 Hz, mainly seen over the right hemisphere, but for a short duration, again in the setting of electrode with a high impedance.  Overall the record is recorded during stage I and stage II and the first stages of sleep.  The patient falls asleep fairly quickly throughout this study.
Heart rate:  78 and appears to be regular.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-50 mV, at times with a very sharply contoured component.  Sometimes they appear to become rhythmic, but not clearly evolved or become continuous.
Focal slowing seen intermittently at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Mild excessive theta in wakefulness and limited wakefulness.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal focal slowing, as well as right mid temporal focal slowing and mild excessive theta in limited wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG in limited wakefulness reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region and independently in the right mid temporal region, both of which are nonspecific in regards to etiology.  In addition, the patient appears to have some mild diffuse generalized dysfunction, which is also nonspecific in regard to etiology.  No seizures or clear epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal focal slowing, as well as right mid temporal focal slowing and mild excessive theta in limited wakefulness.

Overall the record is recorded during stage I and stage II and the first stages of sleep.  The patient falls asleep fairly quickly throughout this study.
Heart rate:  78 and appears to be regular.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-50 mV, at times with a very sharply contoured component.  Sometimes they appear to become rhythmic, but not clearly evolved or become continuous.
Focal slowing seen intermittently at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Mild excessive theta in wakefulness and limited wakefulness.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal focal slowing, as well as right mid temporal focal slowing and mild excessive theta in limited wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG in limited wakefulness reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region and independently in the right mid temporal region, both of which are nonspecific in regards to etiology.  In addition, the patient appears to have some mild diffuse generalized dysfunction, which is also nonspecific in regard to etiology.  No seizures or clear epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal focal slowing, as well as right mid temporal focal slowing and mild excessive theta in limited wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 55-year-old woman with schizophrenia, epilepsy with tonic-clonic seizures, and recurrent hospitalizations for status epilepticus.  Currently, seizure-free for nearly 2 months.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenytoin.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.  There is some electrode placement issues with this EEG, but it is technically acceptable.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is very low voltage with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  Stage II sleep includes vertex waves and spindles.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
There is significant muscle twitch artifact noted in the background.
Heart rate 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this adult with a history of refractory epilepsy.  No epileptiform features were noted today, but complex epileptiform activity has been noted with many different patterns over the past 4 years.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 59-year-old male with increasing frequency of visual spells where he feels like he is losing his visual perception and becoming blind, history of sarcoid and posterior retinal detachment.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Dilantin, and Solu-Medrol,
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is a technically acceptable record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates an unusual pattern.  There is a slow alpha rhythm of approximately 6 hertz.  Intermittently, in the occipital region, there is fast activity of 14 hertz.  There appears to be a subtle asymmetry with a bit more vigorous 14 hertz activity in the left occipital region relative to the right and some subtle underlying occipital slowing noted on the right.  The patient is quite drowsy, transitioning from wakefulness to sleep.  In sleep, there are some POSTS noted, right more so than the left.
Photic stimulation was performed when the patient was drifting off to sleep, and no driving response was noted.
HEART RATE 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult due to:
Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.
An unusual pattern with beta activity noted in the occipital regions which seems to be asymmetric more so on the left than the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient's previous EEGs are not available for comparison.  No definitive epileptiform features were noted, but some of the findings noted today may be similar to previous occipital findings for this individual.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult due to Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm. An unusual pattern with beta activity noted in the occipital regions which seems to be asymmetric more so on the left than the right.

report:
History:	60 year old man who presents with spells characterized by changes in vision and
depth perception.
Medications:	no AEDs
Sedation:	None
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Fast alpha variant is captured.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz
activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta is noted.  During
drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more
prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the
record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
Sleep, stage 2
Beta, excessive
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could
be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could
be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed. This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 hertz alpha rhythm with a 9 hertz wicket activity. Prominent central mew activity was noted. The new activity is 9.3 hertz. Hyperventilation produces some head rocking artifact, but no definitive sharp waves. Photic stimulation does not activate the record. Stage I sleep included spindles, vertex waves and POSTS .
HR:	84 bpm

epileptiform activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:	23 year old right handed woman with complex partial epilepsy, seizure-free,  with recurrent seizures.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra


INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is a one-hour sleep-deprived record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a well-organized background with 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm.  The patient rapidly drifts in and out of sleep with POSTS. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, but the patient is drifting
into stage II  sleep. Spikey POSTS are observed in the abundant stage II  sleep record. In  the sleep recording, there is an amplitude asymmetry for the POSTS which are high amplitude and on one occasion a left parietal sharp wave.  Additionally, with this subtle asymmetry there is also noted asymmetry with more muscle artifact on the right. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is essentially asleep and does not significantly activate the record.

HR:	78 bpm


IMPRESSION: Questionably abnormal EEG due to:
1.  A single left parietal sharp wave.


CLINICAL CORRELATION:   The amplitude asymmetry of the POSTS is an acceptable variant. A single sharp wave is a nonspecific finding. It may represent artifact, and there are other artifacts noted in this record at this time.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Questionably abnormal EEG due to 1.  A single left parietal sharp wave.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   A 61-year-old male with new onset of epilepsy 1 week ago. Seizures are characterized by eye open, shaking lasting seconds. The patient is also developing dizziness after coughing. Laryngeal carcinoma status post radiation therapy.

MEDICATIONS:  METFORMIN,  PILOCARPINE,  DIOVAN, SIMVASTATIN, DILANTIN FLUTICASONE

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic stimulation is performed. The patient experiences a coughing spell during the EEG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness,  the background EEG includes symmetric reactive alpha rhythm. The patient rapidly drifts off to sleep with an increase in background slowing. A coughing spell is associated with movement artifact, but also with an increase in theta and delta.

Heart rate is 104 increasing to 120 BPM with coughing.


IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.


CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No epileptiform features were observed in this EEG. The coughing was associated with an increase in slowing and an increase in heart rate. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a more prolonged study capturing more significant sleep may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 65-year-old gentleman with history of COPD, hypertension, diabetes, tooth cancer, status post treatment, who presents with left focal seizures described as a left arm shaking lasting for a few minutes, resolved by administration of Ativan 2 mg IV.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 7-7.5 Hz in frequency, well-formed on the left side, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 5-7 Hz diffuse theta activity noted during wakefulness.  There is attenuation and loss of faster frequencies in the right hemisphere, most pronounced in posterior quadrant with intermittent slowing in the left cerebral hemisphere.  The lethargic state is characterized by further slowing of the background and disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm.  Heart rate was 90 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:
This is an abnormal EEG recording due to:
Diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen in wakefulness.
Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.
Attenuation and loss of faster frequencies and also slowing in the left posterior quadrant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are suggestive of either metabolic, toxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of sedating medication or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  Attenuation and loss of faster frequencies in the left cerebral hemisphere is likely due to the patient's history of stroke.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures is captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION This is an abnormal EEG recording due to Diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen in wakefulness. Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm. Attenuation and loss of faster frequencies and also slowing in the left posterior quadrant.

report:

MEDICATIONS: Vancomycin, Cefepime, Azithromycin, ASA
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there are some sections of the record with a 9.5 hertz posterior dominant rhythm, but other demonstrates a pattern of subtle, background slowing. At that point, the alpha rhythm slows to 8.3 hertz. Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing. The drowsy pattern differs from the relaxed wakeful pattern in that there are slow rolling eye movements.
HR: 110 bpm
IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Intermittent background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The background slowing is less remarkable than previous studies. Of note, this is the 4th EEG for this patient and to date none have demonstrated epileptiform activity. If seizures or syncope are frequent, a prolonged outpatient monitoring evaluation may be valuable.

report:
INTRODUCTION:
An EEG is performed using standard the 10-20 electrode placement system with an EKG electrode. Awake and stage I sleep is recorded. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were used.
MEDICATIONS:
Vimpat and Tegretol.
TECHNICAL PROBLEMS:
None.
HISTORY:
A 37-year-old female who presents for followup EEG with past medical history significant for generalized epilepsy. Last seizure was reported in February 2011, with fall and loss of consciousness with urinary incontinence and postictal confusion lasting for an hour.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:
Posterior dominant alpha rhythm is seen at 9 to 10Hz frequency and 20 microvolt amplitude which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening. Frontocentral beta rhythm is also seen. Stage I sleep is seen and is normal. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed, which are also normal.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized spike and wave at 4 to 4.5 Hz and 70 to 100 microvolts amplitude is seen, which is located maximum anteriorly. This generalized pattern is asymmetric with slight predominance in the left hemisphere. No seizures are seen.
IMPRESSION:
This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
The EEG findings can be seen in generalized epilepsy; however, a sight asymmetric pattern raises the possibility of a focal epilepsy with secondary bilateral synchrony.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 54 year old right handed woman with left MCA stroke, baseline
right sided weakness, and expressive aphasia with acute change in mental status and
eye deviation to the right.
MEDICATIONS: Insulin, Zocor, Metoprolol, Zosyn, Vancomycin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is lying flat and has
very little spontaneous movement. but she is awake. She is restless only in the later
sections of the record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG in much of the relaxed
wakeful record is slow bilaterally. There is a discernible, slow alpha rhythm of 7 Hz with
some smaller 6 Hz activity. What is striking, particularly in relaxed wakefulness is the
record is actually slower on the right than the left with disruption of faster frequency in
the right hemisphere, particularly in the right posterior region. Features of sleep include
vertex waves. In the transition to sleep, there are some bursts of FIRDA
HR: 96 bpm irregular
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Superimposed focal slowing from the right hemisphere.
3. Bursts of FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings should be correlated with imaging. No
epileptiform features were noted in this record. Because of the history provided above,
concern about an underlying, new structural process are appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized background slowing. 2. Superimposed focal slowing from the right hemisphere. 3. Bursts of FIRDA.

report:

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG in wakefulness and early drowsiness due to Left temporal focal slowing with a component of left frontal central focal slowing
Left anterior temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 28 year old woman with recurrent episodes which appear to be seizures. Past medical history: Post traumatic stress disorder, assault victim, others.

INTRODUCTION: Digital Video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a vigorous, 50-70 microvolt 10 Hertz upper rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, fronto-central beta activity. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude data background. Photic stimulation elicits harmonic and spur harmonic driving. As the photic stimulation begins the patient looks to the left and covers her face. She has her hands over her eyes and appears to be crying. When the technologist turns towards the patient at 10:18:08 the technologist interacts with the patient who begins to have jerking. The patient exhibits pelvic thrusting and neck thrusting and involuntary jerkins. The jerking of the right arm persists even as the study ends at 10:21 but the patient is able to look and interact with the physician. The EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern throughout the entire event. There is no spike in wave activity and a well defined alpha rhythm is observed.
HR: 60-120 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The behavior recorded was not associated with epileptiform activity. In addition, the behavioral features of the event would be very unusual for a seizure. These findings were discussed with the clinical team.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:

No epileptiform discharges No stage 2 sleep
