report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 18 year old right handed woman with a first ever tonic clonic seizure. This seizure began with staring followed by tonic clonic activity, incontinence and 30 minutes of postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial sections of much of the waking record unfortunately includes head rocking artifact in the posterior regions. There is a 10.5 hertz alpha rhythm which is higher amplitude on the right than the left and posterior activity is always higher amplitude on the right than the left in this individual. Brief stage II sleep includes vertex waves, spindles and POSTS. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response, but the driving response is somewhat asymmetric, more vigorous on the left compared to the right. In addition, there is also a suggestion of a subharmonic driving response elicited on the left more so than the right.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Equivocally abnormal EEG due to:
1. Asymmetric photic stimulation described above.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The head rocking artifact is in the same region as the area of potential abnormality. A somewhat asymmetric photic stimulation is not necessarily pathological and some of the features that this patient demonstrated are compatible with normal variant. To more completely evaluate her epilepsy, a follow up study with more extended sleep is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Equivocally abnormal EEG due to 1. Asymmetric photic stimulation described above.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 22 year old female with a history of seizures since age 17. Seizure free since 2010, Diagnosed with lupus  2 years ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Topiramate, prednisone, Plaquenil, others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 40-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, but the overall background is somewhat disorganized.  There is a small amount of shifting slowing and a small amount of background theta.  Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic theta.  Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Notable in this record are paroxysmal bursts of rhythmic, high amplitude theta, some of which demonstrate frequency evolution.  In addition, there are irregular bursts of 4-5 Hz spike and wave activity noted in the frontal regions.  On occasion, some of these seem to be a bit more prominent in the right.  These bursts are overall, relatively asynchronous.
Hyperventilation produced 1 of these bursts of high amplitude, theta frequency activity with a questionable right frontal spike and slow wave complex as well as some rhythmic theta.
Photic stimulation elicited a bilateral driving response.  The photic stimulation may also have accentuated some of the epileptiform activity, although on the whole.  The epileptiform activity was pre or post the photic stimulation.
Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to.
Small degree of background disorganization for an adult of this age.
Somewhat irregular asynchronous bursts of high amplitude spike and wave activity as well as paroxysmal theta.
Occasional bursts of shifting, slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this individual.  Previous studies have demonstrated 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity, or independent right or left temporal lobe sharp and slow wave activity.  The findings today are similar to this patient's original EEGs in 2010.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to. Small degree of background disorganization for an adult of this age. Somewhat irregular asynchronous bursts of high amplitude spike and wave activity as well as paroxysmal theta. Occasional bursts of shifting, slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old male with new onset seizures.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Continuous digital video EEG was preformed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient keeps a log. He is able to push the button for all of the events that he experiences. He has multiple episodes of dizziness or disorienting feeling.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 hertz posterior dominant rhythm which is symmetrically reactive. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background theta with vertex waves, spindles and stage II sleep. There is an epoch in which REM sleep is seen.
In the interictal EEG, there is a single left temporal sharp wave.
Events: The patient has multiple dizzy spells including 129, 125, 312, 336, 536, 546 and then there are no additional push buttons noted.
Although not all of the seizures have a clear clinical correlate and some have only either subtle theta or subtle disruption of faster frequency activity in left temporal region, some have clear, rhythmic 4 hertz theta from the left temporal region with some spread to the frontocentral region bilaterally, typically lasting 20-40 seconds. The patient receives Depakote at 2:20p.m., the discharges are briefer, more evanescent more allusive.
Event time 12930: the patient has a dizzy spell characterized by decreased alpha frequency activity from the left temporal region and a brief burst of left temporal theta.
Event time: 2:32 p.m.: There is a brief burst of left temporal theta which differs from the background.
Event time: 3:12p.m.: Aura of dizziness, left temporal theta.
Event #3: Aura characterized by dizziness time 335 to 33729, rhythmic temporal theta as described above.
Event #4: Subtle left temporal theta at 3:53:52.
Event #5: 536, very subtle left temporal theta.
Event #6: Aura 5:46:13, brief burst of left temporal theta.
HR: 100 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG monitoring due to:
1. Subtle, intermittent attenuation of alpha frequency activity in the left temporal region.
2. A handful of well defined auras characterized by rhythmic 4 hertz theta with clear frequency evolution. The characteristic seizure pattern for this patient includes attenuation of alpha in the region, then the theta and then some bilateral frontocentral spread.
3. Rare interictal findings including sharp waves in the left temporal region and sharply contoured theta. An example of this is at 4:35:37 a.m. on the morning of the second.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is diagnostic of a localization related
mechanism for epilepsy. These findings were reviewed with the patient during the hospitalization.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG monitoring due to 1. Subtle, intermittent attenuation of alpha frequency activity in the left temporal region. 2. A handful of well defined auras characterized by rhythmic 4 hertz theta with clear frequency evolution. The characteristic seizure pattern for this patient includes attenuation of alpha in the region, then the theta and then some bilateral frontocentral spread. 3. Rare interictal findings including sharp waves in the left temporal region and sharply contoured theta. An example of this is at 4:35:37 a.m. on the morning of the second.

report:
History:	52 year old woman with seizures.
Medications:	Topamax, Phenobarbital
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is noted.  During drowsiness, the background
slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate
voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair effort, and produces no effect.  Stepped
photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.  Irregular heart
rate with inter-QRS interval of up to 1.5 seconds is noted on a single EKG lead.
Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
No stage 2 sleep
Cardiac arrhythmia
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 21-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. Excessive beta activity could be
secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  Irregular heart rate
with inter-QRS interval of up to 1.5 seconds is noted on a single EKG lead.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 21-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. Excessive beta activity could be
secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  Irregular heart rate
with inter-QRS interval of up to 1.5 seconds is noted on a single EKG lead

report:

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There are occasional bursts of shifting slowing, particularly in the right central region. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is transitioning in and out of stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles, and POSTS. There are rare, right central sharp waves noted, as well as a single posteriorly predominant spike at P4.  There are really only the two C4 spikes and the posterior spike.

Shifting slowing, a little bit more so on the right central region on the left.
Two right central and one occipital, right greater than left, sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The sharp waves are in the region of this patient's cerebrovascular disease.  The shifting slowing is a nonspecific finding which can be
seen in the context of underlying ischemic cerebrovascular disease.  Overall, this was otherwise a sharply contoured, but otherwise unremarkable background.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Shifting slowing, a little bit more so on the right central region on the left. Two right central and one occipital, right greater than left, sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 58 year old left handed male with intractable epilepsy, complex partial seizures, last seizure unclear.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Xanax, Prozac, Celexa, Prilosec, Citalopram, Ambien
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake record with hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9Hz, 40 microvolt posterior-dominant rhythm. The alpha rhythm is sometimes disrupted from the right hemisphere. There is some shifting arrhythmic delta activity identified bilaterally. High amplitude right anterior temple spike and slow wave complexes are observed most of which are maximum at T-2 but some of which are maximum T4 and T6. All are high amplitude, sometimes exceeding 100 microvolts with a generous field of spread within the right hemisphere and disruption of faster
frequency activity. Hyperventilation clearly accentuates the epileptiform activity. Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm. There is some bilateral posterior slowing and drowsiness. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. The focal right greater than left posterior slowing is noted in photic stimulation. Stage I sleep starts to emerge at the end of the EEG but sleep is not sustained.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. High amplitude right anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes.
2. Right hemisphere and right temporal focal slowing.
3. Sharp waves in the right hemisphere with variable maximum but most of which are maximum in the temple regions
4. A modest degree of background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a structural process as well as a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. High amplitude right anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes. 2. Right hemisphere and right temporal focal slowing. 3. Sharp waves in the right hemisphere with variable maximum but most of which are maximum in the temple regions
4. A modest degree of background slowing.

report:
HISTORY:
A 47-year-old woman found in a drug house with seizure-like activity. Abnormal MRI suggesting encephalitis but no cells in
CSF
ROOM NUMBER:
Emergency room.
MEDICATIONS:
Ativan 8 mg.
INTRODUCTION:
Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the emergency room using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement
with one channel of EKG. The patient is examined during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:
The background EEG begins With a marked asymmetry between the two hemispheres. It is very low-voltage suppressed
with a paucity of beta activity on the left. In contrast, the right includes generous beta, diffusely. In this relatively
low-voltage pattern on the left, there are subtle, periodic sharp waves or sharply contoured delta at C3-P3. As the
recording continues, the patient is starting to move about, there is additional beta activity noted from both hemispheres.
The periodic complexes are still apparent underneath the muscle and movement artifact. Stimulation of the patient
produces an increase in muscle artifact. As the recording continues, the epileptiform activity transitions to a bit more of a
frontotemporal broadly contoured discharge with a broad field of spread.
Heart rate 104 BPM.

IMPRESSION:
Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1.
Initially, a markedly slow and suppressed pattern on the left.
2.
An asymmetry that persists throughout the record with a much slower pattern on the left.
3.
A periodic complex seen intermittently from the left. The patient was a bit more agitated by the end of the record, but
on the video, no jerking can be discerned during the video to correlate with the periodic complexes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
In this individual with recent seizures characterized by right-sided jerking, the periodic complexes and focal slowing should
be correlated with imaging to exclude a structural pathology. No prolonged seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION Markedly abnormal EEG due to 1. Initially, a markedly slow and suppressed pattern on the left. 2. An asymmetry that persists throughout the record with a much slower pattern on the left. 3. A periodic complex seen intermittently from the left. The patient was a bit more agitated by the end of the record, but
on the video, no jerking can be discerned during the video to correlate with the periodic complexes.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  47 year old woman with IV drug abuse admitted August 2nd, then August 27th.  Evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Oxycodone, Lisinopril, Dilaudid, Metoprolol, ASA
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This was an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz 50 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low-voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is scant amount of theta noted in the record.  There are occasional bursts of rhythmic, paroxysmal frontal delta.  Epochs of stage II sleep include vertex waves. Paroxysmal, high-amplitude delta is noted as the patient starts to transition toward sleep. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is transitioning in and out of sleep and does not significantly activate the record.
HR:    60 bpm and slightly irregular.
IMPRESSION:  Slightly abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent bursts of paroxysmal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were seen in this EEG.  None were seen in the August 8th EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Slightly abnormal EEG due to Intermittent bursts of paroxysmal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 56 year old left handed male with post traumatic epilepsy, head
trauma 20 years ago. The patient was seizure-free for 20 years until April 3rd, when he
had a seizure with loss of consciousness, incontinence and confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is
somewhat slow and slightly disorganized. The alpha rhythm is 8 Hz, 30 microvolts with
excess frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation produces head rocking artifact as
well as some rhythmic slowing. Features of drowsiness include an increase in
background slowing. Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
I. Mild background slowing.
2. Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed. The background
slowing described above is a nonspecific finding, supporting a diffuse, bihemispheric
disturbance of cerebral function. To more. completely characterize this individual's
epilepsy, a followup study may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to I. Mild background slowing. 2. Slowing of the alpha rhythm.

report:
HISTORY
A 56-year-old male with tonic-clonic seizures and loss of consciousness on June 11, 2011, history of head injury and
hypertension.
MEDICATIONS:
Keppra and metformin.
INTRODUCTION:
Digital video EEG is performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one-channel EKG. This is an
awake and drowsy record. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:
In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing with
Vertex waves and stage 1 sleep. Pulses are also noted.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.
IMPRESSION:
This EEG is within limits of normal with an alpha rhythm of 8.5 Hz.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
In contrast to the previous EEG of April 19, 2011, the background EEG was somewhat slow. There are sections of the
records where the patient does achieve a normal alpha rhythm and therefore this EEG would be considered within normal
limits, neither EEG demonstrated epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION This EEG is within limits of normal with an alpha rhythm of 8.5 Hz.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 21 year old right handed woman with epilepsy. Medications nonadherence in pregnancy. She subsequently had a seizure, fell, head trauma, subdural hematoma now in a hard collar in the intensive care unit. History of learning disability and focal seizures.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Depakote, Morphine, Famotidine, Zofran, Valproate

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is uncomfortable wearing a hard cervical collar and has difficulty cooperating with the study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a relatively slow pattern. The patient is very drowsy and morphologies of stage II sleep include vertex waves and occasional spindles. There are bursts of delta. Artifacts are noted and there seems to be some attenuation in the right posterior region but unfortunately there is significant electrode artifact.
HR: 66bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing.
2. A hypersomnolent individual.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no epileptiform features observed in this EEG. The background slowing and the hypersomnolence may be due to the head trauma and/or medications. Prior EEGs were abnormal but without epileptic activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Background slowing. 2. A hypersomnolent individual.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old male with adult onset complex partial epilepsy, refractory, tonic-clonic, and secondarily generalized medicines.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is a technically satisfactory routine EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage, but there is an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Alpha squeak was noted.
Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, spindles, K complexes, and POSTS.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was in stage II sleep and did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Low voltage, otherwise normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified in the routine EEG.  Additional EEG recording was undertaken to characterize this patient's epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Low voltage, otherwise normal EEG.

report:
History:	46 year old man with a known seizure disorder, now presents after several
Medications:	Amitriptyline, Citalopram,  Depakote,   Ativan, Topamax
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes, awake,
lethargic
Description:
There is no clear PDR or AP gradient.  The background consists of low amplitude diffuse fast
activity.  Patient appears awake throughout the study.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Beta, excessive
No stage 2 sleep
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake-only 31 minute portable EEG because the normal background has
been replaced by diffuse fast activity. This could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not
rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake-only 31 minute portable EEG because the normal background has
been replaced by diffuse fast activity. This could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not
rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  70 year old right handed female with complaints of seizure last year, CVA, diabetes, hypertension, not taking medications for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Zantac, Metoprolol, Nifedipine, Hyzaar, Lipitor, Insulin, Omeprazole, Gabapentin, Metformin, Furosemide, not taking the prescribed Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedure including photic stimulation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 8.5-9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal amount of frontocentral beta.  Activating procedure was photic stimulation, produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness, stage 1 sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at F7/T3 rarely throughout the study.
Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7/T3 at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts and a frequency of 2-4 Hz.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1.   Focal sharp waves in the left anterior temporal region.
2.   Focal slow waves in that region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy with seizures arising from the left anterior temporal region.  No seizures
were seen.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1.   Focal sharp waves in the left anterior temporal region. 2.   Focal slow waves in that region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  45 year old man right handed with history of seizures as a child, now with recurrent seizures and concurrent insomnia, anxiety, depression and migraines.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Lamictal, Temazepam, Seroquel, Effexor, Letherezia (?)
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement as well as anterotemporal electrodes and EKG electrodes.  The EEG was recorded with photic stimulation and hyperventilation was performed.  Sleep stage I and stage II were recorded.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Frequent bilateral temporalis muscle artifact seen during the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontal central beta.  Sleep stage I and stage II is recorded.  Photic stimulation and hyperventilation presented no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
There are 2 short bursts of less than 400 milliseconds seen with left frontal predominant sharp waves and slow waves which appeared to have a bilateral component and distribution more consistent with fragment of general spike and wave, however, a focal left frontal spike cannot be excluded.
SEIZURES:   None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Left frontal asymmetric spike and wave discharges likely fragments of generalized spike and wave
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with evidence of cortical irritability which is suggestive of an idiopathic generalized epilepsy.  However, the slight asymmetry of the spike and wave fragments may also suggest a focal origin with secondary bilateral synchrony.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1.  Left frontal asymmetric spike and wave discharges likely fragments of generalized spike and wave

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 47-year-old male with childhood epilepsy, seizures recurred in 2011 associated with anxiety and depression.
MEDICATIONS:  Temazepam, Celexa, lamotrigine, and carbamazepine.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a routine 20 minute EEG with acceptable impedances.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is somewhat drowsy.  The patient transitions in and out of an awake state with a well-defined, 9.2 hertz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements.
Hyperventilation was performed early on in the record and serve to keep the patient awake as well as increasing the amplitude of the alpha rhythm.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving response.
Brief, stage 2 sleep included some electrode artifacts, but spindles were identified.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This is in contrast to a previous EEG, October 27, 2011, which identified 2 left frontal sharp waves/spikes.  If additional information is needed, a more prolonged sleep study may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  24 year old right handed woman with history of episodes of loss of consciousness, some with quick return to baseline and some with confusion after the episodes and previous to the episodes having a strange smell.  The patient is 6 months pregnant.  She also has a history of open heart surgery in the past.
MEDICATIONS:  Prenatal Vitamins, Folic Acid.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Episodes of loss of consciousness and confusion.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG is performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  Procedures included photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior rhythm that reaches 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontal central beta.  Activity and procedures included photic stimulation, which revealed no abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded mainly in wakefulness and some drowsiness.  However, no clear stage I or stage II was seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES: Single focal slowing noted at F8/T4 with sharp contour preceding it in the frontal region, which appeared suspicious; however, no clearly pathologic.
SEIZURES:  None.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right anterior temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG revealed evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.  Please note that the sharp contour to the discharge appears somewhat suspicion and prolonged recording with deeper stages of sleep is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Right anterior temporal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 25-year-old woman with recurrent syncopal spells for the past 5 years.  They occur once per month with sudden loss of consciousness and  quick return to baseline.  She may be confused afterwards.  She may have an aura of a strange smell prior to the spells.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel  EKG.  This was a routine 20 minute EEG with photic stimulation.  Hyperventilation was deferred.  Impedances were generally under 5 kilo-ohms.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta.  There is significant eye movement artifact.  Drowsiness was characterized by generous beta.
Photic stimulation elicited vigorous driving with supra harmonic driving.
HEART RATE 48 BPM, irregular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The supraharmonic driving was a normal finding, but the electrocardiogram lead was abnormal.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  42 year old left handed gentleman who had a confusional state lasting 2 hours after cleaning out the garage.  Past history of asthma, renal and pancreatic cancer.
MEDICATIONS:  Prograf, Lorazepam, Vasotec, Rapamune
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.   This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is occasional isolated posteriorly predominant 4-5 Hz activity.  Features of drowsiness included attenuation of the alpha rhythm and the appearance of occasional vertex waves or posts. Hyperventilation produces bilateral rhythmic slowing.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is falling off to sleep and does not activate the record.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Occasional bursts of bilateral background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The intermittent background slowing is a non-specific finding which can be seen in a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy.  Correlation with imaging and medications is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Mildly abnormal EEG due to Occasional bursts of bilateral background slowing.

report:
History:	59 year old woman who presents to the hospital after 5 reported convulsions. Medications :  Tegretol, Topamax, Ativan
Sedation:
EEG Type: Technique:
Routine, awake & drowsy, portable
International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy
Description:
There is no PDR or AP gradient.  The background consists primarily of diffuse polymorph ic theta activity with underriding beta activity and overriding prominent polymorphic slow delta activity. Right frontocentral region contains frequent subtle stereotyped runs of activity that are concerning for electrographic
seizures. These runs start with right frontocentral (Fp2, F4, C4) medium amplitude fast activity that evolves into - 6 Hz rhythmic sharply contoured theta activity that spreads towards midline (Cz lead) and posteriorly (P4 lead). These runs last - 20-30 seconds and occur frequently throughout the recording. There is no obvious clinical correlate. During drowsiness, EMG artifact disappears.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed. Summary of  Findings:
Status epilepticus, right, frontocentral Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, moderate
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL 22-minutes awake and drowsy portable EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing and recurrent brief runs of stereotyped activity that are concerning for recurrent seizures (partial status epilepticus)  Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction , which is etiologically nonspecific. There epileptogenic structural abnormality over the right frontocentral region.
These findings were conveyed to the primary team at the time of the record review.  Patient was subsequently  placed on continuous  EEG monitoring.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL 22-minutes awake and drowsy portable EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing and recurrent brief runs of stereotyped activity that are concerning for recurrent seizures (partial status epilepticus)  Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction , which is etiologically nonspecific. There epileptogenic structural abnormality over the right frontocentral region

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  An 87-year-old male with a history of subdural hematoma, bilateral subdural burr holes including left frontal right central floor, evaluate for change in mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Famotidine, Zocor, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake record.
This is a technically somewhat challenging EEG in a patient who is not completely cooperative. There is a significant amount of muscle artifact. There were minor challenges with impedances leading to the appearance of a somewhat attenuated record in the right posterior region.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is low voltage, diffusely slow with a breach rhythm noted at C4.  There is a suggestion of a slow alpha rhythm with approximately 7-8 Hz.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.  Heart rate is 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Mild background slowing.
Clinical correlation.  Breach rhythm is an anticipated finding for a subject this age.  The slowing of the alpha rhythm and the excess data are nonspecific findings.  Previous EEGs were not available for comparison.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to Mild background slowing

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old gentleman admitted with a diagnosis of status epilepticus on 11/09/2011.

MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Keppra.

INTRODUCTION: Continuous digital video EEG monitoring was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is initially intubated. Afterwards, he is wearing a face mask. The patient is obtunded in the first section of the record and progressively more awake over time.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial sections of the record demonstrated a low voltage beta pattern particularly a frontal beta pattern and some shifting posterior in delta. There is some head rocking artifacts and sweat. Over the course of the long term monitor, stimulation of the patient starts to produce an arousal response. Later on, eye opening and eye closure is noted when someone is at the bedside with the patient and by the end of the EEG, he is intermittently awake with low voltage beta pattern. At other points, there is a somewhat slow background in wakefulness.

HR: 120 bpm max

IMPRESSION: This long term video EEG monitoring is remarkable for:
1. Initially slow pattern with frontal beta.
2. The absence of epileptiform activity.
3. The eventual appearance of a relatively normal awake pattern.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified. These findings should be placed into the appropriate clinical context.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This long term video EEG monitoring is remarkable for 1. Initially slow pattern with frontal beta. 2. The absence of epileptiform activity. 3. The eventual appearance of a relatively normal awake pattern.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 61-year-old male with traumatic brain injury, failure to thrive, status post PEG and trach.  The patient now awake and alert after multiple seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Trileptal.  Others, metoprolol.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20 minute digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is quite fragile, but awake.  He is responsive to questions.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  The right hemisphere is low voltage and relatively featureless.  The left hemisphere is remarkable for a craniotomy defect, but also periodic, high amplitude delta activity with a left central parietal spike and wave complex.  The spike and wave complex is periodic in nature and has the periodicity of about 8 per 10 seconds.  There is a small amount of waxing and waning of the epileptiform discharge, but no clear ictal pattern.  Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in theta in the left hemisphere as well as eye movement.
Heart rate:  80 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
A continuous periodic discharge, which includes a spike as well as periodic delta from the left hemisphere, maximum in the central parietal region.
Markedly slow and suppressed pattern from the right with volume conduction of the epileptiform discharge on the left to the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The patient seems to be awake and interactive despite the discharge described above.  In addition, stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting response on top of the periodic complex.  The discharge described above may be a chronic finding or a post-ictal finding, but does not appear to be to be a true seizure.   Ongoing vigilance is suggested. No clinical seizures noted at this time.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to A continuous periodic discharge, which includes a spike as well as periodic delta from the left hemisphere, maximum in the central parietal region. Markedly slow and suppressed pattern from the right with volume conduction of the epileptiform discharge on the left to the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 61-year-old male with epilepsy.  Has complex neurosurgical history including traumatic brain injury, subarachnoid hemorrhage, subdural hematoma, aphagia, skull defect, and past left-sided edema.  Past history of recurrent seizures in July 2014, recently admitted to the hospital in February 2015.  No recent reported seizures, but previous status epilepticus and pleds from the left.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, atorvastatin, Keppra, metoprolol, phenobarbital, and Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  This is a technically acceptable EEG with acceptable impedances, although there is a prominent craniotomy defect.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background from the right hemisphere includes a low voltage, continuous, primarily beta frequency pattern.  The left hemisphere demonstrates a prominent breach rhythm.  There are bursts of rhythmic 3 to 4 Hz activity of 1 to 3 seconds duration.  Some of these are associated with a sharp waves.  The bursts of rhythmic slowing with left mid temporal sharp waves are more prominent as the patient became drowsy.
Heart rate: 54 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
A marked interhemispheric asymmetry.
A low voltage slow pattern from the right with primarily beta frequency activity.
A pattern from the left with higher amplitude delta, a prominent reach, and a left mid temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this adult, who has been evaluated for status epilepticus and seizures.  The epileptiform activity today is primarily left mid temporal, which in some ways is similar to the continuous EEG monitoring.  A contrast to February 2015 EEG monitor, which identified epileptiform activity from the left hemisphere, but that epileptiform activity was much more prominent in the central parietal region.
This EEG continues to support a focal mechanism for this patient's seizures.  The epileptiform activity is in the region of the patient's head trauma.  The bilateral background slowing supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to A marked interhemispheric asymmetry. A low voltage slow pattern from the right with primarily beta frequency activity. A pattern from the left with higher amplitude delta, a prominent reach, and a left mid temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 61-year-old male with traumatic brain injury, left skull fracture, the patient presented with recurrent seizures today, some of which were prolonged.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, oxybutynin, Trileptal, Keppra, phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Impedances were generally under 5 kilohms with the exception of the T1-T2 electrodes.  The skull defect was as described above
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is quite drowsy.  Generous beta is noted but there is no well-defined alpha rhythm.  Breach rhythm is noted on the left with higher amplitude activity in this region.  Sharply contoured slowing was noted with T1 and T3 phase reversal with most bursts about 500 milliseconds in duration.  Tactile stimulation of the patient produces an arousal response with a glimpse of a 10 Hz alpha rhythm on the right and more of a theta pattern on the left.  The patient then returns to a drowsy state.
Heart rate 96 BPM
IMPRESSION:
Abnormal EEG due to continuous focal slowing from the left hemisphere.
Sharply contoured delta from the left maximum mid temporal.
Continuous
Mild slowing on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is supportive of a structural or functional process on the left.  For this patient with recurrent status epilepticus, this record demonstrates an ongoing irritative process.  This EEG is similar to previous studies of April 2015.
IMPRESSION:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  60 year old right handed male with complex partial epilepsy described as a feeling of spinning, hot flashes with loss of consciousness, and bowel and bladder incontinence.  Past history of closed head injury.

MEDICATIONS:  None.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage with generous beta and a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  With testing the alpha improves to 10 Hz.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  Wicket is noted in relaxed wakefulness. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record.  The patient is falling asleep during hyperventilation with vertex waves and spindles.  There are some normal variants, including small sharp spikes of sleep, but there is also some left temporal focal slowing.  The patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep.  Again, subtle left temporal focal slowing is noted.  Simple sharp waves, as are common in normal variants, are also noted in the left temporal region. These are again noted with photic stimulation.  The patient is once again falling asleep during photic stimulation.

HR:    60 bpm

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Subtle left temporal focal slowing.
2. Left temporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The left temporal sharp waves have a simple morphology as can be seen in a normal variant.  However, they occur in the context of focal slowing and are more suggestive of a focal mechanism for epilepsy.  In comparison to a previous EEG, both EEGs demonstrate some of the same normal variants and some of the same unique challenges.

DD:01/05/2012
DT:01/05/2012
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1. Subtle left temporal focal slowing. 2. Left temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 61-year-old gentleman with a 4-6-year history of seizures characterized by a feeling of spinning followed by hot flashes with loss of consciousness, incontinence of bowel and bladder, and postictal confusion.  Past history of closed head injury.  His last seizure was December 2012.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.


INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage with 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Temporal wicket was noted.  In addition, there is subtle, left temporal focal slowing which was accentuated by hyperventilation.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta followed by vertex waves.  The subtle focal slowing persists into stage I sleep.  Stage II sleep includes vertex waves and spindles.  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was relatively drowsy or in stage II sleep.  No driving response was identified.

Heart rate:  60 BPM.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to subtle left temporal focal slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No definitive sharp waves were seen in this EEG although left temporal sharp waves were noted in the 2 previous studies.  This EEG supports a structural or functional abnormality.  Of note, there was wicket and left temporal focal slowing and subtle underlying seizures may have been under recognized.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to subtle left temporal focal slowing.

report:

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.

Focal sharp waves in the left anterior temporal region.
Independent bitemporal slow waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  35 year old right handed male, with a seizure May 7, described as a feeling of euphoria and then lost consciousness. The patient is aware afterwards, when he is postictal, he is terrified and combative.  He reports 3-4 times per week he wakes up out of sleep feeling as if he may have had a seizure in sleep, is confused.  Past history of bipolar disease and positive family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Cymbalta, Tegretol, Tramadol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm of 40 mV.  There is a small amount of background theta noted in the background.
Hyperventilation is performed early in the record producing an increase in theta.  At the end of hyperventilation and as the patient drifts off into drowsiness, there is a subtle asymmetry with a bit more irregular theta on the left, but this disappears as the patient transitions towards stage II sleep.  Muscle artifact persists at times into the transition into sleep. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Subtle left temporal theta noted primarily in the transition to drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were seen.  The left temporal theta is a nonspecific finding which can be a seen in a structure or functional abnormality.  It can also be seen in individuals with epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Mildly abnormal EEG due to Subtle left temporal theta noted primarily in the transition to drowsiness.

report:

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.

There is anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  There is excess beta activity. report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old right handed woman with new-onset seizures and end-stage renal disease on hemodialysis.
MEDICATIONS:  Protonix, Hydralazine, Plavix, Metoprolol, ASA, Lipitor, Lisinopril.
REASON FOR STUDY:  New-onset seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Photic stimulation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that best reaches 7 Hz and which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is a lack of normal frontocentral beta.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.  Throughout the recording, there appears to be diffuse generalized theta, 5 to 7 Hz discharge, that is intermixed with bursts of high-amplitude delta seen bilaterally with multiple sharp components throughout those discharges that last, at times, up to 30 to 40 seconds.  There is no clear evolution or change during these discharges.  The morphology is consistent with triphasic waves, but there are some intermixed sharp waves that we will discuss in "abnormal discharges" below.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen independently at F7/T3, as well as F8/T4, and at times FP2.
Bursts of generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 50 microvolts.
Triphasic waves.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Multifocal sharp waves.
Bursts of generalized slow waves.
Triphasics in the midst of moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of multiple focal cerebral irritability and dysfunction, in addition to diffuse cerebral dysfunction which may be, at least in part, due to a metabolic derangement.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Multifocal sharp waves. Bursts of generalized slow waves. Triphasics in the midst of moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.

report:

MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and briefly drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, the EEG is well organized with a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm. As the patient becomes drowsy, there is somewhat asynchronous theta noted. In addition, there is a drop out of the alpha rhythm, a little faster in the left hemisphere with a little bit of slowing on the left relevant to the right. Hyperventilation produces an increase in theta. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving with harmonic and super-harmonic driving. Super-harmonic driving is seen with faster frequency activity. Stage I sleep includes vertex waves.
HR: 60 bpm with occasional PVCs.
IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1.Several asymmetries in the temporal region, particularly as the patient becomes drowsy with left greater than right temporal theta.
2. Disrupted alpha as the patient transitions toward sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were seen. In addition, there were no specific features to suggest an inherited mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to 1.Several asymmetries in the temporal region, particularly as the patient becomes drowsy with left greater than right temporal theta. 2. Disrupted alpha as the patient transitions toward sleep.

report:

The alpha rhythm is 50 to 60 microvolts, approximately 10 Hz on the left and consistently 0.7 Hz faster on the right.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in amplitude of the background. IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1. A slower alpha rhythm on the left.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 34-year-old male with history of alcohol withdrawal seizure, was discharged, when he had a general tonic-clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Serax, thiamine, Lovenox, nicotine patch, folic acid.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches at 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Bursts of generalized spike and waves which is anterior predominant and symmetric, and bursts of 3-4 Hz were seen intermittently, at times with preceding polyspikes throughout the recording.  Some of them appeared more asymmetric on the right than the left, but the majority appear symmetric.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of epilepsy.  The discharges seen above are most commonly seen with a generalized type of epilepsy.  However, some of them appeared slightly asymmetric and may suggest a possible focal onset with secondary generalization.  Repeated EEG capturing seizures or clinical followup may aid in elucidating the clear classification.  These findings were reported to the consult team as soon as the EEG was read.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old right handed female with left carotid stenosis and left CEA with a history of left stroke in June of 2012.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol, Percocet, Fentanyl, Vecuronium, Isoflurane
REASON FOR STUDY:  Left carotid endarterectomy.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed during left carotid endarterectomy using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during the entire operation.  Feedback was given to the surgeon as well as discussions with Anesthesia was had throughout the procedure.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The baseline record revealed a posterior dominant rhythm that reached 9-10 Hz which was reactive to eye opening.  At times there was some focal slowing seen at F7/T3 at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.  Otherwise, there was nice frontocentral beta. During the procedure the common carotid was clamped at 10:32:36 and the internal carotid was clamped at 10:31:50.  After clamping no change in the faster frequencies over the left hemisphere were noted and this was informed to the surgeon at 3 and 5 minutes.  The recording continued to be monitored and there continued to be no change at 11:48:13 a.m.  The carotids were unclamped and again there was no change in the faster frequencies in the recording.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG consistent with symmetric background of 9 Hz with no change in the background upon carotid artery clamping.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This was an uneventful left carotid endarterectomy with no changes.  Feedback was given continuously to the surgeon about the EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG consistent with symmetric background of 9 Hz with no change in the background upon carotid artery clamping.

report:

MEDICATIONS:  Lorazepam, phenobarbital, Tylenol, vitamin B12.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with an additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness, drowsiness, and stage I sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an excessive amount of diffuse beta.  The patient is mainly in drowsiness or sleep, stage I.
Hyperventilation produces no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal slow waves seen intermittently at T3 and at times at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Excessive theta in wakefulness.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  78 and regular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to bilateral independent mid temporal slowing, as well as excessive theta in wakefulness with superimposed diffuse beta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral mid temporal regions, but of which are nonspecific with regards to etiology.  In addition, there was evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology, but may be due at least in part to medication effect.  The excess beta supports a possibility of benzo or barbiturate use as a cause of the diffuse dysfunction.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to bilateral independent mid temporal slowing, as well as excessive theta in wakefulness with superimposed diffuse beta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 56-year-old man who presented with a chief complaint of left-sided numbness and shaking.  While in the emergency room he was observed having shaking while in the CAT scan.  Past medical history is notable for diabetes, hypertension and neuropathy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Zolpidem, lisinopril, aspirin, insulin, and others.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were  performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of well modulated low amplitude 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  No clear sleep is captured.  Intermittent polymorphic delta activity is captured over the right anterior temporal region.  Hyperventilation produces no change in the background.  Photic stimulation induces symmetric occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
Intermittent moderate right anterior temporal slowing.
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 56-year-old man with a history of left-sided numbness and weakness and shaking and falling down stairs.  History of diabetes, hypertension, and neuropathy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Altace, Ativan, and Oxycontin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation and hyperventilation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a background, which appears to have diffuse beta and mainly in sleep.  There is no clear posterior dominant rhythm, but this may be obscured by the diffuse beta.  Overall, the patient easily drowses off and is in limited wakefulness.  During hyperventilation, there appears to be some bursts of rhythmic bifrontal slowing.  Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient reaches stage I and stage II sleep.  Please note that at times there is also rhythmic bursts of theta, which are anterior maximal, which are most consistent with drowsiness, however, some of them have a slightly suspicious appearance.
SEIZURES:  None.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
HEART RATE:  78.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG.  The excessive beta seen may be due at least in part to medication effect.  Please note that even though no clear posterior dominant rhythm could be seen, this may be due to the excessive beta, and in addition, the rhythmic anterior theta is likely due to drowsiness, however, if clinical suspicion for epilepsy remains, a more prolonged EEG may be helpful in elucidating or clarifying the diagnosis.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.

report:
HISTORY:  A 68-year-old woman, admitted with known cardiac


pathology, admitted to the medicine service for chest pain.

Subsequently earlier today patient had abrupt right-sided

weakness with head deviation and neglect.  Initial imaging was


unrevealing for acute stroke and then patient became more

globally confused.  Found to have Acute infarct in the posterior

limb of the left internal capsule.




MEDICATIONS:  Unknown.




INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed at

bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1

channel EKG.  This is a technically challenging record in a


patient who was poorly interactive with significant muscle

artifact.




DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background initially has low

voltage with generous beta and a glimpse of an 11 Hz alpha rhythm

and some central alpha and beta frequency activity.  There are


isolated bursts of slowing with lower voltage delta noted in the




background.  At the very end of the record, the patient seems to

be becoming more drowsy with a decrease in muscle and an increase


in slowing.




Heart rate 60 bpm.



IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging, but abnormal EEG due to:

1. Excess beta.


2. Intermittent isolated bursts of delta.




CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal features could be identified in

this record.  There were no epileptiform features seen.  Overall,

this EEG is more supportive of a global disturbance of cerebral

function.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging, but abnormal EEG due to 
1. Excess beta. 

2. Intermittent isolated bursts of delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 21-year-old woman with an unknown early developmental history, depression, and posttraumatic stress syndrome.  The patient has been having an episode to right arm rotation and had a seizure with loss of consciousness and incontinence.  She continues to feel, as if she is experiencing myoclonic jerks.  I got interrupted and I did not do the history.

MEDICATIONS: Lorazepam, Remeron

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This is a bedside record without hyperventilation and photic stimulation.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there was a 10Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness was characterized by an increase in beta.

In wakefulness, there were bursts of frontally predominant rhythmic high amplitude 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity.

No impairment of awareness was noted with the events.  The patient was able to answer questions even with very brief discharges, but again discharges are typically 1 to 1.5 seconds after going slow activity, lasting an another second at maximum duration.

The technologist notes 1 or 2 movements of the patient, but no definitive myoclonus was captured.

Heart rate 84 BPM.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike in wave activity occurring in brief bursts.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  For this young adult with unclear medical history and a 1st ever seizure and myoclonus, this EEG is most compatible with a inherited, generalized mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1. frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike in wave activity occurring in brief bursts.

report:

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Trileptal, Xanax, Claritin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and asleep record.  It was a technically acceptable record.

Mu rhythm was noted, but testing was not performed to confirm this.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  Deeper stages of sleep were not sustained.
Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving with vigorous supra-harmonic driving.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In contrast to a previous EEG 2 years ago, there were no bursts of 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  If this patient is thought to have frequent seizures, more prolonged EEG monitoring may be obtained.  These findings may be carefully correlated with clinical symptoms in this individual, whose previous EEG pattern suggested that she is at risk for myoclonic or tonic-clonic epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.

report:

Medications:	DILANTIN, KEPPRA
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
The background consists of polymorphic low amplitude 8-9 Hz activity posteriorly, poor AP gradient
and excess polymorphic theta activity.  The background improves during sleep: symmetrical sleep
spindles and vertex waves are captured.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.  A single
EKG lead demonstrates heart rate of ~ 49 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild
Disorganization, mild
Sleep, stage 2
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and asleep 28-minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing and
disorganization. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild diffuse cerebral
dysfunction.  A single EKG lead demonstrates heart rate of ~ 49 bpm.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and asleep 28-minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing and
disorganization. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild diffuse cerebral
dysfunction.  A single EKG lead demonstrates heart rate of ~ 49 bpm

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 28-year-old right-handed male who has a history of epilepsy since 2007, has about 1 seizure every 1-2 years, presently not on any medications.  Last seizure was several nights ago.  The seizure was preceded by a severe headache.

MEDICATIONS:  None.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.  There was a technical limitation with the T6 electrode which persisted even after it was fixed by the technician.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of 9.5 Hz in frequency and 20-40 microvolts in amplitude best seen in the occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  In drowsiness there is diffuse rhythmic theta bursts in all the channels.

There is an occasional burst of focal slowing seen in the left frontocentral region.

Hyperventilation was performed which showed a diffuse slowing of the record and increase in amplitude.

Photic stimulation showed minimal driving at 13 Hz but no abnormalities.

Heart rate 60 beats per minute.

IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to occasional bursts of focal slowing on the left frontocentral and frontotemporal regions.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is suggestive of a possible underlying structural abnormality in the left frontocentral and frontotemporal regions.  No epileptiform discharges were identified.  A more prolonged EEG recording may be more helpful to identify spikes or sharp waves.

Attestation: I personally reviewed the EEG with the trainee and agree with the report.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to occasional bursts of focal slowing on the left frontocentral and frontotemporal regions.

symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over

beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.

sleep spindles and K complexes appear.  Patient transitions rapidly between wakefulness and
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.

symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does
not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
Sleep, stage 2
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 64-year-old gentleman with history of seizures and motor vehicle accident status post fall and loss of consciousness.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:  Significant for hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and back pain.
MEDICATIONS:  Vicodin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using the standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is a technically limited study due to muscle artifact in most of the recording.  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 8-8.5 Hz in frequency noted for a short period of time in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 6-7 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness.  There is generalized low amplitude beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm and slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact, as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves.  Stage 2 sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in no driving response.  Hyperventilation was associated with slowing of the background activity.  Heart rate was 80 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically limited EEG due to a muscle artifact in most of this recording.  This is an abnormal EEG due to slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm and background activity during wakefulness and sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm and background activity are suggestive of cerebral dysfunction due to toxic, metabolic, infectious, or degenerative disorders.  The generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including benzodiazepine, barbiturate, or could be due to anxiety or hypothyroidisms.  No epileptiform abnormalities were seen in this record.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  A repeat EEG is recommended due to technically limited recording.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a technically limited EEG due to a muscle artifact in most of this recording.  This is an abnormal EEG due to slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm and background activity during wakefulness and sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this record.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.

There is presence of low-amplitude diffuse beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically. report:
DURATION OF STUDY:  Study date 03/26/2013 through 03/27/2013, for a total of 15 hours.  However, due to technical difficulties only 5 hours could be reviewed.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  39-year-old woman with episode of bilateral arm stiffness and gaze deviated to the right.  Has 4-5 seizures in the past month, screaming, with a history of Lennox-Gastaut, mental retardation.  Follow-up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Ativan, famotidine, Lovenox, topiramate, Flagyl, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  A long-term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with the addition of anterior temporal single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software in addition to nurse's notes were used to review the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm and frontocentral beta.  Overall, there are theta delta mixed frequencies intermingled with multiple multifocal spikes which I will describe in Abnormal Discharges.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Multifocal spikes seen at O1, O2, T6, Fp1, Fp2, T3, and P4.  However, the spikes are mainly seen at O1 and O2 and Fp1/Fp2.
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen almost continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  During the record, there are multiple seizures which in the EEG appear to begin suddenly and display rhythmic, sharply contoured theta intermixed with beta that at times appears to be maximal frontally and then centrally with an overlying rhythmic occipital sharp focus.  The maximal focus or origin of the seizure is unclear.  It is also atypical as it does not appear to evolve as it suddenly starts, remains in the EEG at almost this irregular but continuous frequency, and then appears to slowly dissipate.  During these discharges, the patient appears to move her head side to side and sometimes moves her arms in a wild fashion.  On 1 occasion, her mouth appeared to twitch in the video.  The duration of these episodes can be anywhere from 1 or 2 minutes to prolonged 38-minute seizure.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to multiple seizures with unclear origin and multifocal spikes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of multiple generalized seizures with unclear origin as well as multiple areas of irritability and structural dysfunction as well as diffuse dysfunction consistent with diagnosis of symptomatic generalized epilepsy.
These findings were communicated to the primary team as soon as the EEG was read.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to multiple seizures with unclear origin and multifocal spikes.

Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen almost continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  Again during the recording there are multiple seizures, about 13 of them, some of them lasting up to 30 minutes where the EEG appears to seldom display a rhythmic sharply contoured theta intermixed at beta and at times maximally frontally and centrally with an overlying rhythmic occipital sharp focus.  It is unclear where the origin of the seizure is.  It is also atypical in that it does not clearly evolve, it just suddenly starts and appears to slowly stop.  The patient appears to move her head side to side and arms moving in a wild flinging fashion.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to multiple seizures with unclear origin and multifocal spikes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of multiple generalized seizure of unclear origin as well as multiple areas of irritability and structural dysfunction as well as diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is consistent with the diagnosis of symptomatic generalized epilepsy.  These findings were conveyed to the primary team.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to multiple seizures with unclear origin and multifocal spikes.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 53-year-old female, who was admitted for change in mental status.  She has a history of diabetes, hypertension, depression, and breast cancer.

MEDICATIONS:  Insulin, Haldol, lorazepam, labetalol, vancomycin, aztreonam, lisinopril.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  At 11:22:17 a.m., there is a seizure onset at 9-10 Hz alpha activity, maximum in left occipital region (01) with spread to left posterior quadrant and right occipital region, after 20 seconds seizure activity continues as 4-5 Hz theta activity maximum in left posterior quadrant for 40 seconds.  This activity was followed by sharply contoured delta activity with bihemispheric distribution for 90 seconds.  It was followed by postictal attenuation noted in bihemispheric region.  Clinically, patient did not show shaking or jerking, but per video patient seemed less responsive with eyes closed.  Towards the end of this recording, there were left periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges noted in left posterior quadrant region lasting for several minutes with no evolution. There was almost continuous left posterior quadrant slowing almost continuous noted during this recording.

IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to;
1. Electrographic partial seizure originating from left occipital/left posterior quadrant region.
2. Left posterior quadrant slowing.
3. Left periodic lateralized epileptiform

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Focal slowing is a consistent with functional or structural abnormality in left posterior quadrant. PLEDs (Periodic Lateralized Epileptiform Discharges) are consistent with left hemisphere structural lesion (tumor, infection, and stroke). It could also be due to a post-ictal state. One episode of electrographic focal seizure is consistent with partial epilepsy in the setting of Hx of seizure. Clinical correlation and long-term monitoring are recommended.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to;
1. Electrographic partial seizure originating from left occipital/left posterior quadrant region. 2. Left posterior quadrant slowing. 3. Left periodic lateralized epileptiform
