report:
LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  27 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 53-year-old woman with a history of seizures, diabetes, hypertension, depression and breast cancer.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Topamax, insulin, Dilantin,  Lipitor, Klonopin, lisinopril, aspirin and others.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to standard the 10-20  system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  During maximal wakefulness the posterior dominant rhythm consists of 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  Fast alpha variant is occasionally observed.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep), 2 to 3 second bursts of diffuse sharply contoured theta activity, symmetrical sleep spindles and vertex waves are noted.  Hyperventilation is performed with   poor effort and does not result in significant change in the background.  Stepped photic stimulation does not result in significant change in the background.  The patient is either drowsy or asleep throughout most of the recording.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
Stage 2 sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal mostly drowsy or asleep and briefly awake 27 minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal mostly drowsy or asleep and briefly awake 27 minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 64-year-old gentleman with memory loss, atrial fibrillation, asthma and hearing impairment.
MEDICATIONS:  Diltiazem, nitroglycerin, aspirin, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is an alpha rhythm of 8 to 8.3 Hz.  Most typically when the patient is maximally awake, the EEG is well organized with 8 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta.  In hyperventilation and following hyperventilation there are rare bursts of slowing in the temporal regions as the patient becomes drowsy.  Vertex waves are noted in stage I sleep.  The patient transitions in and out of stage I sleep and there is a slight asymmetry with slight disruption of faster frequency activity noted just in the transition in and out of sleep on the right.  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting and out of stage II sleep, and results in scan driving.
Heart rate 84 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
Shifting slowing in drowsiness and in the transition to stage II sleep, out of the acceptable range of normal for an adult of this age.
Slight focality with disruption of faster frequency activity on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The slowing of the alpha rhythm is a nonspecific finding, but supports an organic cause for this patient's clinical complaints.  Slowing of the alpha rhythm is a nonspecific finding, but can be seen in dementia, as well as a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy.  The subtle focal features described above may be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to Slowing of the alpha rhythm. Shifting slowing in drowsiness and in the transition to stage II sleep, out of the acceptable range of normal for an adult of this age. Slight focality with disruption of faster frequency activity on the right.

report:
LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  24 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 38-year-old man who presents with a new onset seizure lasting approximately 10 minutes.  There was associated tongue biting and loss of consciousness.  Of note, the patient was noted to have seizure activity approximately 20 to 30 minutes prior to this EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications include Dilantin, Norvasc, and hydralazine.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of polymorphic moderate amplitude 9 to 9.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  The anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient is weak.  Additional diffuse polymorphic theta activity is present.  Diffuse excess beta is captured, as well.  During sleep, the background attenuates and symmetrical sleep spindles are captured.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  A single EKG lead demonstrates a heart rate up to 120 beats a minute.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Excess beta.
Stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Sinus tachycardia.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 24-minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing.  This finding indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction that in this case could partially be related to an excessively sedated/drowsy patient.  Excess beta could be secondary to medication effect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Sinus tachycardia with a heart rate up to 120 beats a minute is captured in a single EKG lead.

MEDICATIONS:  Norvasc, hydralazine, and hydrochlorothiazide.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed, but sleep was not achieved.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10.5 hertz, 70 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low-voltage, frontal central beta activity.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and a small increase in beta, but sleep was not sustained.  Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicited supra harmonic driving.
Heart rate:  78 bpm.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 62-year-old woman with a pituitary tumor, asthma, peripheral vascular disease, diabetes, hypertension, with episode of syncope versus seizure, occurred while watching TV, the last one happened 2 weeks ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Hydralazine, metoprolol, Neurontin, lovastatin, insulin, coenzyme, fentanyl patch, albuterol, Symbicort, MiraLAX, oxycodone, Lasix, and amitriptyline.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage I and stage II.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen rarely at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz, amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Heart rate 78.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to rare left anterior temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to rare left anterior temporal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 62-year-old right-handed woman with history of hypertension, asthma, and CHF who presents to EMU for seizure differential diagnosis.  She has episodes of losing time between 5 minutes to 2 hours.
MEDICATIONS:  Hydralazine, metoprolol, Neurontin, lovastatin, insulin, oxycodone, and amitriptyline.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG monitoring was performed in the EMU using the standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  An automated seizure and spike detection system and a patient activated alarm system were used.  Records were reviewed daily for EEG abnormalities and clinical events.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Interictal EEG from 08/12/2013 to 08/15/2013:  In the most alert state, there is a posterior dominant rhythm with frequency of 8.5-10.5 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is presence of frontal central low amplitude beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  A stage I sleep was characterized by disappearance of alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of eye blink and muscle artifact, as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves.  Stage II sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Slow-wave sleep and REM sleep were also captured.  Focal slow waves seen rarely at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolt.
Clinical events:  On 08/14/2013 at 05:37 a.m., there was a push button event as the patient experienced 1 episode of missing time, slurred speech, disorientation.  There were no EEG ictal changes associated with this event.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal video EEG monitoring study due to rare left focal slowing at F7/T3.  Patient had 1 event as described above during this recording while she was awake and reports 1 episode of missing time with disorientation.  This event was associated with no ictal change on EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Focal slowing could be due to structural or functional dysfunction of underlying brain in the subcortical white matter in the left hemisphere.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  Patient had 1 event of missing time and disorientation for a few minutes with no EEG correlations.  This is one of the typical event that patient experiences as a seizure activity.  The capturing of missing time and confusion without any associated ictal change on EEG may be suggestive of a simple partial seizure since simple partial seizures are not always captured on scalp EEG or it could be suggestive of a nonepileptic event.  This EEG monitoring does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy since all of the patient's habitual events have not been captured.  If seizure remain a clinical concern, a repeat video EEG monitoring may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal video EEG monitoring study due to rare left focal slowing at F7/T3.  Patient had 1 event as described above during this recording while she was awake and reports 1 episode of missing time with disorientation.  This event was associated with no ictal change on EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 19-year-old woman with a history of Lyme disease, gastroparesis, and an episode of staring with short periods of confusion.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Protonix, Lovenox, Xarelto, and oxycodone.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens up with posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There an excessive amount of diffused beta seen throughout the recording.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and sleep, stage I and stage II.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep electroencephalogram.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Please note that the excessive beta may be due to medication affect.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep electroencephalogram.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Recurrent seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 19-year-old woman with Lyme disease, gastroparesis, episodes of staring spells and confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Toradol, oxycodone, Lovenox, Protonix.
INTRODUCTION:  A long-term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software along the patient's alarm events as well as nurses notes were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some electrode artifact during the episodes as described below.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENTS:  The patient had 3 events during the admission.  The first one occurred at 7:00 p.m. after the doctor asked her to raise and lower her hands, and breathe heavily.  The patient started complaining of a headache, later ringing in the ears and became unresponsive with the eyes twitching and rolling backwards with forced eye closure, and some trembling.  The patient also had complaints of some right-sided numbness before the episode started.  The patient remained unresponsive to verbal motor commands until about 7:06:28 p.m.  She had a second event at 8:53:40 p.m. with a similar presentation of eyes rolling back and becoming unresponsive to verbal commands, and then trembling lasting until 8:58 p.m.  At the end she cried just as she did in the first event.  Then she had a third event occurring at 9:53:08 p.m. lasting until 9:58:47 p.m. again with eye fluttering,  trembling and following commands, and afterwards crying.  During all 3 events even though the last 1 there was some substantial electrode artifact and muscle artifact there was no clear EEG changes.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  The 3 episodes which were described above had no EEG correlate and clinically appeared to be consistent with her typical spells.  The lack of any EEG abnormalities during the event is diagnostic of a psychogenic nonepileptic event.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 19-year-old woman with gastroparesis, staring spells, and confusion.  History of seizures with aura of headache, lightheadedness, ringing in her ears, and loss of vision.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a somewhat unusual background.  There are sections of the record with some 5-6 Hz posteriorly predominant activity with a 9 Hz mu rhythm.  The posterior dominant activity is slow, notched, and somewhat regular, suggesting that there may be an underlying somewhat irregular alpha subharmonic.  Prominent lambda confounds this picture.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements.  The somewhat notched posterior predominant pattern is seen when the patient is awake, as well as she starts to drift into drowsiness.
Hyperventilation seems to accentuate underlying, posteriorly predominant slowing.
Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response.
Heart rate:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This must be considered an abnormal EEG due to:  Somewhat slow irregular theta frequency activity in the posterior regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Harmonic since subharmonics are normal findings, but there is clearly irregular posteriorly predominant theta that cannot be considered a normal variant.  This EEG differs from a previous EEG on January 4, 2013 which was a normal routine study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This must be considered an abnormal EEG due to:  Somewhat slow irregular theta frequency activity in the posterior regions.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 50-year-old woman with a history of resection of a left frontal meningioma in 2009, mastectomy for breast malignancy, hypertension, depression, RSD, hyperlipidemia, pseudoseizures, right facial paucity, right hemibody shaking, unresponsiveness, and head shaking episodes.
MEDICATIONS:  Topamax, Ativan, Prilosec, Zocor, Effexor, Neurontin, baclofen, and metoprolol.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with addition of anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness only.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal swelling seen intermittently at C3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.
EPISODES:  During this recording the patient had an episode where she suddenly became unresponsive and her face on the right appeared to look slightly drooped.  She would not follow commands but would response to painful stimuli and at 1 point would answer questions.  Mainly she remains with her eyes closed and her right face appeared slightly drooped.  However, if they stimulated her, her eyes would open and she remained with a right facial droop except when talking.  This episode lasted about 4 minutes after which the patient started responding and then she started shaking her head again in a back-and-forth high-frequency motion, again appeared to be unresponsive, lasted for 30 seconds, stopped, and started again, and she was responsive in between.  After the episode she was clinically responsive and knew the code word.
Heart rate:  84.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The episode described above had no clear EEG correlate.  As such she may represent simple partial seizure which in 25% of the cases does not have EEG signature or alternatively may represent a non-epileptic event.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake EEG.

report:
LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 44-year-old woman who presents with an episode of tonic clonic convulsion characterized by first head turning to the left, eyes rolling back and convulsing.
Past medical history is significant for alcohol abuse, pancreatitis and substance abuse.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilaudid, Keppra, Topamax, Cipro, Serax.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The procedure done reaches approximately 8 to 8.5 Hz.  Alpha activity:  The anterior to posterior frequency gradient is present, but weak.  Additional diffuse polymorphic theta activity is present.  Abundant frequent bursts of moderate to high amplitude diffuse frontal with predominant rhythmic delta (FIRDA) are captured.  Frequent theta bursts increases during drowsiness.  No clear normal sleep architecture is present; however, quiescence is captured.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Photic stimulation resulted in symmetrical signal driving.  A single EKG lead demonstrates regular heart rate.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
FIRDA abundant.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to mild diffuse slowing (FIRDA).  These findings indicate etiologically nonspecific cerebral dysfunction.  FIRDA could be seen in encephalopathy, increased intracranial pressure and bilateral deep white matter lesions. The lack of epileptiform discharges on routine EEG does not preclude clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to mild diffuse slowing (FIRDA).  These findings indicate etiologically nonspecific cerebral dysfunction.  FIRDA could be seen in encephalopathy, increased intracranial pressure and bilateral deep white matter lesions. The lack of epileptiform discharges on routine EEG does not preclude clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Dizziness and syncope.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 45-year-old woman with a history of stroke 20 years ago and right-sided weakness, hypertension, left ventricular hypertrophy, complains of dizziness, syncope and weakness, profuse sweating for 2-3 months; last episode was 1 week ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Lotrel, Diovan, Catapres, Coreg, hydralazine.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some muscle artifact in the temporal region.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Infrequent focal slowing seen at T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  48.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left mid temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left mid temporal region, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left mid temporal focal slowing.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 70-year-old woman with a right frontal craniotomy on July 6, 2012, and seizures a couple of days after and had surgery.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Cozaar, Lopid, Flonase, albuterol.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  Patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedure included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is mild excessive beta seen diffusely.  the patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.
Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges which included only photic stimulation.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at F8/F4 while in wakefulness and sleep.
Focal slow waves seen at F8/F4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-50 microvolts.  There is an increased amplitude and presence of faster frequencies consistent with a breach rhythm in that region.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  Eighty-four.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram due to right frontal slowing and sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of  localization-related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the right frontal region.  In addition, there is evidence focal cerebral dysfunction in the right frontal region consistent with the known surgery.   No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram due to right frontal slowing and sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 50-year-old male with bipolar schizoaffective disorder, admitted to the trauma service after head trauma 1 day prior to this EEG.  Past history of alcohol, cocaine, opiates, benzodiazepine, and PCP ingestion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Ativan, fentanyl, midazolam.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed at bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient had noted to have been agitated, yelling, and cursing when awake and had been sedated for the study.  The patient is wearing a hard collar.  This is a technically acceptable EEG with impedances under 5 kilos with the exception of the T1-T2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a continuous, relatively low voltage pattern.  Despite the sedation, intermittent arousals were noted with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm followed by more of a beta state with a lower voltage beta pattern and then a transition to stage 2 sleep with spindles and POSTS.
The technologist stimulates the patient and the patient arouses briefly with a 7 Hz background and a glimpse of a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.
Heart rate:  90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG primarily in sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  With arousals, a normal awake pattern was noted.  The pattern described above is compatible with pharmacologic sedation.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing when the patient is out of the ICU and able to cooperate is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG primarily in sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 49 -year-old woman with a history of seizures for the last several years, who is currently admitted for the presurgical evaluation.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications include Vimpat off, Lyrica 150 mg in the morning and 75 mg in the evening, Seroquel.
INTRODUCTION:  Condition of the recording:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  Medical staff notes and nursing notes were reviewed.  The patient was equipped with event button.  The study was reviewed intermittently throughout the 24 hour recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 10 to 11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep, symmetrical sleep spindles, vertex waves, slow wave sleep,  K-complexes and several epochs of REM sleep are captured.  There is occasional polymorphic theta and delta activity observed over the left temporal region.  Additionally, somewhat monomorphic theta is observed intermittently over the left temporal region.  This activity does not evolve.  This activity is not present during sleep.
FINDINGS:  Occasional mild left temporal slowing.
Intermittent periods of monomorphic theta runs over the left temporal region that are present only over the left temporal region.
No events or seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 21 hour continuous audio video EEG monitoring due to occasional mild left temporal slowing.  This finding indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology.  Runs of monomorphic theta observed over the left temporal region during sleep of unclear clinical significance since they disappear as the patient falls asleep.  This left temporal monomorphic theta has been present since the beginning of the monitoring.  No electrographic seizures or events occurred.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 21 hour continuous audio video EEG monitoring due to occasional mild left temporal slowing.  This finding indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology.  Runs of monomorphic theta observed over the left temporal region during sleep of unclear clinical significance since they disappear as the patient falls asleep.  This left temporal monomorphic theta has been present since the beginning of the monitoring.  No electrographic seizures or events occurred

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old woman who had an episode of syncope on 07/05/2013, while she was having a tilt-table test.
MEDICATIONS:  Albuterol.
INTRODUCTION:  This is 1-hour digital video EEG performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG opens to posterior dominant rhythm at 10 Hz with mid temporal delta activity at times and 7 Hz theta activity in the background.  Of note, there is left temporal sharp waves during a sleep that is out of criteria for normal variant.  In a stage I and a stage II of a sleep, the temporal sharp waves are more prominent especially on the left side.  These sharp waves can potentially be epileptogenic.  There is also prominent hypersynchronous theta activity and thorough sharp waves in transition from stage I and stage II of sleep, which again are out of proportion for normal variant.  At times, there is hypnagogic hypersynchronous activity seen.
Heart rate was 78 b.p.m.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is mildly abnormal due to:
Rare left temporal sharp waves.
Subtle focal slowing on the left side.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG has multiple normal variants and due to mild left rare temporal slowing that is more pronounced during the sleep.  This could be also potentially epileptogenic.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is mildly abnormal due to Rare left temporal sharp waves. Subtle focal slowing on the left side.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 21-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 17, recent MVA.  Seizures previously described as tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Pentasa, methotrexate, Celexa, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Impedances were acceptable, although T1 and T2 electrodes slightly greater than 5 kohms.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a low voltage, 11 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  In the initial sections of the record there is frequent eye blink, but there is also a subtle area of sharply contoured slowing in the right mid temporal region at T2 and T4.  Hyperventilation is performed slightly after this finding is noted and produces an increase in amplitude, an increase in beta and does not clearly accentuate this finding which is noted again as the patient becomes drowsy with slow rolling eye movements.  This subtle lower voltage focal slowing in the right mid to posterior temporal region has almost a periodicity and when there is some overlying alpha frequency activity there is appearance of a low voltage sharp but without an after going slow wave.  It persisted into drowsiness with an increase in beta but deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
The patient was relatively drowsy during photic stimulation which did elicit a driving response.
Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to right mid to posterior temporal focal slowing at times sharply contoured with a frequency of approximately 4 Hz.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are very similar to the previous study 05/13/2013.  There is a slight periodicity of the focal slowing.  These findings contrast to previous EEGs in childhood which are reported to have demonstrated generalized spike and wave activity.  But these findings were similar on the previous study and therefore are not likely to have been associated with the car accident and concussion.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to right mid to posterior temporal focal slowing at times sharply contoured with a frequency of approximately 4 Hz.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 22-year-old young woman with seizures beginning in 2007 consisting of generalized tonic-clonic convulsions with tongue biting.  She has not had any recent seizure activity.  The study is done as a followup.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Routine 21-channel EEG was performed utilizing the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement along with hyperventilation and photic stimulation EKG and EOG monitoring.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The white cresting background reveals a large amount of 50-70 microvolt amplitude posterior alpha rhythm with a large amount of 18-30 Hz low voltage of her frontocentral regions.  Large amount of eye blink artifacts were seen throughout much of the waking record.  Moderate amount of muscle artifact was also seen.  With eye opening, there was attenuation of alpha activity.  Periods of drowsiness were seen with attenuation of posterior rhythmic activity and increased slow to medium amount due to symmetric irregular slowing.  Hyperventilation for 3 minutes produced mild increased low to medium amounts.  Bilateral delta and theta frequency slowing.  Photic stimulation was accompanied by symmetric occipital driving.  EKG monitor showed normal sinus rhythm at 60 per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.  A normal EEG cannot exclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, a sleep deprived tracing capturing stage II sleep or more prolonged ambulatory EEG may provide additional information.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.  A normal EEG cannot exclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, a sleep deprived tracing capturing stage II sleep or more prolonged ambulatory EEG may provide additional information

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  19-year-old with and epilepsy since age 5 or 6.  Seizure free for 10 years until he had 2 breakthrough seizures over 2 days with loss of consciousness, tongue biting, postictal confusion.  Headaches precede the seizures.

MEDICATIONS:  None.

INTRODUCTION:  Routine 24-minute outpatient digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  Impedances were acceptable under 5 kilohms with the exception of the T1-T2 electrodes.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is abnormal.  At best, there is an 8 Hz alpha rhythm but there is excess background theta.  In addition, there are occasional bursts of background delta some of which are a bit more posteriorly predominant.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the record and accentuated this finding.  As the patient became drowsy after hyperventilation, there was some shifting arrhythmic slowing a bit more prominent in the posterior regions.  Deeper stages of sleep were not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.

HEART RATE:  40 BPM.

IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background slowing.
2. Bursts of frontal slow delta.
3. Occasional shifting occipital slowing.
4. Bradycardia.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  To put this EEG in the proper context, it is important to know when this patient had his most recent seizures.  This may represent a postictal finding.  Comparison with previous EEGs is suggested.
The ordering physician will be contacted regarding the bradycardia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to 1. Marked background slowing. 2. Bursts of frontal slow delta. 3. Occasional shifting occipital slowing. 4. Bradycardia.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 38-year-old male. status post traumatic brain Injury more than a decade ago with gunshot wound to the face and orbit, the patient has had difficult to control seizures with a facial abrasion 1 month ago.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Xanax, others.
Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 1D-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This was a 1-hour EEG. It was a technically satisfactory study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm identified bilaterally with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta. Breach rhythm is noted with artifacts noted in the right frontotemporal region. Sharply contoured slowing is noted as the patient becomes drowsy.
Hyperventilation clearly accentuates focal slowing In the right hemisphere with sharply contoured slowing, primarily seen from the right, and rare sharp waves. Features of drowsiness include an increase In background slowing and of course accentuation of the focal slowing. There is disruption of faster frequency activity noted in the right frontal region in sleep. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION: This Is an abnormal EEG due to:
1. Intermittent focal slowing noted In the right hemisphere, particularly frontotemporal region
accentuated by hyperventilation and sleep.
2. Sharply contoured slowing and rare sharp waves maximum F8/T4.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are congruent with a past history of traumatic brain injury, and a focal mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: This Is an abnormal EEG due to 1. Intermittent focal slowing noted In the right hemisphere, particularly frontotemporal region
accentuated by hyperventilation and sleep. 2. Sharply contoured slowing and rare sharp waves maximum F8/T4.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 22-year-old woman who was shoved 10 the floor on the 23rd, no loss of consciousness, but then had 2 episodes that were described as seizures. Previous, "minor" head injury without loss or consciousness.
MEDICATIONS: Depacon, Zofran, tramadol, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode
placement with 1 channel EKG. Impedances were acceptable aside from the T1-T2 electrodes.
Electrode placement was perhaps suboptimal due to some or the features of the vertex waves.
DESCRIPTION OF THE As the tracing begins, the patient is asleep. Features of stage 1 and
stage 2 sleep are noted with vertex activity and spindles. Intermittent bursts of delta were noted. There
is prominent beta. There is a slight asymmetry noted with a bit of slowing noted on the left with a bit more
delta on the left relative to the right Eye movement and EKG artifacts as well were noted 10 the
background.

Hyperventilation was performed early in the record. Hyperventilation clearly accentuates focal slowing
from the left hemisphere, and in hyperventilation, discrete left temporal sharp waves emerge. As the
hyperventilation concludes, the patient drifts off back to sleep with generous beta and again focal slowing
noted from the left. In more prolonged stage II sleep, some of the vertex waves and spindles are slightly
asymmetric. Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep. II does not
significantly activate the record, but the focal sharp waves and focal slowing persist In sleep, there are
some lower voltage, discreet bilateral spikes noted with a bit of a field to the left.
At the close of the record, the patient is transitioning back into stage II sleep, but limited wakefulness was
identified with a symmetric brief posterior dominant rhythm.
Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG due to:
1. Focal stowing from the left temporal region.
2. Discrete fell temporal spikes.
3. A number of discrete, bifrontal spikes.
4. Hypersomnolence.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Th1s EEG supports a structural or functional process on the left with focal
epileptiform features These findings may be correlated with Imaging
This patients medications should also include Remeron and Abilify.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal EEG due to 1. Focal stowing from the left temporal region. 2. Discrete fell temporal spikes. 3. A number of discrete, bifrontal spikes. 4. Hypersomnolence.

report:
History:	22 year old woman with a history of seizures.  Patient is currently 6 months pregnant.
Medications:	Trileptal, Zofran, (Patient stated on drugs for depression, but can not remember)
Sedation:	None
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes, awake,
drowsy, asleep, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10-10.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is noted.  During drowsiness, the background
slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep) are
abundant.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and
symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.  Patient is asleep throughout the majority of the
No clear focal slowing is present.  No clear epileptiform discharges are present.  A single sharp
transient is noted over the left midtemporal region.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep), prominent
Beta, excessive
Sleep, stage 2, abundant
Sharp transients, one, left temporal
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 23-minute briefly awake and mostly asleep EEG. The presence of a single left
temporal sharp transient is of uncertain clinical significance.  Excessive beta activity could be
secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 23-minute briefly awake and mostly asleep EEG. The presence of a single left
temporal sharp transient is of uncertain clinical significance.  Excessive beta activity could be
secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
History: 56 year-old woman with history of seizures for the last 5-6 years as associated with alcohol use. No seizure since 8/2013. Patient has history of SDH
Medications: Serax, Keppra
EEG Type: Awake & asleep
Technique: International 10-20 System: standard 21 electrodes with T11T2 electrodes, hyperventilation, photic

Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. Symmetric 5-15uV. 18-25Hz activity is present. maximal over bilateral frontal regions. No normal sleep architecture is present.

No focal slowing is present. No epileptiform discharges are present.

Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse symmetric background slowing. Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.


Summary of Findings:
No stage 2 sleep
No epileptiform discharges

report:
History:	69 year old man with focal seizures. Medications:	Keppra, Dilantin, Phenobarbital Sedation:
EEG Type:	Continuous (inpt, video), 24 hrs
Technique:		International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy
Continuous bedside video-EEG  monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for 24 hours from 08/26/2015 till 08/27/2015.    Nursing­ initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior.  Ongoing raw EEG data was reviewed at least twice daily by the EEG team for detection of seizures and changes in EEG patterns.   All automatically detected events were reviewed in detail by the attending neurologist.
# Push button events
Description of pushbutton events
Description:
There is no clear PDR or AP gradient while the patient is awake. The awake background consists of a mixture of a low amplitude beta>theta activity with theta activity most pronounced over the left frontotemporal region. As the recording progresses, the background becomes more attenuated- this corresponds to initiation  of phenobarbital. Additional underriding fast activity is captured over the left anterior quadrant. Diffuse excess beta activity is seen. Continuous high amplitude rhythmic and semi­ rhythmic (PLEDs and quasi-PLEDs) up to 1 Hz sharp waves with aftergoing slow waves emanate from
the left anterior quadrant, most prominent over the F3 lead. Starting at -8:27 AM, intermittent left anterior quadrant seizures appear. They last - 25-60 seconds and have no clinical correlate. They occur at variable frequency throughout the recording, up to multiple times per hour (between 4-5 PM), ie, frank focal status epilepticus. Last clear seizure is captured at -2:07 AM. Electrographically, seizures start with rhythmic left anterior delta- theta activity that rapidly increases in amplitude and rhythmicity, decreases in frequency and spreads throughout the left hemisphere. Periods of brief background discontinuity and sleep-spindle-like waveforms (more visible over the left) are seen during sleep.
Summary of Findings:
Seizure, left anterior, variable frequency , last @2:07 am Status epilepticus , left anterior, between - 4-5 PM
PEDs (periodic epileptiform discharges), left anterior Pseudoperiodic discharges, left anterior
Beta, excessive
Attenuation , due to phenobarbital initiation
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL continuous video -24 hour EEG due to continuous left anterior periodic and semi periodic epileptiform discharges (PLEDs and quasi-PLEDs), left anterior quadrant focal seizures and brief focal status epilepticus, left anterior focal slowing and diffuse slowing . There is a focal structural epileptogenic lesion in the left anterior quadrant.  Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically nonspecific. Breach rhythm is secondary to the skull defect. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
These findings were conveyed to the primary team and medication regimen was adjusted (phenobarbital was added).

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This 40-year-old left-handed woman with asthma, stroke, migraine headache, and seizures.  Patient had recurrent seizures, 1-2 days prior to admission with 2 seizures, and then 3 seizures on the day of admission with 1 hour postictal confusion.  The patient is on the 4th floor.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation was performed.  Photic stimulation was not completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG was somewhat slow and disorganized.  With a posterior dominant rhythm of 7 Hz, intermittent background theta was noted.  As the recording continues, the patient was stimulated and briefly a 9 Hz alpha rhythm emerges.  Hyperventilation was performed with good effort, serving to alert the patient, and a more normal pattern was identified.  Following hyperventilation, the patient drifts off into drowsiness.  There is a bit of irregular slowing in the right hemisphere particularly centrotemporal and centroparietal.
Posts were noted in stage 1 sleep.
Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging bedside record with some impedances greater than 5 kilohms, but abnormal due to paroxysmal slowing and apparent wakefulness in the context of a patient who seemed to be quite drowsy.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were subtle focal features noted only on 1 section in this bedside record.  These findings may be correlated with imaging.  The background slowing is a nonspecific finding, but this paroxysmal pattern can be seen in a postictal pattern or in the context of a toxic or metabolic pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging bedside record with some impedances greater than 5 kilohms, but abnormal due to paroxysmal slowing and apparent wakefulness in the context of a patient who seemed to be quite drowsy.

report:
History:	49 year old woman admitted with right parietal hematoma.
Medications:	Valproic acid
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes, awake,
Description:
There is right to left intrahemispheric asymmetry with slower waveforms over the right.  The
background over the left hemisphere consists of 9.5-10 Hz PDR with preserved AP gradient and
excess polymorphic theta activity.  There is no PDR or AP gradient over the right.  The background
over the right hemisphere consists of polymorphic continuous theta and delta activity, most
pronounced over the temporal region.  Frequent brief (2-5 second) bursts of 100-200uV, 2-4Hz
rhythmic bifrontal slow waves occur throughout the recording, increasing in frequency during
drowsiness.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear
No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, continuous, moderate, right hemispheric, most pronounced over the
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild
No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
FIRDA (frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity)
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 22-minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing and
continuous focal moderate right hemispheric slowing, most pronounced over the temporal region.
Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically nonspecific.
Continuous focal slowing is indicative of a focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology.
FIRDA (frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity) is seen in encephalopathy, increased ICP and
bilateral deep white matter lesions.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not
rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  These findings were conveyed to the primary team.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 22-minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing and
continuous focal moderate right hemispheric slowing, most pronounced over the temporal region

report:
History:	35 year old man with a history of seizures since 1999 after a gun shot wound behind

left year.  Most recent seizure occurred ~ 2 weeks ago.

Medications:	Tegretol, Keppra

Sedation:

EEG Type:	Awake & asleep

Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG

electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic

Description:

Brief waking background is characterized by low voltage Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates

symmetrically with eye opening.  Fast alpha variant is observed.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz

activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows

to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm

attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate

voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.

No focal slowing is present.  Intrusions of polymorphic theta and delta activity are seen during brief

wakefulness.  Similar theta and delta activity is noted during sleep.  No epileptiform discharges are

present.

Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and patient falls asleep.

Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at

multiple flash rates.

Summary of Findings:

Other, intrusions of drowsiness into wakefulness

Sleep, stage 2

No epileptiform discharges

Interpretation:

This is a NORMAL briefly awake and mostly drowsy and asleep 21-minute EEG. This patient

demonstrates hypersomnolence, please correlate clinically.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on

a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation 
This is a NORMAL briefly awake and mostly drowsy and asleep 21-minute EEG. This patient

demonstrates hypersomnolence, please correlate clinically.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on

a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 35-year-old male status post gunshot wound to left retro-orbital region 15 years ago with ultimate development of epilepsy.  This is a repeat 1 hour EEG in search of epileptiform abnormalities.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  A 1-hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient was quite somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the overall EEG is low voltage with generous beta.  Scant alpha rhythm was identified.  In this low voltage record, in hyperventilation and drowsiness, there is a subtle, low voltage infrequent somewhat irregular, left temporal slowing.  In addition, there are rare bursts of focal slowing from the right temporal region noted following hyperventilation.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta, followed by vertex waves and K complexes, as well as spindles.
Notable findings in this record include a brief burst of slower, rhythmic 3 hertz delta activity from the left temporal region.  This is followed by a single, low voltage, left temporal sharp waves.  These findings are best visualized in an average reference.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.  Hyperventilation as described above.  Heart rate slightly irregular 90bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to:
A single, well demarcated burst of rhythmic left temporal slowing.
Very infrequent bursts of shifting lower voltage, temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Only, a single sharp wave was noted in this record.  In this particular clinical context, however, the single sharp waves may be considered as part of this patient's pathology.  No well-defined, higher amplitude spike and slow wave and sharp and slow wave complexes were noted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to A single, well demarcated burst of rhythmic left temporal slowing. Very infrequent bursts of shifting lower voltage, temporal slowing.

report:
History:	22 year old woman with new onset seizures.
Medications:	None
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10-10.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions. Brief (1-3 seconds) bursts of diffuse moderate-to-high amplitude 6 Hz theta activity are noted during wakefulness. Their frequency and duration increase in drowsiness and they are no longer present during sleep. During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent. During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present. No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and produces no effect. Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates. An episode of left pinky twitching occurs from ~7 min 45 sec till ~ 10 min 15 sec into the recording. This is not associated with an abnormal activity on the scalp EEG.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Other, episode of left pinky twitching without EEG correlate Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 27 minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. Patient rapidly transitions into sleep. Bursts of diffuse theta activity likely represent intrusions of sleep architecture into drowsiness. This could be explained by an excessively drowsy patient. An episode of left pinky twitching is captured (it lasts ~ 2 min 30 sec). There is no abnormal activity captured on a scalp EEG. However, only ~ 25% of simple partial seizures are captured on a scalp EEG.
.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a NORMAL 27 minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. Patient rapidly transitions into sleep. Bursts of diffuse theta activity likely represent intrusions of sleep architecture into drowsiness. This could be explained by an excessively drowsy patient. An episode of left pinky twitching is captured (it lasts ~ 2 min 30 sec). There is no abnormal activity captured on a scalp EEG. However, only ~ 25% of simple partial seizures are captured on a scalp EEG

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is an 81-year-old woman for EEG monitoring for possible hypothermic protocol.  Temp 34.6.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol, fentanyl, and midazolam.
INTRODUCTION:  Intraoperative monitoring was recorded from 7:21 a.m. until 9:48 a.m.  This recording was performed in anticipation of possible utilization of hypothermic protocol.  Physician was available for remote review and physician remote review was employed for 50 minutes, from 8:10 until 9 a.m.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG begins with the patient somewhat sedated.  The patient is awake with a posterior dominant rhythm with a generous beta, theta, and occasional shifting slowing.  An 8.3 Hz alpha rhythm was noted.  At 7:42, anesthetic medications are employed and EEG demonstrates an increase in background slowing.
Anesthetic medications are adjusted from 9 a.m. and EEG recording is intermittently pause for Bovie and other maneuvers.  The EEG demonstrates an intermittently discontinuous pattern.
Shortly after 9 a.m., the surgeon changes the operative strategy and EEG monitoring was not required.  The team signed out of the OR at 9:48, at which point there was a discontinuous pattern, compatible with anesthesia.
HEART RATE 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Limited intraoperative monitoring demonstrated symmetric, relatively normal awake baseline and the appearance of a burst suppression pattern with the utilization of anesthesia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Limited intraoperative monitoring demonstrated symmetric, relatively normal awake baseline and the appearance of a burst suppression pattern with the utilization of anesthesia

report:

MEDICATIONS:  Phenytoin, Zofran
INTRODUCTION:  1 hour Prolonged outpatient EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were deferred.  This is an awake and extended sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background theta with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTs noted in sleep.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.

report:

MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, topiramate, levetiracetam, Solu-Medrol, others.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 25-year-old right-handed woman with adult-onset recurrent seizures with previous normal EEG, events without aura, loss of consciousness, and associated injury.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  Stage 2 sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTs.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background as well as a focal response.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Notable findings in this EEG include rhythmic left temporal theta which waxes and wanes, increasing in drowsiness.  In addition, occasional left anterior temporal sharp waves with after-going slow waves, medium to high amplitude were noted in wakefulness around the time of photic stimulation.  Photic stimulation also seems to accentuate the rhythmic slowing and sharp waves.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Rhythmic left temporal slowing.
Left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These are new findings for this individual and support a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Rhythmic left temporal slowing. Left temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 41-year-old woman with new-onset spells with nocturnal tongue biting, nocturnal incontinence, and daytime staring spells.
MEDICATIONS:  Unknown.
INTRODUCTION:  Routine, 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This was a technically satisfactory EEG capturing wakefulness and drowsiness.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in theta.  Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicited symmetric, bilateral driving.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration, a followup study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 23-year-old woman with bipolar disease, limited education, 5 weeks postpartum.  Mother reports abrupt onset of head bobbing, arm shaking, and episodes with loss of consciousness for the past 48 hours.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  A 30-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient had limited communication skills and a translator was used during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is awake with a 12 hertz alpha rhythm generous, low voltage, frontal central beta.
In wakefulness and early drowsiness, brief bursts of high amplitude, generalized spike and wave activity were noted.  Some of these seem to begin with a burst of fast activity in the occipital regions with a 3-5 Hz spike and wave complex.  The complexes vary in the frequency, many of them are 3 hertz with a polyspike, but the later spikes in the complex are always consistently slower.  Generally, these are frontally predominant spike and wave complexes and those that occur out of drowsiness do not have this beta buzz prior to the spikes.  The patient is noted to have a subtle head bob and sometimes some movement of her legs during the bursts.  She seems to have clinical symptoms with bursts that are 2 seconds in duration.  The bursts are present in wakefulness and early drowsiness.  Hyperventilation may have increase the duration of the spike and wave and polyspike and wave complexes.  In addition, during hyperventilation, there may be a little bit more fast activity.  The patient was otherwise able to answer questions, before and after the discharges.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response.  Spike and wave activity was noted with a 21 hertz discharge, but was not prolonged relative to other sections of the record.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave activity with bursts of 3-5 Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The EEG pattern described above is most compatible with generalized mechanism for epilepsy.  The patient's behavior of the head bobbing and sometimes the leg movements are not outside of normal for a absence seizure.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave activity with bursts of 3-5 Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity.

report:
History:	23 year old female with episodes of left eye twitching and post ictal headaches.
Medications:	Keppra, ambien to sleep, ritalin for bipolar
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes, awake,
drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 12Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  There is diffuse excess beta.  During drowsiness, the background slows to
central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate
voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
Sleep, stage 2
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could
be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges
on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could
be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 41-year-old gentleman status post acoustic neuroma resection, June 2014.  The patient treated briefly with Keppra, which was resumed after the patient had a recurrent seizure.  Episode in 2015 with seizure characterized by impairment of awareness.  Chronic left headache, left facial twitching.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Klonopin.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was deferred, but photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is an 8.5-9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  A clear breach rhythm was noted from the left with higher amplitude alpha on the left in comparison to the right.  There is prominent muscle artifact noted in the left frontal temporal electrodes with fast activity of approximately 35 hertz.  As the patient becomes drowsy, focal slowing is identified in the left mid temporal region.  The patient does not sustain deeper stages of sleep.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving response.  Hyperventilation was deferred.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to
intermittent focal slowing noted in drowsiness from the left temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The breach rhythm identified above is an anticipated finding following craniotomy and is congruent with the previous left cranial surgery.  There is prominent 35 hertz fast activity noted in the left temporalis/ scalp over congruent with the patient's clinical symptoms and he has complaint of an ongoing muscle spasm in that area.  (Muscle artifact)
This is the 3rd EEG for this individual.  It demonstrates significant improvement in comparison to the immediate postoperative study in June 2014.
No epileptiform features were noted in the last two EEGS.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to
intermittent focal slowing noted in drowsiness from the left temporal region.

report:
History:	53 year old woman with new onset episodes of right arm shaking.


Medications: Sedation: EEG Type: Technique:


None


Routine, awake & drowsy
International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation




Description:
The background consists of low-to-moderate amplitude polymorphic 8 Hz theta activity and weak AP gradient.  Excess diffuse admixed 50-75 uV, 5-7Hz activity is present throughout the recording and increases during drowsiness.   During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely.

Intermittent polymorphic theta and delta activity is present in the left frontocentral region during wakefulness, increasing during drowsiness.   Frequent left frontocentral sharp waves are present.  Maximal scalp negativity occurs over F3/C3 electrodes.   Frequency of sharp waves increases during drowsiness.  They are often periodic and semi periodic (PLEDs and quasi-PLEDs), 1-2 Hz,  occurring in brief runs (up to 20 seconds long).  Two seizures are captured at - 7 min 17 seconds and 22 min 42 seconds into the recording.  They last - 12 seconds and 43 seconds, respectively.  The first seizure does not an obvious clinical correlate.  The second seizure is associated with rhythmic right hand shaking.

Electrographically seizure #1 is characterized by rhythmic left frontocentral sharp waves that rapidly increase in frequency (up to 2 Hz) and amplitude.  Onset of seizure #2 is obscured by EMG.  There is appearance of rhythmic F3/C3 sharp waves that gradually increase in frequency (up to 4 Hz) and amplitude and speed to Cz electrode.  Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces diffuse symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation is not performed.

Summary of Findings:
Seizure, two, left, frontocentral: sz #2 associated with right arm shaking
PLEDs {periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges), occasional, left, frontocentral; also quasi-PLE Focal slowing, polymorphic, intermittent, moderate, left, frontocentral

Interpretation:
This is a very abnormal awake and drowsy 24 minute EEG due to left frontocentral focal slowing, left frontocentral semi-periodic and periodic epileptiform discharges and 2 brief focal left frontocentral seizures. These findings are indicative of a structural lesion and an epileptogenic focus in the left frontocentral region.  These findings were conveyed to the primary team at the time of the record review. Patient will be placed on continuous EEG monitoring.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a very abnormal awake and drowsy 24 minute EEG due to left frontocentral focal slowing, left frontocentral semi-periodic and periodic epileptiform discharges and 2 brief focal left frontocentral seizures. These findings are indicative of a structural lesion and an epileptogenic focus in the left frontocentral region.  These findings were conveyed to the primary team at the time of the record review. Patient will be placed on continuous EEG monitoring

report:
History:	53 year old woman with a history of seizures.
Medications:	Lorazepam, Dilantin
Sedation:
EEG Type: Continuous (inpt, video}, 24 hrs, portable
Technique: International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for 24 hours from 8/28/2014 till 8/29/2014.  Nursing-initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior. Ongoing raw EEG data was reviewed at least twice daily by the EEG team for detection of seizures and changes in EEG patterns.  All automatically detected events were reviewed in detail by the attending neurologist.
# Push button events
Description of pushbutton events
Description:
There is right-to-left intrahemispheric asymmetry with slower waveforms over the left. The background over the right consists of polymorphic 8 Hz theta posteriorly, weak AP gradient and excess polymorphic theta activity.  There is no PDR or AP gradient over the left. The background over the left consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta activity with most pronounced delta over the left posterior quadrant.  Excess beta activity appears in the second half of the recording. Sleep spindles are captured. They are better formed over the right.
Continuous variable amplitude complex sharp waves are captured over left parietal region. These discharges frequently occur in brief 1-5 seconds (up to 10 sec} non-evolving runs. No clear electrographic seizures are captured.
Summary of Findings:
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild-to-moderate: more so by the end of the recording Beta, excessive, in 2nd half of the recording
Sharp waves, continuous, left parietal, variable amplitude; frequently occurring in 1-5 sec runs No electrographic seizures
Focal slowing, polymorphic, moderate
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL 24 hour continuous video EEG due to (1) mild-to-moderate diffuse slowing; (2) focal moderate left hemispheric slowing (especially over the left parietal region} and continuous left parietal epileptiform discharges. There is a highly irritative epileptogenic likely structural focus in the left parietal region. Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically nonspecific, but in this case is at least partially related to the effect of CNS-active medications due to increase in the degree of slowing as the recording progresses.  No clear clinical or electrographic
seizures are present. These findings were conveyed to the consult team.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL 24 hour continuous video EEG due to (1) mild-to-moderate diffuse slowing; (2) focal moderate left hemispheric slowing (especially over the left parietal region} and continuous left parietal epileptiform discharges. There is a highly irritative epileptogenic likely structural focus in the left parietal region. Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically nonspecific, but in this case is at least partially related to the effect of CNS-active medications due to increase in the degree of slowing as the recording progresses.  No clear clinical or electrographic
seizures are present. These findings were conveyed to the consult team
