report:
History:	38 year old man with extensive psychiatric history, now with episodes concerning for
seizures.
Medications:	HYDROXYZINE,LAMICTAL,HALOPERIDOL,BENZTROPINE,DIPHENHYDRAMINE,
FAMOTIDINE, CLOZAPINE
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9-10 Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Patient remains awake throughout the recording.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce any effect.  HR was 102.  Persistent eye blinking artifact is present throughout
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 27-minute awake-only EEG.   No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage
2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. There is a persistent blink artifact throughout the recording, so subtle
anterior slowing might have been missed.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 27-minute awake-only EEG.   No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage
2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information. There is a persistent blink artifact throughout the recording, so subtle
anterior slowing might have been missed

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 74-year-old male admitted to the Medicine service recently for episode of loss of consciousness with postictal confusion, cardiac pathology.
MEDICATIONS:  Lisinopril, Requip, metoprolol, aspirin, Mevacor, Plavix, others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a followup EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness was characterized by slow rolling eye movements.
Notable in this record, hyperventilation seems to elicit a somewhat asymmetric hyperventilation response with drop out of faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right and a bit of slowing on the left, although there is some movement artifact.  In addition, in drowsiness, the alpha rhythm drops out on the left a little earlier than the right.
Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
Heart rate irregular, 60-80 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing noted on the left, seen in hyperventilation and in the transition to drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are some technical limitations to this record, but the left focal features appear to be genuine.  The irregular heart rate may be a new finding and the patient's outpatient physician will be contacted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG due to Focal slowing noted on the left, seen in hyperventilation and in the transition to drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 30-year-old woman who had an abrupt, generalized tonic-clonic seizure, falling forward with scalp laceration 4 days ago.  No prior history of epilepsy or epilepsy risk factors, but for the last 6 weeks has been having intermittent myoclonus throughout the day.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is a technically acceptable 20-minute EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Tramadol.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the record producing bursts of rhythmic theta.  There is a single, notched, frontal generalized burst noted in the 1st 2 minutes of hyperventilation, but there are no definitive spike and wave complexes noted in hyperventilation.  As the patient became drowsy following hyperventilation, there is an increase in frontal theta.  The patient waxes and wanes in and out of a drowsy state.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
HEART RATE 72 BPM.
There were some shifting asymmetries noted in the hyperventilation response as well.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Although, there is a prominent hyperventilation response with some bursts of slowing, there is 1 suspicious burst, but no definitive spike and wave complexes.  Additional recording may be of value in search of definitive epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within the limits of normal.

report:
MEDICATIONS:  VPA, LEV, PHT
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 32-year-old woman, transferred from outside hospital with repetitive seizures, head turning and persistent left-sided weakness.
INTRODUCTION:  Routine 20 minutes digital EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is primarily unawake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background includes a symmetric reactive 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness includes an increase in background slowing. Deeper stages of sleep were not sustained.
Hyperventilation:  elicits a small amount of theta
Photic stimulation:  vigorous bilateral driving
Heart rate:  90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep and brief drowsiness.
Generous beta
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This individual with acute neurological symptoms, this is the baseline for continuous video EEG monitoring. Of note, this is similar (normal) to a one hour EEG performed on May 28, 2015
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep and brief drowsiness. Generous beta

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 67-year-old woman with advanced dementia, failure to thrive, prior refusal to eat, cervical myelopathy, status post fusion, admitted with recurrent seizures characterized by twitching of the mouth and right hand.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenytoin, Vimpat, benzodiazepines, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The recording began several hours after the patient has been treated for recurrent focal seizures with little in the way of a clear change in mental status.
 04/07/2015 to 04/08/2015
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  During the early hours of the record, the background EEG is diffusely slow.  There are intermittent rhythmic bursts of theta noted from the left temporal region, but these do not have clear build up and are not associated with clear change in the patient's level of consciousness.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, the EEG is markedly slow and featureless.
In this section of the record, no clinical seizures were recorded.  Practice push buttons were noted.  The patient had an episode of vocalization without clear clinical correlate.
Heart rate:  90 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Day #1, April 7th to 8th:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for:
A markedly slow pattern.
Some bursts of rhythmic slowing noted in the initial sections of the record without clinical change.
Markedly slow background.
04/08/2015 to 04/09/2015
MEDICATIONS: Phenytoin, Vimpat, others.
INTRODUCTION:  During this section of the record, the patient was increasingly arousable and interactive, although essentially nonverbal.  No clinical seizures were noted.
Background:  The overall background is markedly slow, lacking the typical morphologies of wakefulness or sleep for this adult.  Intermittent more rhythmic theta was noted from the left temporal region, but not in sustained bursts. Additional recording on the morning of April 9th demonstrate a patient, who is more awake.  The background EEG remained markedly slow, heart rate 90 bpm.
Epileptiform activity: None
Clinical seizures none.
Electrographic seizures none.
Sleep record:  Markedly slow pattern with at times, rhythmic theta.
Heart rate:  90 bpm.
Impression:  This 2 day, continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for:
Markedly slow background.
Relatively featureless pattern, lacking in a normal wave forms expected in wakefulness and sleep for an adult of this age.
Bursts of rhythmic theta noted from the left temporal region, most remarkable on the 7th, seen much on the 8th and not present on the 9th.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In this individual with recurrent seizures on the morning of the 7th, this EEG shows resolution of a recurrent seizure pattern for this patient with a clinical diagnosis of focal motor status epilepticus.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Day #1, April 7th to 8th:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for A markedly slow pattern. Some bursts of rhythmic slowing noted in the initial sections of the record without clinical change. Markedly slow background. 04/08/2015 to 04/09/2015
MEDICATIONS: Phenytoin, Vimpat, others. INTRODUCTION:  During this section of the record, the patient was increasingly arousable and interactive, although essentially nonverbal.  No clinical seizures were noted. Background:  The overall background is markedly slow, lacking the typical morphologies of wakefulness or sleep for this adult.  Intermittent more rhythmic theta was noted from the left temporal region, but not in sustained bursts. Additional recording on the morning of April 9th demonstrate a patient, who is more awake.  The background EEG remained markedly slow, heart rate 90 bpm. Epileptiform activity: None
Clinical seizures none. Electrographic seizures none. Sleep record:  Markedly slow pattern with at times, rhythmic theta. Heart rate:  90 bpm. Impression:  This 2 day, continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for Markedly slow background. Relatively featureless pattern, lacking in a normal wave forms expected in wakefulness and sleep for an adult of this age. Bursts of rhythmic theta noted from the left temporal region, most remarkable on the 7th, seen much on the 8th and not present on the 9th.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 45-year-old male with epilepsy, recurrent seizures, and significant postictal agitation.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is postictal, agitated, and had difficulty cooperating.  Impedances were all under 5 kilohms because of this.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG includes generous muscle and generous beta.  There is a glimpse of a 12 Hz alpha rhythm, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is also some lower voltage rhythmic frontal delta noted in wakefulness.  At the very final few minutes of the EEG, the patient starts to drift off to sleep with a lower voltage beta pattern.  In this technically challenging EEG, there is a slight beta asymmetry with a bit more beta noted on the left, relative to the right.
Heart rate 120 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is technically challenging, but abnormal EEG due to:
Excess beta.
Likely some frontal delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Given the limitations of this EEG, focal features may be overlooked and the beta asymmetry is of unclear significance.  To more completely characterize this patient's EEG, a followup study when he is more cooperative is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is technically challenging, but abnormal EEG due to Excess beta. Likely some frontal delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 45-year-old right-handed male with epilepsy, recent hospitalization for seizure with agitation  patient not able to provide additional history.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenytoin.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a very tense patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there was a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness was characterized by attenuation of alpha rhythm with slow rolling eye movements.  In drowsiness, the rhythmic theta was slightly asymmetric, slightly more prominent on the right.  Unfortunately, sleep was not sustained.
Hyperventilation produced a small amount of slowing in the frontal regions without definitive asymmetry.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is at the limits of normal in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Limited sleep was identified, but there is a suggestion of some focal slowing on the right in the transition to sleep. This is the second EEG without epileptiform activity.  Consideration for a more prolonged study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is at the limits of normal in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 45-year-old male with epilepsy and recent hospitalization for recurrent seizures.  Patient is persistently agitated during prior attempts to record EEGs.  Currently, seizure-free.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenytoin, BuSpar, bupropion, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 40-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This is a technically acceptable EEG capturing wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Drowsiness includes attenuation of the alpha rhythm with POSTS.  In stage 2 sleep, vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS were noted.
Hyperventilation produces muscle artifact.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Of note in this record, there is a single, well-defined right temporal sharp wave noted just following the vertex wave and a single, more subtle discharge also noted in stage 2 sleep.  The primary discharge noted seems to occur after an arousal with eye movement in stage 2 sleep.
Heart rate 96 b.p.m.
IMPRESSION:  A 40-minute technically satisfactory EEG, but abnormal due to
rare, right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal slowing was seen in this technically acceptable EEG.  There is one well-defined sharp wave with another more subtle discharge, hence the sharp wave is considered significant, albeit quite rare.  This is the third EEG for this patient but the first has identified any sharp waves whatsoever.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  A 40-minute technically satisfactory EEG, but abnormal due to
rare, right temporal sharp waves.

report:

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of 9.5 Hz, with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness was characterized by rhythmic central theta.  Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved and the patient transitioned in and out of wakefulness and sleep. Hyperventilation was performed with good effort and did not significantly activate the record.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate 60 bpm.

report:

Excess theta.
Mild disorganization.

IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Very mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to,
Excess theta. Mild disorganization.

report:
History:	 69 year old woman undergoing left CEA.

INCISION;   5:50PM
HEPARIN: 5000 UNITS  6:47PM +1000 7:48PM +1000 HEPARIN 8:50PM
CLAMP:  6:55PM    SHUNT 6:59PM
RECLAMP 8:47PM
REMOVE SHUNT:   8:50PM
UNCLAMP: 8:54PM
Medications:	VERSED, FENTANYL, ETOMIDATE, ROCURONIUM, SEVOFLURANE, ESMOLOL,
PHENYLEPHRINE
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Extended, >60 min
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, comatose
Description:
Patient is sedated as the recording opens.  The background is symmetrical and consists of a mixture
of polymorphic frequencies (delta, theta, alpha and beta).  Occasionally the background becomes
discontinuous or frankly burst-suppressed.  These changes are related to adjustments in anesthesia.
Left internal carotid artery is clamped at 6:55 pm and left common carotid artery is clamped ~ 25-
30 seconds later.  Within ~ 15-20 seconds of clamping the left common carotid artery, diffuse
change is seen.  It is more pronounced over the left.  This change is characterized by voltage
attenuation as well as abrupt disappearance of fast frequencies.  The attending surgeon is notified
of these changes immediately and shunt placement takes place.  Simultaneously, there is increase
in the dose of  sevoflurane and prominent diffuse delta activity appears as a result.  The primary
team is informed of these changes.  EEG returns to the pre-clamp baseline b ~ 7:06 PM.  Left
carotid artery is re-clamped at ~ 8:48 PM and EEG changes within ~ 5 seconds.  This change is
characterized by diffuse (left>right) voltage attenuation and dominance of delta activity.  EEG
change persists until ~ 8;55 PM when left internal and common carotid arteries are unclamped.
EEG gradually returns to the pre-clamp baseline.
Summary of Findings:
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL ~4 hour continuous intraoperative EEG due to global (left>right) changes
that were seen after clamp was applied to the left common and internal carotid arteries. However,
by the end of the recording, EEG appeared symmetrical and at pre-clamp baseline.  Total time of
the direct EEG monitoring by the EEG attending: ~ 2 hours.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL ~4 hour continuous intraoperative EEG due to global (left>right) changes
that were seen after clamp was applied to the left common and internal carotid arteries. However,
by the end of the recording, EEG appeared symmetrical and at pre-clamp baseline.  Total time of
the direct EEG monitoring by the EEG attending: ~ 2 hours

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 22-year-old male with single seizure in January, perhaps reactive.  Patient subsequently received tramadol for a fracture and had a tonic-clonic seizure.  The patient was started on carbamazepine and since then, complains of feeling spacey.
INTRODUCTION:  One-hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient has received levetiracetam 1000 mg during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the background EEG is diffusely slow with an 8.7 Hz alpha rhythm, but with excess beta and bursts of theta.  Bursts of frontally predominant spike and wave activity are noted.  In addition, isolated right or left frontal spike and wave discharges are noted.  Some of these demonstrate a prominence in the right hemisphere.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the record and clearly accentuates frontally predominant spike and wave activity.  The spike and wave activity ranges from 3 to 5 hertz in frequency.   Discharges are not sustained with most spike and wave complexes either isolated or occurring in bursts, less than 1.5 seconds duration.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep.  This spike and wave discharges did not seem to be augmented by the photic stimulation, but as the patient transitions to sleep, there was a higher amplitude, frontally predominant slowing with a bit more slow spike and wave activity.  Levetiracetam was given at approximately 12 p.m. and the EEG was recorded until 12:41.  Following the levetiracetam, by 12:30, there did appear to be a decrease in the spike and wave activity.  The paroxysmal slowing was a little less remarkable and while the EEG remained abnormal with excess theta, the overall pattern was improving.  The alpha rhythm was at 8.3 hertz at conclusion.
Heart rate, slightly irregular at 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Initially markedly abnormal background with excess slowing and disorganized pattern, improving towards the close of the record.
Frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity.
Focal spike and slow wave activity with a predominance further on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG may represent a focal or a secondary generalized mechanism for epilepsy.  There was a small degree of irregularity in the heart rate noted in the final pages of the EEG, which may be evaluated by different mechanisms.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Initially markedly abnormal background with excess slowing and disorganized pattern, improving towards the close of the record. Frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity. Focal spike and slow wave activity with a predominance further on the right.

report:
History: 59 year old woman with a reported first convulsion several days ago.
Medications:	Ativan, Ambien, Zoloft
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
The posterior dominant rhythm consists of 10.5-11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eye
opening.  There is an expected AP gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.
Diffuse excess beta activity is captured.  Symmetrical sleep architecture consisting of vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes is captured in the second half of the recording.
Multiple events concerning for focal electrographic seizures are captured in the first half of the
recording.  Clinically, patient has not complaints and able to answer questions correctly, including
able to count during these events.  They last ~ 35-55 seconds.  The onset is not clearly lateralized
for the majority of the events.  They start with P3/P4 broad moderate amplitude sharp waves that
gradually increase in frequency up to 6 Hz and spread to the left posterior temporal region
(example ~12:17 PM).  Some events start with ~ 4 Hz medium amplitude rhythmic right parietal
activity that gradually spreads to the left parietal and left temporal regions (example ~12:35:50 pm).
After hyperventilation, brief bursts (<10 sec) of non-evolving shifting bilateral
posterior 5-6 Hz rhythmic moderate amplitude delta activity are captured.  Once P3 and P4 leads
are exchanged at ~12:46:55 PM, the above activity is no longer present.  A single clear right

report:
History:	28 year old woman with a history of seizures.  Seizures stopped ~ 8 years ago and
patient stopped her AEDs.  Seizures now recurred: she has experienced ~3 seizures
in the last 3 weeks.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9.5-10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow
waves appear diffusely.
No focal slowing is present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at
multiple lash rates.  There is frequent eye flutter artifact.
Summary of Findings:
No stage 2 sleep
Artifact, other, eye flutter
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information. There is frequent eye flutter artifact, so subtle anterior
abnormalities might have been missed.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does
not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information. There is frequent eye flutter artifact, so subtle anterior
abnormalities might have been missed.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does
not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 61-year-old male with diabetes, hepatitis C, previously evaluated for verbal unresponsiveness.  The patient now transferred from a facility for an episode with lip smacking, unresponsiveness, stiffness followed by confusion.  This was considered a seizure.
MEDICATION:  Ativan
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  Hyperventilation was deferred.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 8 Hz alpha rhythm.  Stage 2 sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
Heart rate: 96 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  EEG might mildly abnormal due to:
Mild slowing of the alpha rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the second EEG for this individual.  Neither study identified epileptiform activity.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a followup study may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG might mildly abnormal due to Mild slowing of the alpha rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 22-year-old male, transferred from prison to an outside hospital with multiple recurrent seizures. History of childhood epilepsy, asthma, schizophrenia, no known structural abnormalities on MRI.
MEDICATIONS:   Depakote, Keppra, Ativan, Celexa.
INTRODUCTION: A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient was relatively somnolent. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The EEG demonstrates a diffusely slow pattern with rhythmic theta and delta.  Spontaneous eye opening and movements are noted, as is some chewing artifact.  In this diffusely slow record, there is some bursts of shifting slowing and subtle asymmetry characterized by somewhat lower voltage pattern on the right with a bit more arrhythmic delta activity and a bit more theta on the left. Stimulation of the patient produces a bit more theta as well as eye opening.
Heart rate 80 bpm.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified. Overall background described above is typical of a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy, notable for this individual elevated serum ammonia. If additional information is needed, either a repeat study or a long-term EEG monitoring may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. Shifting slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 22-year-old with a history of lupus and schizophrenia.  The patient with difficult to control hallucinosis, admitted on 09/03/2015, after excessive ingestion of Haldol with dystonic reaction.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a low voltage record with 9 hertz, symmetric reactive alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta and attenuation of the alpha.  Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTs.
Photic stimulation elicits:  Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep and produced minimal driving.
Hyperventilation elicits:  Hyperventilation did not activate the record.
Heart rate:  100 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were seen.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  Of note, this EEG is markedly improved compared to previous study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:
History:	30 year old woman with new onset of events concerning for seizures.
Medications:	Trileptal in am only and then stopped
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Continuous (inpt, video), 24 hrs
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for ~24 hours from 11/2/2015 till 11/3/2015.   Nursing-
initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior. Ongoing raw EEG data was reviewed
at least twice daily by the EEG team for detection of seizures and changes in EEG patterns.   All
automatically detected events were reviewed in detail by the attending neurologist.
# Push button events
Description of pushbutton events
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is present.  During drowsiness, the background
slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate
voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.  Two typical events are
captured early in the recording (~11:47 AM and 12:07 PM).  They are characterized by decreased
responsiveness, eye closure, no recollection of the event, not following commands and being
emotional at the end of the event.  They last several minutes. The background remains normal
throughout the events and following the events.
Summary of Findings:
Event, two, no EEG correlate
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL ~24-hour continuous video EEG. Two events characterized by decreased
responsiveness, not answering commands and post-event emotional liability have no abnormal
EEG correlate.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL ~24-hour continuous video EEG. Two events characterized by decreased
responsiveness, not answering commands and post-event emotional liability have no abnormal
EEG correlate

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old male with 20-year history of epilepsy.  Tonic-clonic seizures often when the patient is going to sleep with tongue biting and incontinence.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol and Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and briefly drowsy record.  It is technically acceptable with most impedances below 5 kilohms with the exception of T1-T2.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a symmetric reactive 50 microvolt, 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart Rate:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness.

	No stage 2 sleep

dysfunction.  No epileptiform discharges are present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If 
clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information.
